<FIRST>u i AM-Gulf-Hostages     08-02 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gulf-Hostages,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violence Condemned, Calls for U.S. Restraint</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia on Wednesday denounced both
the Israeli kidnapping of a Shiite Moslem cleric and the killing of
U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins.
   The official Saudi press agency quoted ``a responsible source''
as saying Riyadh ``always condemns and denounces terrorist acts of
all forms and of whatever methods ... These are despicable, inhuman
acts.''
   Arab media criticized Israel for abducting Sheik Abdul Karim
Obeid from south Lebanon Friday and urged the United States to show
restraint amid reports of U.S. fleet movements in the Mediterranean.
   The Dubai-based Al-Bayan wrote in an editorial: ``Israel has
flung the doors of hell wide open.''
   ``What is the objective behind the Israeli act which can only be
classified as organized state terrorism?'' asked Abu Dhabi's
state-run Al-Ittihad daily.
   The hard-line newspaper Al-Khaleej, in neighboring Sharjah
emirate, said ``the Zionist terrorist operation in south Lebanon
and its repercussions must be attributed to U.S. policy in the
region and the full and unconditional U.S. bias toward Israel.''
   The Kuwait newspaper Al-Rai Al-Aam cautioned the United States
against a military response to Higgins' purported hanging.
   ``The United States does not possess many effective means for a
speedy revenge of the hanging of a Marine colonel by a group
operating in a country with usurped sovereignty such as Lebanon.
   ``An effective military action is impossible in a country
overburdened with rocket launchers, artillery, tanks, bombs,
booby-trapped cars and suicide squads, which could be mobilized in
any reaction to an American retaliatory strike,'' it wrote.
   Oman's leading Al-Watan newspaper said ``blame should be pinned
on Israel as it is the instrument of violence in the region.''
   Al-Watan and other Persian Gulf newspapers, urged self-restraint
in the crisis.
   The newspapers noted that an Arab League committee announced an
impasse in efforts to end Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   The Qatar newspaper Al-Raya said that Israel could exploit the
situation ``to direct a major blow against Lebanon'' that could
lead to its ``partition into small states after
internationalization of its crisis.''
   Syria voiced ``surprise and outrage'' at claims of Higgins'
death but blamed Israel for abducting Obeid and refusing to free
him. Israel offered to exchange Obeid and Shiite Moslem prisoners
it holds for three Israeli servicemen and all 16 foreign hostages
in Lebanon.
   Egypt, a U.S. ally and at peace with Israel, urged ``all parties
concerned, whether regional or international, to exercise extreme
self-restraint.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
