<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     08-02 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Cheers,' `13 East' Lead NBC to 58th Consecutive Ratings Win</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC might have flopped with its nurse drama
``Nightingales,'' but its summer nurse comedy ``13 East'' finished
in the Top 10, helping the network win another Nielsen ratings
derby victory.
   For the week ended July 30, NBC's ``Cheers'' landed in first
place for the fourth time in five weeks, narrowly topping ABC's
``Roseanne.'' ``Cheers'' had a rating of 17.5, only one-tenth of a
point ahead of ``Roseanne.''
   Last week they tied for first place at 17.4.
   NBC easily won the week for its 58th straight victory in the
A.C. Nielsen Co. survey. The only surprise in the Top 10 was the
appearance of lightly regarded ``13 East,'' which finished 10th.
   Other than CBS' ``60 Minutes'' and ``Murder, She Wrote,'' all
the shows in the Top 10 were comedies.
   The ratings are certainly proof of the resurgence of the
situation comedy, which was all but written off a few years ago.
   Prime-time soap operas like ``Dallas'' and ``Dynasty'' dominated
the ratings until the appearance of ``The Cosby Show'' in 1984. In
the 1983-84 season the only comedy in the Top 10 was CBS' ``Kate &amp;
Allie.''
   Comedy also dominated the second 10 highest-rated shows this
past week with seven entries.
   Here are the Top 10: NBC's ``Cheers,'' ABC's ``Roseanne,'' NBC's
``The Cosby Show,'' NBC's ``A Different World,'' NBC's ``Dear
John,'' NBC's ``The Golden Girls'' and CBS' ``60 Minutes'' tied,
CBS ``Murder, She Wrote,'' ABC's ``The Wonder Years'' and NBC's
``13 East.''
   Fox Broadcasting continued its summer surge in the ratings.
``Married ... With Children'' was in 29th place, ``America's Most
Wanted'' was tied for 34th and ``Totally Hidden Video'' was tied
for 39th place.
   NBC was first with an average of 10.8, CBS was second with 8.9
and ABC was third with 8.7. The averages since the fall season
began on Sept. 19 were: NBC 14.8, ABC 11.9 and CBS 11.8.
   The ratings is the percentage of the estimated 90.4 million
homes in the United States with television. The share is the
percentage of sets in use.
   The NBC summer show, ``Knight and Daye,'' did not fare that well
in the ratings. It was in 37th place.
   The lowest-rated show on the three networks was CBS' ``American
Nuclear.'' Here are the bottom five: CBS' ``Tour of Duty,'' NBC's
``Jim Henson,'' ABC's ``Nick and Frankie,'' ABC's
``Trans-Antarctica Expedition'' and CBS' ``American Nuclear.''
   CBS had the highest-rated evening news show. The ratings: CBS
9.0, ABC 8.8 and NBC 8.6.
</TEXT>
