<FIRST>u p AM-Pepper'sSeat 3rdLd-Writethru a0805 08-02 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepper's Seat, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0805,0747</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban-American Wins GOP Nod for Pepper Seat; Dems Head to Runoff</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Democratic runoff, final
results. Picks up below dash.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban-born state Sen. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen romped to
the Republican nomination Tuesday in the race to succeed the late
Rep. Claude Pepper, while a Cuban-born former city commissioner and
a prominent Jewish attorney headed to a Democratic runoff.
   Attorney Gerald Richman claimed momentum as he narrowly led a
seven-candidate field in the ethnically diverse district. Former
Miami city commissioner Rosario Kennedy, also Cuban-born, had been
the front-runner but was criticized for late negative campaigning.
   She ran just behind Richman, who in his stump speech said the
U.S. House slot was ``an American seat.'' Pepper's niece, Jo Ann
Pepper, fell short of the Aug. 15 runoff for the District 18 seat.
   ``It is really incredible,'' said Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, who was
carrying nearly every precinct with 80 percent-plus totals. ``We're
quite humbled and really flabbergasted. We really just hoped for a
victory without a runoff.''
   Elections officials said turnout was best in the Little Havana
precincts. The Aug. 29 special election to fill the seat Pepper had
held for the Democrats since 1962 could result in election of the
first Cuban-American in Congress.
   While the Democrats battle in a runoff campaign, Ms.
Ros-Lehtinen will get help from a fund-raising visit Wednesday by
Vice President Dan Quayle for the state Republican Party and she
will film a new television commercial Thursday. ``We are going to
charge ahead,'' she said. ``We don't let up for one minute.''
   In unofficial returns from all 146 precincts, Ms. Ros-Lehtinen,
36, had 16,555 votes, or 85 percent; fellow Cuban-American Carlos
Perez, 57, had 1,997 votes, or 10 percent; insurance broker David
Fleischer, 54, had 555 votes, 3 percent, and evangelist John
Stembridge, 51, had 456 votes, or 2 percent.
   In the heated Democratic race, Richman, 48, had 5,513 votes, or
28 percent, while Ms. Kennedy, 44, had 5,402 votes, or 27 percent.
Ms. Pepper, 39, had 4,757 votes, or 24 percent.
   Some 1,000 Democratic absentee ballots remained to be counted
Wednesday.
   Professor Marvin Dunn, 48, had 1,625 votes, or 8 percent; and
real estate agent Sonny Wright, 54, had 1,476 votes, or 7 percent.
They are both black.
   Businessman Bernard Anscher, 67, had 662 votes, 3 percent, and
striking Eastern Airlines pilot John Paul Rosser, 38, had 264
votes, or 1 percent. Florida hasn't elected a black congressman
since Reconstruction.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Pepper, a liberal champion of the elderly and poor, drew no
opposition in 1988. He died May 30 at age 88, and his death left
the Republicans with a 10-8 majority in the state's congressional
delegation.
   The district includes the retirement communities of Miami Beach,
predominantly black neighborhoods such as Liberty City, heavily
Cuban neighborhoods and affluent Coral Gables.
   The elections office said the district's 100,198 registered
Democrats comprised 16,028 Hispanics, 32,183 blacks and 51,987
non-Latin whites. The 71,620 registered Republicans comprised
46,738 Hispanics, 23,656 non-Latin whites, and 1,226 blacks.
   But the figures for Hispanics are low, because the office counts
only those who were born in Hispanic nations. Unofficial estimates
that include second-generation Hispanics run to about half of the
registered voters.
   Ms. Lehtinen, an educator and conservative married to U.S.
Attorney Dexter Lehtinen, led candidates in fund-raising with more
than $200,000 reported as of July 20. She avoided joint appearances
with Perez, a businessman and fervent supporter of Ronald Reagan
and Oliver North, the former National Security Council adviser who
endorsed Perez.
   Ms. Kennedy, whose former husband is David Kennedy, an ex-mayor
of Miami and one of her top political advisers, was criticized in
the campaign's final week for negative mailings aimed at Ms. Pepper
and Richman.
   She was endorsed by the AFL-CIO, The Miami Herald and state
Democratic Party chairman Simon Ferro.
   Richman, former Florida Bar Association president, was attacked
in the mailings for representing international arms dealer Sarkis
Soghanalian, indicted on charges of illegally conspiring to smuggle
combat helicopters to Iraq. Richman called Soghanalian a patriot
who has helped U.S. causes.
   Ms. Pepper, portrayed as a naive political novice by the Kennedy
forces, said she learned inside politics and government during her
frequent travels with her uncle. She said 14 years as a federal
probation officer gave her tough views on crime.
</TEXT>
