<DOCNO> AP890802-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0236EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Snub     08-02 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Snub,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Newspaper Chain Ends 40-Year Snub of East Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since East Germany was founded 40
years ago, West Germany's largest publishing chain has snubbed its
socialist sibling by placing quotation marks around every reference
to the state.
   But starting today, Axel Springer newspapers and magazines will
end the practice that has irked authorities in East Berlin,
Springer officials said.
   The quotation marks have cost the publishing empire journalistic
accreditation in the neighboring socialist state and readership
among much of West Germany's left-leaning populace.
   But far from conceding defeat in the ideological battle, the
publishers contend the war against the division of Germany
continues.
   ``The hope for reunification is unshaken,'' Manfred Schell,
editor-in-chief of the conservative daily Die Welt wrote today.
   But, in light of changes in East-West relations, the barriers to
improving the flow of information between the political blocs must
fall, Schell said.
   The giant Springer publishing network includes Europe's
largest-circulation daily, Hamburg-based Bild Zeitung, which sells
nearly 5 million copies daily. It also includes the influential
Berliner Morgenpost and Bonn's Die Welt.
   Despite Springer's broad audience, its journalists have been
denied accreditation to work in East Germany on the grounds that
the company's editorial policies are insulting to the Berlin
government.
   A spokesman for the East German Foreign Ministry said the
government had no immediate comment on Springer's reversal.
   Schell hinted in his editorial that the newspaper considered the
dropped quotation marks a step toward gaining permission to report
from East Germany. Referring to East Germany as ``DDR,'' the German
abbreviation for Deutsche Demokratische Republik, was the protest
of the publishing chain's founder, Axel Springer, who died nearly
four years ago.
   Germany's division after World War II weighed heavily on
Springer, who moved his prospering business from his native Hamburg
to West Berlin in 1967.
   After construction of the Berlin Wall in 1961, he put up a
lighted readerboard to flash news from the West across the barrier.
   Springer also issued political and moral guidelines for the
publications in 1967, and the first and foremost called for the
reunification of Germany.
   From the 1949 founding of East Germany, Springer publications
refused to acknowledge the socialist government and the quotation
marks demonstrated their disdain.
   Die Welt administrative chief Jens Lueddeke said other West
German publications also initially declined to acknowledge East
German statehood, using similar quote marks or skeptical references
to the government.
   But most dropped the practice after West Germany recognized the
east in 1970.
   Springer editors concede now that the quotation marks have now
lost their meaning and in some cases simply confuse readers.
   Circulation of Springer's main dailies has fallen by as much as
10 percent over the past few years, and many attribute the drop to
shifts within the West German populace toward detente with nations
of the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
   ``The number of people who can recall adult life in a unified
Germany is a minority,'' Die Welt editor Schell wrote.
   ``With this step we come to grips with the developments in East
and Central Europe, in particular the reform efforts in Hungary,
Poland and the Soviet Union,'' Schell said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0157EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SleepStudy     08-02 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sleep Study,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Working Women Sleep Less</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Working women sleep about 25 minutes
less per night than their male counterparts, though the average
woman sleeps slightly longer than the average man, researchers said
Tuesday.
   ``Working women really take it in the neck. They sleep less,''
said Daniel Hamermesh, professor of economics at Michigan State
University and one of the authors.
   ``One possible explanation is that a woman who works still has
to maintain a lot of household duties,'' said Jeff Biddle,
assistant professor of economics at the school.
   ``They aren't spending much less time doing those things, and
their husbands aren't sharing chores with them, so the time has to
come from somewhere and often it comes from sleep time.''
   Mothers of children less than 3 years old get less sleep than
the average person, but being parents to children younger than 3
doesn't cut into the amount of sleep fathers get, Hamermesh said.
   The study of the sleep habits of 1,500 people also found that
people who work sleep less than people who don't work and that for
every extra hour worked, a person sleeps 15 minutes less.
   The more a man works, the less sleep he gets, the report said.
   Men who earn a higher wage per hour sleep less than lower-paid
men, but that pattern fails to hold up for women.
   ``One reason may be that women who are already working are
sleeping less already and so the margin is gone,'' he said.
   Hamermesh and Biddle gleaned the findings from reviewing
information gathered in 1975-76 by the University of Michigan
survey research division. In 1980-81, 620 members of the study
group were interviewed again.
   Biddle said the time lapse since the data was collected
shouldn't matter because lifestyles haven't changed significantly
since then.
   ``Lifestyles and attitudes toward money and family are pretty
much the same. Things like household habits are very slow to
change,'' he said.
   Wide variances in the amount of time people sleep were turned up
by the study. Hamermesh said 10 percent reported sleeping less than
6.5 hours a night and 10 percent reported sleeping more than 9
hours.
   ``Sleep is not something biologically fixed. People can
substitute other activities for sleep,'' Hamermesh said.
   ``Although it's true we do need a certain amount of sleep, we do
have some control,'' Biddle said. ``How much time is valued is
going to enter into that decision.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
