<HEAD>Daughter of Hank Williams to Perform With Father's Band</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jett Williams will perform her own music
with songs written by her father, country great Hank Williams, when
she begins touring with his Drifting Cowboys band.
   ``It's meant to be, because a lot of strange things have
happened,'' said Ms. Williams, who recently won a decision by the
Alabama Supreme Court recognizing she had been cut out of her
father's estate. ``I know who I am now. I know that my father
wanted me and that's taken me a whole lifetime.''
   She signed a deal Monday with Buddy Lee Attractions of Nashville
to tour with the two Drifting Cowboys who still perform, fiddler
Jerry Rivers and steel guitarist Don Helms. Tour arrangements were
incomplete.
   Ms. Williams, whose real name is Cathy Deupree Adkinson, was
born in Montgomery five days after Williams' death on Jan. 1, 1953.
Williams and her mother, Bobbie Jett, were not married, and the
child was raised by Williams' mother, Lillian Stone.
   After Mrs. Stone's death the girl was put up for adoption. The
Alabama court decided she should share Williams' songwriting
royalties with Hank Williams Jr.
   Ms. Williams, who is married to Washington attorney Keith
Adkinson, will also perform songs she has written about her own
life, including ``Conceived in Love.''
