<FIRST>r a PM-MistakenIdentity     08-02 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mistaken Identity,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Mistaken For Parole Violator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVER EDGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A case of mistaken identity landed a man
in jail on his wedding day, and it took the word of the reverend
who was to preside at the service to get him out.
   Frank Padilla of Carlstadt said Tuesday he was riding with three
friends on Route 4 about 3:15 a.m. Saturday when police stopped him
at River Edge in northeastern New Jersey because his car had a
broken tail light.
   The officer checked Padilla's driver's license and found it was
expired. The officer then checked to see if Padilla had a record.
   A computer check showed a warrant for a Frank Padilla, who was
convicted in 1981 and 1986 on narcotics charges and was listed as a
parole violator. The computer listed the wanted man's birthday as
Aug. 15, 1962.
   Padilla's expired license showed the same birthday, landing him
in jail.
   He told police they'd made a mistake.
   ``They said, `That's fine, but we need proof,''' he said.
   Padilla, who described himself as a ``Bible-believing
Christian'' and said he taught emotionally disturbed children in
Edgewater, spent about 45 minutes alone in a jail cell. He said he
sang ``songs to the Lord.''
   While police checked his story, Padilla's friends rounded up
character references for him.
   The police finally accepted the word of the Rev. Tom Mahairas,
who was due to officiate at Padilla's wedding later Saturday.
   He was released about 5 a.m. on his own recognizance in lieu of
$350 bail on the suspended license charge, said Lt. Frank Starace
of the River Edge Police Department. A hearing was set for Aug. 22.
   Ten hours after his release, Padilla and Judith Thomas were
married in Hackensack.
   The bridegroom said he bore no malice toward police.
   ``The officers were very nice about the whole thing,'' Padilla
said. ``They were just doing their job.''
</TEXT>
