<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearCleanup     08-02 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Cleanup,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Department Outlines Plan to Clean up Atomic Weapons Plants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Energy Department report on the
government's nuclear weapons program describes a pattern of shoddy
waste management and hazardous conditions with contamination of
ground water or soil at many plants.
   The findings were included in a detailed assessment Tuesday on
what it will take to clean up the nuclear weapons plants after
decades of environmental neglect by plant operators.
   Energy Secretary James Watkins said the first phase of the
cleanup effort will cost $19.5 billion over the next five years
with the overall cleanup likely to take at least 30 years. Overall
cost estimates range from $90 billion to as much as $150 billion.
   The department's report listed numerous cases where shoddy
handling of hazardous waste has contaminated ground water, posing
various degrees of risk to surrounding communities.
   For example, according to the report:
   _At the Oak Ridge Reservation in Tennessee, ``surface and ground
water contamination'' was blamed on abandoned waste storage tanks.
Some public surface water was found to be contaminated and further
``potential health risks exist.''
   _Soil and ground water was found contaminated at the Savannah
River uranium processing plant near Aiken, S.C., where wastes are
buried in unlined pits and lagoons. Some of the contaminated
wastewater has been discharged into streams.
   _Uranium dust has contaminated water at the Idaho National
Engineering Laboratory where spent nuclear fuel is recycled. The
report also warned of an ``immediate risk to employees through
exposure to contaminated drinking water'' and said radiation
exposure ``is a potential health risk'' to nearby property.
   _Ground water also was cited at the Hanford nuclear reservation
in eastern Washington state, where particular concern was noted
because of the facility's proximity to the Columbia River.
   _Among other priorities was reducing ground water contamination
at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory at Livermore, Calif.,
and digging up barrels of liquid chemical waste at the Nevada Test
Site north of Las Vegas.
   The report said ground water contaminants must be reduced at
other federal nuclear facilities including the Welden Springs
nuclear site in Missouri; the Fernald uranium processing plant in
Ohio; the Rocky Flats plutonium processing plant in Colorado; and
the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico.
   At Los Alamos, ``untreated liquid ... were sometimes discharged
(into) canyons'' and radioactive wastes stored in various pits,
trenches and shafts. As yet, the health risk of those actions
``cannot be quantified,'' the report said.
   Watkins outlined the department's proposed cleanup effort in a
speech Tuesday to the National Press Club.
   He acknowledged ``the cost will be high'' and said even an
optimistic timetable ``passes much of the burden to the next
generation.''
   The plan, which must be approved by Congress, calls for spending
$2.4 billion next fiscal year. After that the annual bill is
expected to steadily increase, peaking at more than $4 billion in
both fiscal 1994 and 1995.
   The money would be used to clean up pollution where federal and
state safety laws are violated, repair faulty equipment and develop
new procedures and technology for future waste disposal, the
department said.
   Most of the $19.5 billion will be used at 17 nuclear weapons
plants in a dozen states as well as other nuclear facilities, most
of which are inactive but continue to have hazardous waste problems.
   Among the sites considered most contaminated and getting the
largest share of the cleanup money are: the Hanford nuclear complex
in Washington state, $4 billion; the Savannah River facility near
Aiken, S.C., $3.4 billion; the Oak Ridge Reservation complex in
Tennessee, more than $2.7 billion; and the Idaho National Energy
Laboratory, nearly $2.2 billion.
   Meanwhile, Environmental Protection Agency officials Jonathan Z.
Cannon and Richard E. Sanderson criticized the plan, saying it
``provides for tradeoffs among compliance-related activities''
rather than a commitment to doing everything necessary to clean up
the plants.
</TEXT>
