<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0329EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ExportSubsidies     08-02 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Export Subsidies,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Subcommittee Chairman Says Agriculture Department Overreacted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic chairman of a House agriculture
subcommittee describes the government's cancellation of some farm
export projects as an overreaction, saying the program has been
handled like a covert operation.
   ``It's almost operated like a Defense Department operation,''
Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., said about the Export Enhancement
Program. ``I don't want a stealth EEP.''
   The Agriculture Department, citing congressional leaks of
sensitive information, said Tuesday that all projects approved but
not announced under the EEP have been canceled.
   ``A list of proposals that had been approved but not announced
was made public by members of Congress yesterday (Monday) in a
hearing. This information is market sensitive and was not
authorized for release,'' Richard Crowder, undersecretary for the
USDA's International Affairs and Commodity Programs, said in a
statement.
   The export subsidy program has operated since 1985 to make U.S.
commodities competitive in targeted markets where foreign
competitors _ especially the European Economic Community _ intrude
with subsidized sales of their own.
   About 65 countries, including the Soviet Union and China, have
been designated for subsidized sales.
   Under the program, private exporters can sell U.S. commodities
at lower prices to meet foreign competition and then collect free
government surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses or
subsidies.
   The Agriculture Department and the General Accounting Office,
the investigative arm of Congress, told a House agriculture
subcommittee Monday that the program has succeeded in boosting farm
exports.
   In response to questions by subcommittee members, the GAO gave
the panel a list of export subsidy proposals, some of which had not
been announced.
   The list, which was classified, could enable foreign competitors
to seek out the intended buyers of U.S. goods overseas and offer
better deals, an official said.
   ``If information is released prior to the announcement of a
decision, then the effectiveness of the program dissipates and the
ultimate cost is borne by U.S. farmers by making it more difficult
to compete in markets abroad,'' Crowder said.
   Glickman, chairman of the subcommittee, said in an interview
that ``the GAO voluntarily handed over the document to us. It
became a public document.''
   ``He is overreacting,'' Glickman said of Crowder. ``He's also
inexperienced. But he is an honest, decent guy.''
   Glickman, who said he planned to meet Friday with Crowder, sent
a letter acknowledging that the incident was ``unfortunate'' and
``shouldn't have happended.''
   Rep. David Nagle, D-Iowa, said the incident began when he asked
Crowder if the Soviet Union was interested in buying soybean oil
from the United States. Crowder said he didn't know and asked the
GAO, which led to the distribution of the sheets that included
rejected projects.
   ``Obviously he (Crowder) doesn't want this list out,'' Nagle
said. ``They don't want to admit they haven't been taking advantage
of sales opportunities and have been rejecting programs.''
   Nagle said the papers showed rejections to the Dominican
Republic for 200,000 tons of wheat, Venezuela for 700,000 tons of
wheat, Brazil for 500,000 tons of wheat and to Israel for 16,000
tons of rice.
   But Rep. Bill Emerson, R-Mo., an agriculture committee member
who was not at Monday's hearing, blamed Nagle and said the
Agriculture Department had no choice but to cancel the EEP projects.
   ``It is hard to quarrel with what they have done because it
could have adverse effects on the market,'' he said. ``It is
incumbent on the members to be a little more sensitive to tossing
this information around.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
