<DOCNO> AP890802-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0332EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia-Analysis 1stLd-Writethru a0421 08-02 0867</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-Analysis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0421,0893</SECOND>
<HEAD>After the Speeches, Underbrush Still Remains</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: To CORRECT that ASEAN has six members, SUB 25th graf, `And
the ... of co-existence.' Picks up 26th, `Outside nations ...' ^By MORT
ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers hoping to clear a path to peace
in Cambodia went home after a ringing round of speeches, leaving
deputies to hack through almost impenetrable underbrush.
   Even if four disparate Cambodia factions reach an accord,
allowing internationally supervised steps toward reconstruction,
good intention must stand the test of political reality.
   ``A lot of delegates express optimism, but I don't think very
many of them are optimistic,'' a Japanese official said before a
month of committee work began Tuesday.
   The crucial obstacle is what to do about the Khmer Rouge, no
mere negotiating point to any Cambodian who left his family on the
killing fields.
   Front-page cartoons in the Paris daily Le Monde keep fresh the
memory of Pol Pot's regime of the 1970s, in which at least 300,000
people were executed or starved in class purges.
   Tuesday's drawing showed one Cambodian telling others: ``I
propose we forget our little differences.'' They sat at a table
engulfed by a vast sea of skulls.
   Khmer Rouge leader Khieu Samphan sat impassively in the hall,
taking his turn at the rostrum to denounce subsequent Vietnamese
crimes in Cambodia as equal to Adolf Hitler's.
   Speaker after speaker rejected any Khmer Rouge role in
Cambodia's long-term future, but aides acknowledged privately it
was not likely the Khmer Rouge would go away.
   Even U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III endorsed Khmer
Rouge participation in a transitory coalition, regarding that as a
necessary evil to remove Vietnam from the scene.
   Vietnam's role was another imponderable.
   Vietnamese authorities pledged to evacuate their last troops by
Sept. 27, whatever the 19-nation Paris conference decided in
month-long deliberations.
   ``Will the Vietnamese really get out, even if they remove their
troops?'' reflected Lek Hor Tan, a Cambodian historian who helps
edit the London-based Index on Censorship. ``I don't believe it. We
have jungles, sanctuaries.''
   Other expert observers disagreed with Lek. Vietnam's lingering
presence would be noted, endangering its basic purpose of improving
its international image and attracting more aid.
   Vietnam Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach assured goodwill,
mugging for reporters in a surreal counterpoint to the grim
business at hand.
   He said his Chinese colleague was cordial, modifying Beijing's
harsh tone toward Vietnam. ``We shook hands,'' he said. ``Did we
look at each other and go like this?'' He closed his eyes and stuck
out his tongue. ``No, no.''
   Prince Norodom Sihanouk occupied a pivotal role at the
conference, as he has since his neutralist government crumbled two
decades ago after the Vietnam War spilled across his borders.
   Flitting between China and France, he has rallied support for
his embattled nation, held together by a rich ancient culture that
has absorbed and then shrugged off foreign intrusion throughout
history.
   Still, his popularity is not boundless. Many Cambodians remember
his reign as tainted by profligate relatives of the colorful prince
who, they say, played the saxophone while Cambodia burned.
   Some Cambodian experts see a likely compromise, if any is
forged, will be a symbolic role for Sihanouk under a government
sympathetic to Vietnam with the Khmer Rouge making war at the edges.
   As the conference shifted into grinding low gear, Western and
Cambodian analysts agreed that one of the few concrete results was
a backhand byproduct:
   In the past few months, Hun Sen, the Cambodian prime minister
who was widely spurned as a puppet of Hanoi, has been tacitly
legitimatized as leader of Cambodia.
   He is in a position to hold power while waiting for support to
wane for Sihanouk and for Son Sann, a pro-Western resistance leader
in tenuous control of his forces.
   Despite the obstacles, most of the world is anxious to press for
some sort of settlement.
   The United States and the Soviet Union see it as a costly,
dangerous flashpoint in a world with enough problems. Japan wants
to rebuild Cambodia but cannot without a stable internal framework.
   And the six members of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations have been trying for a decade to get Vietnam to go home and
allow the Cambodians to find some level of co-existence.
   Outside nations hope a thaw in Phnom Penh will melt away
settlements of 300,000 refugees along the Thai border, not only a
human tragedy but also a political tinderbox.
   Beyond the internal issues at the heart of the Cambodian
problem, nations differ over the international structure to
supervise the peace. Some insist that Cambodians should resolve
their own problems at their own pace.
   Canadian Foreign Minister Joe Clark, among others, argued that
the international effort has to be part of a comprehensive
settlement, including agreement among the Cambodians. ``There has
to be a peace to keep,'' he said.
   He added what many Cambodian experts considered to be a
understatement: This will be the most complex peacekeeping
operation since the Congo.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Mort Rosenblum, who is based in Paris, covered
Southeast Asia in the 1970s and has reported subsequently on
Cambodian problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
