<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0339EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-EastBlocAid     08-02 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Bloc Aid,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary Sees Risks, Unrest in Push for Free-Market Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary says it is risking social
unrest, rising unemployment and a possible backlash from the
conservative right in its push toward a free-market economy.
   The government, in a memo Tuesday to a 24-nation conference on
aid to Poland and Hungary, said it is determined to change its
state-controlled economy ``even if it initially causes social
conflicts.''
   Hungary warned, however, of widespread opposition if its
campaign resulted in a sharp and sustained fall in the standard of
living of the country's 11 million people.
   It urged more than 130 officials attending the meeting at the
headquarters of the European Community for financial aid. Hungary's
foreign debt is about $18 billion, the highest per capita in
Eastern Europe.
   The memo said the government was seeking as much as $3 billion
in new Western assistance from 1990 to 1992.
   President Bush and other key world leaders called for the
meeting to draw up a Western aid package that would encourage
democratic change and economic reforms in Poland and Hungary.
   They also urged emergency food shipments for Poland.
   At the one-day talks, the United States pledged an additional
$50 million in food aid to Poland, beginning Oct. 1, to help ease
the shortages caused by that government's moves toward a
free-market economy.
   ``We're trying to help carry them through this period,'' Curtis
Kamman, deputy assistant U.S. Secretary of State for European
Affairs, told reporters.
   Austria and Switzerland also promised food aid. The European
Community, the 12-nation trading bloc, earlier agreed to send $120
million worth of meat, grains and other products to Poland.
   Shortly after Bush's trip last month to Warsaw, the United
States announced it would send $9 million in food from surplus
stocks.
   Poland on Tuesday ended price controls and meat rationing as
part of the current economic reforms. There was concern the abrupt
lifting of price controls might send the country into turmoil.
   Hungary, a founding member of the Warsaw Pact, has been in the
forefront of economic reforms in the Communist bloc since the
1960s. The push has recently accelerated.
   The government's memo said the key goal was for Hungary to
become ``an equal member of the community of the developed
democratic nations.''
   To do so, it wants to create a market economy ``based on the
equality of the different forms of ownership'' and integrated in
the world economy with a currency that can be traded
internationally.
   Hungary's currency, like those of other East bloc nations, does
not circulate in world currency markets.
   ``Parallel with our efforts aimed at creation of the market
economy, economic policy must also be radically changed,'' the memo
said.
   The reforms, it said, require tight monetary and budget policies
that can lead to poor economic growth and higher inflation.
   Hungary said its balance of payments _ a summing up of
international trade payments _ was expected to ``deteriorate'' in
1989. Moreover, it forecast a higher jobless rate due partly to
shutdowns of money-losing companies.
   ``Although unemployment is not yet considerable, its rate is
gradually growing,'' it said, cautioning it could lead ``to serious
problems in certain regions.''
   It invited the nations attending the aid conference to meet in
Budapest next month to take a closer look at Hungary's situation.
   Nations at the meeting were the European Community members of
Britain, Ireland, Norway, Denmark, Belgium, the Netherlands,
Luxembourg, Germany, France, Spain, Italy and Portugal.
   Others present were the United States, Canada, Australia,
Turkey, New Zealand, Japan, Sweden, Switzerland, Finland, Austria,
Norway and Iceland.
</TEXT>
