<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0358EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AIDSCare     08-02 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Care,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Official Says Congress Responsible for Providing AIDS Funding</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress must share the responsibility in the
battle against AIDS by appropriating money for all the programs it
says must be implemented, a federal health official says.
   Dr. James O. Mason, assistant secretary for health at the
Department of Health and Human Services, said Congress often fails
to provide additional money to pay for programs it authorizes.
   ``We have been getting very clear guidance except when we get an
authorization without an appropriation,'' Mason told a House
oversight subcommittee grilling him Tuesday about spending on AIDS
treatment.
   ``It would be helpful if you folks would provide leadership,''
shot back Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., chairman of the subcommittee.
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., said the department won't get a
larger share of limited federal funds ``unless the department is
going to squeak a lot louder.''
   Weiss and Pelosi represent the two cities _ New York and San
Francisco _ with the largest AIDS populations.
   Mason, who headed the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta
before being selected by Bush for the No. 2 HHS job, said he shares
responsibility for the entire Public Health Service budget, which
includes the CDC, National Institutes of Health and the Food and
Drug Administration.
   ``What is enough (for AIDS)?'' he asked rhetorically. ``We can't
drop infant mortality or cancer. We could drop any other of these
and do more on AIDS but I don't think that is what the nation wants
us to do.''
   Moreover, he said, there are problems even within the AIDS
appropriations provided by Congress.
   For example, Mason said Congress authorized $15 million last
fall to help pay for AZT administered to patients who couldn't
afford it during the current fiscal year. AZT, which costs several
thousand dollars a year per patient, is the only approved drug
treatment for AIDS.
   However, the authorization didn't carry with it a new
appropriation to replace the appropriation that had been used up,
leaving HHS officials with the choice of ignoring Congress'
directive to continue paying for the drug or dipping into other
AIDS budget accounts to come up with the $15 million.
   Mason said he was facing the same problem that his predecessor
did because the HHS budget approved by the House Appropriations
Committee contains about $1.6 billion for AIDS, but nothing to
specifically cover the $30 million authorized for AZT payments
during the fiscal year that starts Oct. 1.
   ``The only place I can find that is to take it out of prevention
or biomedical research,'' Mason said. ``Someone has to make a
priority decision.''
   The human resources and intergovernmental relations subcommittee
of the House Committee on Government Operations, which held
Tuesday's hearing, doesn't have jurisdiction of legislation either
authorizing HHS programs or appropriating money for them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
