<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-02 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Post Minor Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended lower against the Japanese yen
Wednesday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange ended
with a marginal gain after erasing most of its early upward
momentum.
   The dollar ended at 136.20 yen, down 0.45 yen from Tuesday's
136.65 yen. It started lower at 135.58 yen and moved between 135.50
yen and 136.30 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues rose just 0.88
point, or 0.003 percent, ending at 34,899.34 after it surpassed the
35,000 mark for the first time at the end of morning trading.
   Dealers attributed the index's fall from the 35,000 mark to
profit-taking and directionless afternoon trading.
   In currency dealings, the dollar in Tokyo opened sharply lower
following its plunges on overseas markets overnight, traders said.
   Minori Takeuchi, a dealer with Chemical Bank in Tokyo, said
dealings in Tokyo were mixed with selling for position adjustment
and buying by foreign investors who will sell it later when the
dollar goes up.
   ``The dollar has been falling as market players became reluctant
to buy it because of the U.S. Federal Reserve Board's move to relax
monetary policy,'' she said, ``But it's no longer a strong
market-affecting incentive because it's already been taken for
granted.''
   Ms. Takeuchi said the dollar is unlikely to fall further,
because investors are no longer selling it only based on the U.S.
interest rate cuts and relaxation of monetary policy.
   ``Currently, the market is concerned about the U.S. unemployment
rate Friday as another indicator of U.S. economic growth,'' she
said.
   The U.S. Department of Commerce is to release the nation's July
jobless rate Friday in Washington.
</TEXT>
