<FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea     08-02 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Korea,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Detains Top Opposition Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security agents interrogated the
country's top opposition leader today to determine if he knew in
advance about a lawmaker's illegal visit to North Korea.
   Investigators from the Agency for National Security Planning,
the government's security arm, questioned Kim Dae-jung after taking
him from his party headquarters to a downtown police station.
   Police and government officials declined comment. A court
warrant was issued allowing authorities to hold Kim for 24 hours.
   The warrant said Kim, head of the Party for Peace and Democracy,
would be investigated to determine whether he was involved in a
trip to the communist north by Suh Kyung-won, a former Party for
Peace and Democracy lawmaker.
   Kim has denied involvement in Suh's trip and charged the
government with political harrassment.
   Suh is jailed on charges of violating national security for
visiting North Korean leader Kim Il Sung in August 1988. South
Korea bans unauthorized trips to the communist north, maintaining
that contacts with its rival must be through official channels.
   Also detained today was National Assembly member Moon Dong-hwan,
a senior Party for Peace and Demcracy member and brother of
dissident Presbyterian Rev. Moon Ik-hwan, who visited North Korea
for talks with North Korean leaders.
   The minister also is jailed.
   Hundreds of party members and supporters chanted Kim's name and
anti-government slogans when agents arrived at party headquarters
and presented detention orders to Kim and Moon before taking them
away.
   ``Disband the NSP (national security agency)!'' they shouted.
The opposition leader smiled and waved as he left.
   Party spokesman Lee Sang-soo said ``the national security
agency's scheme to suppress and destroy the party has reached the
extreme'' with Kim's detention.
   Suh turned himself into authorities June 25 and was formally
arrested three days later. Party leaders said they encouraged Suh
to turn himself in after the party belatedly heard about the trip.
   Kim ran unsuccessfully for the presidency in December 1987,
splitting the opposition vote with rival opposition leader Kim
Young-sam. President Roh Tae-woo, a former army general, received
36.6 percent of the vote.
</TEXT>
