<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador-Battle     08-02 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Battle,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Attack Army Post in Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas attacked an
army post in the capital in a battle that forced thousands of
residents to run for cover. At least two people were reported
killed.
   The guerrillas attacked at dusk Tuesday from their camps on the
slopes of the San Salvador Volcano that looms over the city's
northwest.
   The battle lasted about two hours and one soldier and one
civilian were reported killed. Two civilians and a soldier were
wounded.
   The battle kept thousands of residents of the San Ramon
neighborhood huddled behind walls or vehicles. Automatic weapons'
fire was heard from the northern neighborhoods of Zacamil and
Mejicanos, but there was no immediate word on casualties from those
zones.
   It was the fifth time in eight months that the army post in San
Ramon has been attacked. An estimated 200 rebels are camped on the
volcano.
   Sgt. Ventura Lopez, commander of the detachment of 10 soldiers
at the post, said there were about 60 attackers who hurled TNT.
About 100 army reinforcements later joined the battle.
   Rebels of the leftist Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front,
fighting for 10 years to overthrow the U.S.-backed government, have
stepped up attacks in the capital over the past 10 months after a
three-year lull.
</TEXT>
