<FIRST>r w PM-Hastings     08-02 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hastings,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hastings Tells Panel He Had No Part in Bribe Plot</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judge Alcee L. Hastings, fighting to remain on
the U.S. District Court bench, says he had nothing to do with a
plot to get a $150,000 bribe in a Florida racketeering case.
   ``No, sir,'' Hastings said Tuesday under questioning by his
attorney about the plot to get the $150,000 bribe.
   The first black federal judge in Florida, Hastings was impeached
by the House a year ago on charges of plotting to elicit a bribe,
lying to the 1983 jury that acquitted him of that charge and
improper disclosure of information from a federal wiretap.
   A 12-member panel is gathering evidence for the full Senate
before it votes on whether to impeach him and deprive him of his
$89,500 annual salary.
   Also Tuesday, the panel voted unanimously to move disbarred
Washington lawyer William Borders a step closer to being held in
contempt and perhaps jailed for refusing to testify.
   Borders, convicted and imprisoned for 33 months in the case,
refused twice last week to testify, asserting his right against
self-incrimination.
   The committee contends that he can't refuse to testify on Fifth
Amendment grounds because he already has been granted immunity. The
next step would put the issue before the full Senate and then a
court.
   Taking the stand in his defense, the 52-year-old Hastings
offered an explanation for one of the key points being used against
him.
   He said he appeared for dinner at 8 p.m. Sept. 16, 1981, in the
dining room of the Fontainebleau hotel in Miami. Earlier, Borders
had promised to produce Hastings in the dining room at that time on
that date.
   The idea was to prove Borders could influence the judge and thus
encourage a payoff from a man he believed to be a defendant trying
to buy his way out of a three-year racketeering sentence.
   Unknown to Borders, he was talking to an FBI undercover agent
wearing a hidden tape recorder.
   Hastings said he went to the hotel that night with a date
because Borders had suggested that he would meet him there.
However, Borders was in Las Vegas.
   Hasting said he wasn't surprised that Borders didn't show up.
   Hastings has always maintained that Borders, a longtime friend
and law school classmate, was a ``rainmaker'' who boasted of
influence he didn't actually have as a means of drumming up clients.
   The judge also offered an explanation for behavior prosecutors
say suggests an effort to elude the FBI on Oct. 9, 1981, the day
Borders was arrested as he drove out of a suburban Virginia motel
with a garment bag stuffed with cash and undercover agent H. Paul
Rico by his side.
   That day, Hastings was staying at the L'Enfant Plaza hotel in
Washington, preparing for a testimonial dinner in honor of Borders,
then a leader in the National Bar Association.
   Told of the Borders' arrest, Hastings quickly left for Florida
and went miles out of his way to Baltimore-Washington International
Airport to catch a plane when Washington's National Airport was
only minutes away.
   ``I went there to get a flight that I thought would get me to
Fort Lauderdale,'' Hastings testified. ``I really expected to see
the FBI at the National Airport, the Baltimore airport or Fort
Lauderdale.''
   Agents found him later that night in Miami at a friend's home.
</TEXT>
