<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     08-02 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Drops, Stocks Up Marginally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against the Japanese yen for the
third consecutive day today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main
index rose marginally.
   The dollar closed at 136.20 yen, down 0.45 yen from Tuesday's
136.65-yen finish. It opened at 135.58 yen and moved between 135.50
yen and 136.30 yen.
   The dollar now has declined 3.25 yen in three days.
   Mitsui Bank dealer Yoshitsugu Hanada said market players in
Tokyo were mainly making position adjustments today in the absence
of market-affecting news.
   ``The market's basic sentiment has been toward a weaker dollar
because of the falling U.S. interest rates, but Japanese investors
were trying to buy whenever the dollar fell,'' he said.
   ``When investors found out that the dollar wouldn't fall further
today, some of them started to buy it back, which helped the
currency end higher than its opening rate,'' Hanada added.
   But because of a slowdown in the U.S. economy, the dollar seemed
unlikely to rise again, he said, adding: ``Friday's (U.S.) jobless
rate report will be another indicator.''
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained
in early trading but ended up only 0.88 points, or 0.003 percent,
higher, closing at 34,899.334.
   It surpassed the 35,000 mark for the first time at the end of
morning trading. But Kazuhiro Nomura, a dealer with New Japan
Securities Co., said investors started selling to take profits as
soon as the afternoon session began, and the index fell back.
   ``Market players avoided buying to prevent prices from rising
too fast,'' he added.
   Trading was moderate, with first section volume estimated at 800
million shares, up from Tuesday's 700 million.
   Among gainers were steel, electric power company and chemical
issues.
</TEXT>
