<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0533EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BlochProbe     08-02 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bloch Probe,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bloch Said ``Pierre'' Was Just Stamp-Collecting Friend, Sources Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected spy Felix S. Bloch says he knew his
presumed KGB contact only as a stamp collector, according to
informed sources who also say the U.S. diplomat hasn't confessed to
taking money from the Soviets.
   The sources, commenting Tuesday only on condition of anonymity,
said suspicions about Bloch first arose when the United States
intercepted a May 14 telephone call to Bloch from a man named
Pierre, believed to be a Soviet agent in Paris.
   The suspected Soviet agent was among several individuals under
surveillance, including one who works for the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization, UNESCO,
according to the sources.
   Bloch and Pierre set up a meeting in Paris, and U.S. authorities
arranged for surveillance by the French intelligence service, said
the sources. The French filmed Bloch and the suspected KGB agent
exchanging briefcases a few days later at a Paris restaurant, the
sources said.
   Another telephone call from Pierre to Bloch came June 22, after
the State Department official had returned to Washington. Pierre
voiced veiled concerns that the two of them might be under
counterintelligence surveillance, the sources said.
   Three sources essentially confirmed details of events first
reported Tuesday by The Washington Post. No charges have been filed
against Bloch.
   The telephone call tipping Bloch that he might be in danger was
said to have come on the same day the State Department called him
in, stripped him of his building pass and diplomatic passport, and
placed him on administrative leave.
   Soon afterward, the FBI held its only interview with Bloch. In
it, he portrayed Pierre as a stamp collector and used that
relationship to explain the Paris meeting, the sources said.
   During that interview, Bloch made no admission that he was
working for the KGB or that he had accepted money from the Soviets,
according to the sources. Other reports have suggested he has told
the FBI he accepted money.
   Meanwhile, the apparent standoff in Bloch's espionage case
continued Tuesday, with Bloch inside his Washington apartment,
which coincidentally is just one block from the Soviet consulate.
The apartment was under constant watch by the FBI and the news
media.
   Intelligence sources said the job of making an espionage case
against him remains difficult because of the lack of a confession.
They said that U.S. officials may at some point be forced to
abandon any plans to prosecute and instead may make a deal with
Bloch to do a damage assessment _ an inventory of information that
has been lost or compromised _ if they remain convinced he actually
was helping the Soviets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0545EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0818 08-02 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0818,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Mandy Patinkin in Concert' Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS four grafs with other reviews; no PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mandy Patinkin never does anything halfway.
   If you need proof, the evidence is on display at Broadway's
Helen Hayes Theater where he has opened in a dazzling one-man show
called ``Mandy Patinkin in Concert: Dress Casual.''
   There's nothing casual about Patinkin except maybe his clothes _
red T-shirt, gray sneakers and baggy, black pants. The intense
performer, best known to theater audiences as Che Guevara in
``Evita'' and Georges Seurat in ``Sunday in the Park with George,''
is one of those unique artists who can make an audience cheer. At
the Helen Hayes, he scorches the stage with a virtuosic performance
that is as exhausting as it is exhilarating.
   What makes his show so special?
   Patinkin doesn't just stand there and sing. He takes over each
song as if it were a story, and he were telling it directly to you.
There's a simplicity in his communication that is disarming,
particularly when he is sweetly singing an old standard like
``Pennies from Heaven'' or Randy Newman's ``Marie.'' But he's not
afraid of a little histrionics either, like his almost
over-the-edge, down-on-one-knee version of Jolson's ``My Mammy'' or
``On the Atchison, Topeka and the Santa Fe'' performed at full
throttle.
   Although there is a heavy dose of theater songs, Patinkin's
wide-ranging repertoire is astonishing. His precise diction and
exact phrasing make him a natural singer of Stephen Sondheim songs.
And he doesn't disappoint, coming up with two numbers from ``Into
the Woods,'' as well as a heartfelt rendition of the title song
from ``Anyone Can Whistle'' and a hilarious version of ``Buddy's
Blues'' from ``Follies.''
   His grouping of songs is equally effective. Not many performers
would open with ``Doodle Doo Doo,'' move right into ``When the Red
Red Robin Comes Bob-Bob-Bobbin' Along'' and then finish with
``Tchaikowsky,'' a tongue-twisting recitation of Russian composers
from ``Lady in the Dark'' that Danny Kaye made famous. Somehow it
works.
   The show also includes a medley of seven songs from ``Pal Joey''
that seems like a mini-version of the Rodgers and Hart musical, as
well as an impassioned ``Soliloquy'' from ``Carousel.'' Both shows
sound like ideal vehicles for the singer if he decides to return to
the musical theater. In the ``Carousel'' number, Patinkin bounds
around the stage and even does a few chin ups on a backstage bar
while he sings.
   There are several comic highlights including a wacky version of
the Ella Fitzgerald standard ``A-Tisket A-Tasket'' that sounds like
it came out of the television police show ``Dragnet'' and a rare
Kander and Ebb song, ``Coffee in a Cardboard Cup,'' done with all
the sound effects of a typical greasy spoon restaurant.
   There should be a special mention for piano wizard Paul Ford,
Patinkin's partner during the evening. Ford is not just an
accompanist. He anticipates the singer's needs and provides the
support that Patinkin needs as he does his dangerous high-wire
balancing act.
   One final note. No microphones are used during the show. It's a
relevation and a relief to hear Patinkin's unique voice without the
tinny interference of modern technology. ``Mandy Patinkin in
Concert'' truly is ``live'' theater at its best.
   In other reviews:
   Howard Kissel of the Daily News called Patinkin's show the
``most exciting ... in ages.'' ``The range of what he does and the
imagination and power with which he does it are enough for you to
imagine he could singlehandedly revive the American musical
theater,'' Kissel wrote.
   Clive Barnes of the New York Post called Patinkin the greatest
entertainer on Broadway today and described the concert as
``dazzling fun.'' While he can bring tears to your eyes, Barnes
said, ``most of the time you are just happy to be in the same room
with him.''
   Stephen Holden of The New York Times described the show as
``audacious, often brilliant, but also a touch wacky.'' ``Instead
of a bland, all-American confidence, he radiates a fierce, neurotic
intelligence,'' Holden said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0048 </DOCNO>
