<FIRST>r w PM-WhiteCollarScavengers     08-02 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-White Collar Scavengers,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scavengers Make Off With Computers, Other Equipment at Eviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Well-dressed passersby didn't hesitate to walk
off with computers, desks and other items as U.S. marshals emptied
the office of a downtown Washington computer company whose owner
recently was shot to death.
   ``This is downtown, the Wall Street of Washington, and people
are grabbing and acting like it's a farmer's market and they don't
have to pay,'' said Wendell Holloway, a lobbyist who stopped to
watch the eviction on Tuesday.
   Some people were on their way to work and others were heading to
a sale at a nearby office supply store when they spotted the
merchandise at curbside. Dressed in dark suits, ties, dresses and
high heels, the treasure hunters tossed about words like
``megabytes'' and ``modems'' as they rummaged.
   Marshals removed all the furniture and supplies from an office
that had been leased by Kermit Ferguson, who was fatally shot on
June 28 by a man who walked into another business he owned. No
arrests have been made in connection with the slaying.
   The company was evicted because it owed over $150,000 in rent,
said Blake Esherick, comptroller for Hunter Leasing.
   District of Columbia police said the scavengers are liable for
prosecution on a misdemeanor or felony theft charge, depending on
whether what they took was worth $250 or more.
   A spokesman for the U.S. marshal's office said the property
belongs to the owners and is not considered abandoned until it has
been on the curb for 72 hours.
</TEXT>
