<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru 1stAdd 08-02 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, 1st Add, a0492,0179</SECOND>
<TEXT>WARSAW: increasingly independent.    Prior to Kiszczak's election,
the Communists lost a key parliament vote for the first time in postwar
Poland as Solidarity pushed through a resolution to investigate the outgoing
government for economic misconduct.    The free trade union movement believes
the government of Mieczyslaw Rakowski _ now Communist Party chief _ should
be held accountable for the unraveling of the economy during its nine months
in office.    Poland, convulsed by consumer shortages and triple-digit
inflation, suffered further Tuesday when price controls were lifted on
meat, sugar and other basic commodities.    After a Sejm speech by Communist
floor leader Marian Orzechowski, in which he charged such an investigation
would not be fair, the deputies voted 206-169 with 31 abstentions to create
the commission anyway.    The commission would decide if there were legal
grounds to refer government misconduct to the State Tribunal, which handles
prosecutions of the government.    It was the first substantive vote the
Communists have lost, although they have been on the losing side of some
procedural matters.
