<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Landslide     08-02 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Landslide,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Toll Rises to Eight from Heavy Rains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers today recovered the bodies of three
members of a family whose house was crushed by a landslide,
bringing to eight the death toll from torrential rains in the Tokyo
area, police said.
   Three firefighters died Tuesday while trying to rescue the
family.
   The National Police Agency said three people were still missing
_ one in Saitama, just north of Tokyo, and two in Chiba, to the
south.
   The rains, which began Monday night, flooded 7,111 houses,
caused 298 landslides and damaged roads at 50 places in Tokyo and
four neighboring prefectures, said a national police official who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   In Kawasaki, just southwest of Tokyo, firefighters and police
recovered the bodies of Saburo Kogure, 59; his wife, Nobuko, 57;
and son, Tsutomu, 28, from the wreckage of their two-story wooden
house, which two landslides buried Tuesday, police said.
   The second landslide buried 14 firefighters who were trying to
rescue the family. Three of the rescuers were killed and 11
injured, four seriously.
   In Chiba, a station wagon carrying a family of five fell into a
reservoir after being hit by a landslide, another national police
official said. He said three children were rescued from the
vehicle, but the parents were killed.
   More than 9.8 inches of rain fell in Tokyo, while 17.7 inches
were recorded in parts of Chiba from late Monday through Tuesday,
the Central Meteorological Agency said.
</TEXT>
