<SECOND>PM-Iran-Assassins, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0488,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Reported to Have Overseas Assassin Unit</HEAD>
<UNK>EDs: SUB lead to clarify; CORRECT cycle designation.</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran may be responsible for two recent
political murders outside its borders, according to Western
officials who fear Tehran has set up a unit of assassins to kill
foes on foreign soil, a published report said today.
   Iranian assassins are suspected of the murders of a Kurdish
leader in Vienna and a former Iranian military intelligence officer
in the United Arab Emirates capital of Dubai, The Washington Post
reported.
   Unidentified Iranian exile sources were quoted as saying Iran's
Revolutionary Guards have set up a team of assassins.
   The newspaper quotes unidentified Western diplomats as saying it
was unclear who approved the assassinations, but that the killings
may have resulted from power struggles inside Iran between
moderates and hard-liners seeking to eliminate dissidents abroad.
   The Revolutionary Guards are under the authority of Parliament
Speaker Ali Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani, the winner of Iran's July 28
presidential election. Rafsanjani has shown greater willingness to
open to the West in recent months.
   Austrian Prime Minister Alois Mock said it was ``probable'' the
June 4 attack in Vienna on Abdolrahman Qassemlou, an anti-Iranian
Kurd, was committed by Iran. Iran has denied responsibility.
   In Dubai, police believe an Iranian assassin murdered Ataellah
Bayahmadi, a former military intelligence officer under Shah
Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, while he was on a secret mission to meet
with Iranian military officers sympathetic to anti-government
forces.
   Bayahmadi was working for the Flag of Freedom Organization, a
Paris-based group dedicated to overthrowing Iran's Islamic republic.
   The newspaper quoted Iranian exile sources who said Bayahmadi's
killer has been identified as a man named Kabuli, who was denied
entry to Dubai but who entered the country through the neighboring
shiekdom of Sharjah.
</TEXT>
