<FIRST>u i PM-Hostages-Iran     08-02 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Iran,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Group Claims Rafsanjani Controls Hostage-Takers</HEAD>
<HEAD>PM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's main opposition group claimed
today that President-elect Hashemi Rafsanjani secretly sent his
brother to Syria to ``closely supervise'' the killing of Lt. Col.
William Higgins.
   Rafsanjani has been quoted by the Soviet news agency Tass as
denying in a meeting with visiting Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze that Iran had any ``relation to the tragedy.''
   The Mujahedeen Khalq, or People's Holy Warriors, said in a
statement that Rafsanjani exerts direct control of the radical
Shiite Moslem groups believed to be holding Western hostages in
Lebanon.
   The group said Rafsanjani sent his brother, Mahmoud, ``secretly
to Syria a few days ago in order to closely supervise the terrorist
acts of the regime's proxies in Lebanon, including the execution of
the American hostage, Col. Higgins.''
   The opposition's statement said Mahmoud Rafsanjani heads the
Iranian foreign ministry's ``Lebanon Committee'' set up to
coordinate the kidnappers' activities.
   The statement was sent by telex to The Associated Press from
Baghdad, Iraq, where the group has its headquarters.
   A Shiite Moslem group calling itself the Organization of the
Oppressed on Earth claimed it hanged the U.S. Marine on Monday in
retaliation for Israel's abduction Friday of a Shiite Moslem cleric
in south Lebanon.
   The group released a videotape that purported to show Higgins
hanging from a makeshift gallows. There was no indication when it
was filmed. Prior reports indicated that Higgins, who led a
75-member U.N. truce monitoring force in Lebanon, may have been
killed by his captors last year.
   Moslem fundamentalist groups loyal to Iran are believed to be
holding most of the 16 western hostages in Lebanon.
   They are thought to be linked to Hezbollah, or Party of God, an
Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem group seeking to dominate the
1.2-million strong Shiite community in Lebanon, the country's
largest sect.
   The Mujahedeen statement alleged that several Hezbollah
officials sent from Tehran to Lebanon were told to ``extend their
stay in Beirut for another two weeks on the orders of
President-elect Rafsanjani in order to carry out the execution of
Col. Higgins.''
   Hezbollah denies it has anything to do with hostage-taking,
while Iran has sought to distance itself from the reported hanging
and threats to execute other western hostages held in Lebanon.
   Rafsanjani, who was voted president by a landslide majority in
Friday's election, is believed anxious to erase Iran's image as a
sponsor of international terrorism.
   Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said Monday before Higgins'
death was announced the threat against him ``has nothing to do with
us ... However, we condemn any kind of kidnapping or death threat.''
   But on Sunday, Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi warned
that Islamic groups around the world would retaliate for the
aduction of the cleric, Sheik Abdul-Karim Obeid.
   The Mujahedeen statement said Iran used its embassy in Damascus,
Syria, as a headquarters for Hezbollah activities in Lebanon. Syria
is a close ally of Iran.
   The statement said Iranian Revolutionary Guards based in Lebanon
were responsible for ``military training of terrorists, operational
planning, interrogations and other intelligence operations by the
regime's proxy terrorist groups in Lebanon.''
   About 4,000 Revolutionary Guards are currently believed based in
the Syrian-controlled Bekaa valley in eastern Lebanon.
   Khomeini's 1979 fundamentalist revolution in Iran helped spawn
several Shiite terrorist groups in Lebanon. Revolutionary Guards,
sent into Lebanon during the 1982 Israeli invasion, helped organize
Hezbollah.
</TEXT>
