<DOCNO> AP890802-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0611EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LiquidAir     08-02 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Liquid Air,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Use Liquid To Help Premature Baby Breathe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new respiration technique that uses a
liquid to deliver oxygen to a patient's lungs could save premature
babies and affect the abortion debate, researchers said.
   In May, a baby born after 28 weeks of gestation and within an
hour or two of death from lung damage was kept alive 19 hours when
doctors filled the infant's lungs with perfluorocarbon, an
oxygen-carrying liquid, said Dr. Thomas Shaffer, a Temple
University physiologist and pediatrician who led the team.
   He and his colleagues are on call to attempt the procedure again
when a candidate becomes available, Shaffer said.
   The baby girl, born two months premature and weighing just under
2 pounds, was the first human to undergo the procedure, according
to Dr. Michael Harrison, a pediatric surgeon at the University of
California San Francisico. Harrison was not involved in the
research in Philadelphia.
   If the procedure could be shown to shorten the time a fetus is
dependent on its mother, the technology could affect the abortion
debate in the country, said Arthur Caplan, director of the Center
for Biomedical Ethics at the University of Minnesota in Minneapolis.
   In its controversial decision July 3, the U.S. Supreme Court
ruled states may require doctors to determine through various tests
whether a fetus at least 20 weeks old is capable of surviving
outside the womb. Many states prohibit aborting a viable fetus, but
the court's 1973 decision making abortion legal drew the viability
line at 24 weeks.
   Generally, premature babies delivered 23 to 24 weeks from
conception stand a chance of surviving without major disabilities,
researchers said.
   If the liquid ventilation technique is successful, it could push
that time period back to 20 weeks, Shaffer said.
   However, it is still unclear whether organs other than the lungs
would be developed enough to sustain life at 20 weeks, he said.
   Aside from premature babies, the procedure holds promise for any
kind of situation where a patient's lungs cannot be ventilated with
gas, Shaffer said.
   Dr. Leland C. Clark, a chemist at Children's Hospital Medical
Center in Cincinnati who first discovered the technique, said
perfluorocarbon acts as a liquid Teflon to gently separate parts of
the lung that stick together after a collapse in a premature baby.
   In adults, the body produces surfactant, which prevents the
inside of a lung from sticking to itself. But in premature babies
who have not yet developed surfactant or in babies who lack the
material, normal ventilation runs the risk of bursting a lung or
damaging it, he said.
   The infant, whose lungs had been damaged by two weeks of
conventional ventilation and had partially collapsed, was close to
death May 10 when the experiment was performed, Shaffer said.
   About a half ounce of perfluorocarbon, a liquid that carries
oxygen, was poured into the baby's lungs through her trachea, he
said. About another quarter ounce of the liquid was allowed to flow
in and out of her lungs, bringing fresh oxygen, for 15 minutes,
Shaffer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0612EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-CFCs     08-02 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-CFCs,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nissan to Ban Chloroflourocarbons from Its Vehicles by 1993</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Co. said today that it plans to make
its car air conditioners and manufacturing processes free of
chlorofluorocarbons, the gases blamed for destroying the Earth's
protective ozone layer, by 1993.
   Nissan became the first of Japan's major automakers _ which are
heavy users of chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) _ to announce a total ban
on the gases.
   Nissan spokesman Shingo Suzuki said the company, helped by
air-conditioning makers such as Hitachi Ltd. and Calsonic Corp., is
developing new car air conditioners that use a new substance to
replace CFC-12.
   Nissan has used some 1,150 tons of CFC-12 a year as coolants, he
said, and a total of 1,500 tons of CFC's a year for all purposes,
accounting for 1.2 percent of total CFC use in Japan.
   In the United States, the spokesman said, Nissan already has
stopped using CFC-11 in the making of automobile bumpers and will
do so in Japan by the end of next year.
   By the end of 1993, he said, the company plans to replace
CFC-113 with water for cleansing automobile parts. He said this
will require the company to develop additional processes to dry
parts after washing. CFC-113 dries instantly.
   ``But it depends on the feasibility of CFC alternatives,''
Suzuki said. ``If we can get stable supplies of new substitutes,
our goal is certainly attainable.''
   Toyota Motor Co. spokesman Hiroshi Hashimoto said, ``Although
we've been considering environmental issues, we haven't reached the
stage to announce anything concrete.'' He said Nissan's move would
``prompt Toyota to consider the issue more seriously and swiftly.''
   An official of the freon countermeasure division in the Ministry
of International Trade and Industry called such moves by the
private sector ``very welcome.''
   Companies that have to use additional machines and substances in
the process of cutting CFC use can obtain tax reductions, said the
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In Montreal, Canada, 38 countries agreed in 1987 to reduce
production and use of the gases. Under the Montreal Protocol,
participating countries must freeze their CFC consumption this year
at the 1986 level and reduce consumption to 5 percent of the 1986
level by the end of 1999.
</TEXT>
