<HEAD>Dollar Up, Pound Falls, Gold Steady</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was steady at lower levels this morning
in light European trading.Gold was steady.
   ``A lot of people are on holiday and there is little action,''
said one dealer in London.
   In the currency markets, dealers expected no excitement until
trading began in the United States.
   ``The dollar is being made out of New York, both politically and
from the market,'' said one dealer in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   Another dealer in West Germany said the dollar seemed to have
found technical and psychological support at 1.85 marks, and said
there could be a short-lived rebound.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell .45 yen to close at 136.20 yen. Later
in London, the dollar traded at 136.30 yen.
   The pound sterling traded at $1.6622 early today, up from
$1.6550 late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8508 West German marks, down from 1.8660
   _1.5940 Swiss francs, down from 1.6075
   _6.2725 French francs, down from 6.3135
   _2.0850 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1060
   _1,330.75 Italian lire, down from 1,342.50
   _1.1740 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1743
   Gold opened in London today at $370.55 a troy ounce, up from
$368.25 late Tuesday. At mid-morning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $369.90 an ounce.
   The same price prevailed in Zurich, where trading was suspended
Tuesday for a national holiday. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose 6
cents an ounce to close at $371.32.
   Silver was trading in London at $5.25 a troy ounce, up from
$5.23 an ounce late Tuesday.
