<HEAD>President's Son Rules Out Bid for Texas Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only race that concerns George W. Bush is the
American League pennant chase.
   Bush _ oilman, baseball team owner and president's eldest son _
declared Tuesday he would not run for governor of Texas next year.
   ``I have had time to think and sort things out, and at this
time, I am not a candidate for governor in 1990,'' Bush said in a
speech to lawyers.
   ``For now I want to focus my obligations to the Texas Rangers
baseball team and more importantly on my responsibilities as a
father and as a provider,'' he said.
   Bush is managing partner of the Rangers, who are battling for
the American League West division title.
   Bush said he knows better than to ``never say never,'' but he
felt very little could change his mind about not running in 1990.
   ``I think that's a very honest and forthright statement,'' said
Fred Meyer, state GOP chairman. ``I do believe at some point he's
going to be a factor on the political scene because I think he
handles himself very well.''
   Since returning to Texas last year after helping his father's
presidential campaign, the 43-year-old Bush has been widely viewed
as a likely candidate for governor.
   Republican Gov. Bill Clements has said he will not seek
re-election.
