<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0508,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rabin Renews Trade Offer, Congratulates Soldiers on Kidnap</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with Rabin saying no other nations
informed of Obeid abduction; picks up 4th pvs: The 12-member...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin today defended
Israel's kidnapping of a Lebanese Shiite clergyman, saying the
Cabinet considered the dangers to foreign hostages in Lebanon
before approving the abduction.
   Speaking to parliament, Rabin also disclosed that the Cabinet
had approved Friday's capture of Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid two months
ago.
   He said final approval was delayed until ``every grain of
possibility for dialogue'' had been exhausted on winning the
release of three Israeli soldiers believed held in Lebanon.
   Rabin said Israel did not inform any other country of its
intentions to abduct Obeid. ``We didn't include any other country
before the action and did not even offer information about it,'' he
said.
   The 12-member inner Cabinet of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
also met today to discuss the hostage crisis, but there was no word
on the outcome of that meeting.
   In his address to parliament, Rabin said Israel has rejected an
International Red Cross appeal to visit Obeid, who was abducted
along with two associates from the south Lebanon village of Jibchit.
   He said Israel would agree only if the Red Cross was able to
visit Israeli captives.
   During his 22-minute address, Rabin read anew Israel's offer to
swap Lebanese Shiite prisoners held by Israel and for 16 Western
hostages and the three Israelis.
   Israel is believed to be holding up to 60 Shiites in Israel, and
allied militias in south Lebanon are believed to hold an additional
300.
   Rabin defended the Obeid kidnap against criticism that Israel
did not consider the dangers to foreign hostages.
   ``We took into consideration all the possible reactions,'' he
said. ``We saw them all, including the actions that already took
place, and ones even worse.''
   A Shiite group calling itself the Organization of the Oppressed
on Earth claimed it killed Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins on
Monday after Israel refused to free Obeid. A second group said
another American hostage, Joseph Cicippio, would be killed on
Thursday unless the cleric is freed.
   Israel maintains Higgins was killed several months ago.
   Rabin said the Cabinet approved the abduction of Obeid, a
spiritual leader of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah movement that is
believed an umbrella group for hostage-takers in Lebanon, after
extensive efforts to gain freedom for its captured soldiers. He did
not detail those efforts.
   ``So the government of Israel decided to allow the army to
apprehend the leader of the Hezbollah in south Lebanon so we would
have in our hands valuable property for a prisoner swap,'' he said.
   He described the abduction of Obeid, whom he accused of
involvement in Higgins kidnap and the abduction of two Israeli
soldiers, as ``very successful.''
   ``On this stage, I want to send my blessings to the chief of
staff and the commanders of the army and the unit that carried it
out on the way this mission was carried out,'' he said.
   Rabin spoke in response to three motions of no confidence
introduced by three small Arab-oriented parties. The motions in the
120-seat body were defeated by a 31-5 vote with one abstention and
most of members absent.
   Mainstream opposition groups refused to join in the attack on
the government, saying lives were at stake and criticism should be
postponed.
   The defense minister was interrupted at one point by an Arab
member of Parliament, Mohammed Miari, who chided Rabin for
announcing his hostage swap offer 30 minutes after the deadline set
for Higgins' purported hanging.
   Communist and Arab legislators accused the government of
kidnapping Obeid to divert attention from efforts to resolve the
Palestinian problem and end the uprising against Israeli occupation.
</TEXT>
