<HEAD>Western Wildfires at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a state-by-state look at wildfires burning in the West:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   IDAHO: Hundreds of lightning-caused fires have burned 80,000
acres, much of that on national forest land. Flames were near three
small mountain towns, and more than 5,000 firefighters were on the
fire lines.
   MONTANA: A fire burning in grassland and scattered timber in the
Custer National Forest became the state's biggest blaze of the
summer Tuesday when it surpassed 1,200 acres. About 140
firefighters were dispatched to fight the blaze in the southeast
corner of the state. Several smaller blazes burned elsewhere.
   OREGON: Fires east of the Cascades have burned 80,000 acres and
were being fought Tuesday by 5,000 people. The worst of the blazes
were around Baker, where ranchers forced from their remote homes
over the weekend were allowed back by Tuesday.
   WASHINGTON: Crews contained an 850-acre forest fire in the
Pasayten Wilderness near the Canadian border Tuesday, freeing 80
firefighters to join battles in Idaho and Oregon. About 1,200 Army
troops at Fort Lewis were to head to wildfires in Oregon after
completing a one-day crash course in firefighting.
   CALIFORNIA: More than 1,300 firefighters fought in steep canyons
in the Cleveland National Forest southeast of Los Angeles to
encircle half of a fire that blackened 8,200 acres of brush and
burned a home, a mobile home and a travel trailer. In the Sierra
Nevada foothills, firefighters contained an 11,700-acre wildfire
that destroyed seven homes.
</TEXT>
