<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Floods     08-02 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Floods,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Floods Kill 15 People in Soviet Far East</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helicopters are rescuing people from rooftops in
the Soviet Far East, where the worst flooding in more than 35 years
has killed 15 people, destroyed thousands of houses and washed out
crops, Tass reported today.
   The official news agency said sections of the main railroad in
the region, the Vladivostok-Khabarovsky Railway, were destroyed
Tuesday night.
   Bridges and tracks were ruined as the Ussuri and Malinovka
rivers overflowed near the city of Dalnerechensk, Tass said.
   The report said 1,000 passengers were stranded at the
Vladivostok Railroad Station and that three passenger trains were
turned into mobile homes for people waiting until the tracks are
restored.
   In a report Tuesday, Tass said rivers in the Dalnerechensk and
Lesozavodsk districts had risen more than 20 feet and caused a
``critical situation.''
   Crops _ including potatoes, tomatoes and cucumbers _ were
destroyed on more than 100 farms, and more than 70,000 head of
cattle were cut off from pastures or stalls, the news agency said
Tuesday. Thousands of houses were destroyed and hundreds of miles
of roads and telephone and power lines were ruined.
   The Maritime Emergency Commission told Tass that preliminary
estimates put the number of dead in the floods at 15. The area is
near the Sea of Japan, 4,500 miles east of Moscow, and 250 miles
northeast of Beijing.
   Rain inundated the area for five days, but it has now stopped
and the water level of rivers is declining slowly, Tass said.
   Military helicopters were taking people perched on rooftops and
trees to safety and bringing food, medicine and clothing to
inundated villages.
   Tass said the flooding was the worst in the area since 1953,
when virtually the entire north of the maritime territory of the
Soviet Union was under water.
</TEXT>
