<FIRST>u i PM-Kiszczak     08-02 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kiszczak,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Polish Prime Minister Oversaw Talks with Solidarity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's new prime minister, Gen.
Czeslaw Kiszczak, played a leading role in suppressing Solidarity
in 1981, but he also helped initiate this year's campaign that made
the union legal again.
   Once a shadowy figure best known for his crackdowns on
dissidents, Kiszczak emerged earlier this year as a valuable
negotiating partner for the opposition in the two months of talks
that resulted in Solidarity's legalization and in partially free
elections.
   Despite Kiszczak's new outlook, Solidarity opposed him for prime
minister. Members of the Communist-allied Peasant Party also talked
of defecting, but he gained victory by a slim margin today in
parliament.
   The 63-year-old army general, who has been interior minister
since 1981 and thus supervised the nation's police forces, donned a
civilian suit for this year's talks with Solidarity. He often drove
his red Peugeot to a palace in downtown Warsaw where negotiations
were held.
   With a mixture of charm and toughness, Kiszczak quickly
impressed union negotiators. He disarmed underground writers by
praising their essays.
   It was Kiszczak who made the proposal for talks with the
opposition on political and economic reform a year ago during a
wave of nationwide strikes, Poland's worst labor unrest since the
early days of Solidarity seven years ago.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa refused to commit Solidarity to
talks without a pledge that the union would be legalized. In a
dramatic reversal, President Wojciech Jaruzelski, then the
Community Party leader, pushed through an offer to restore the
union's legal status at a party plenum in January.
   Three weeks later, as chief negotiator for the government side,
Kiszczak opened the negotiations. Agreements reached April 5 led to
legalization of Solidarity and partially free elections in which
Solidarity scored dazzling victories July 4 and July 18.
   But Kiszczak was one of 33 out of 35 top government and party
officials who ran unopposed on a national slate and failed to get
the required 50 percent of votes cast.
   Kiszczak's relations with the opposition were not always so
cordial.
   Along with Jaruzelski and Defense Minister Florian Siwicki,
Kiszczak helped impose the December 1981 martial-law crackdown in
which thousands of Solidarity activists were rounded up and
imprisoned.
   Three years later, Interior Ministry security police on his
payroll murdered the Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko, a pro-Solidarity
priest who kept the ethos of the union alive in monthly Masses for
the homeland at his Warsaw parish.
   Kiszczak saw that the four officers were convicted of murder,
but the trial stopped short of revealing any higher-level
involvement, which some opposition members still suspect.
   As head of the ministry responsible for containing the
opposition which flourished underground after martial law, Kiszczak
developed a deep knowledge of Solidarity.
   One leading Solidarity activist who has spent years in jail
recently joked that one of the best collections of underground
literature can be found in the ministry's basement.
   Born in 1925, Kiszczak's war experiences contributed to the
evolution of a tough, young officer. Shipped by the Nazis to work
as a forced laborer in the southwestern city of Wroclaw, Kiszczak
escaped and made his way to communist resistance forces in Austria.
   He joined the Communist Party in 1945 and helped in the campaign
against Polish partisans opposed to the imposition of Communist
rule.
   Kiszczak later attended the Voroshilov Academy of the Soviet
armed forces in Moscow and was promoted to general in 1973. He
served as head of military intelligence between 1972 and 1979 and
head of the military police in the Ministry of National Defense
between 1979 and 1981.
   Jaruzelski named Kiszczak head of the Interior Ministry in
August 1981, several months before the crackdown on Solidarity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0909EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-Kiszczak-Text     08-02 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Kiszczak-Text,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Acceptance Speech, Kiszczak Tries to Enlist Opposition</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a text of the acceptance speech by
Interior Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak after his election as prime
minister. The speech was monitored on Polish television and
translated by The Associated Press:
   I would like to thank you for entrusting me with the honorable
mission of forming the government of the Polish People's Republic.
   The confidence which I enjoyed in the support for my candidacy I
treat as ... an obligation. I will do whatever is in my might not
to fail this confidence.
   With attention, I approach those deputies who voted against my
candidacy. Their opinion inclines me toward an active search for
ways and means of gaining a broader parliamentary and social
understanding and approval for the activities of the government
which I intend to form.
   I face, and naturally the high chamber (the Sejm) faces, the
question of the shape of the new Cabinet, its program and
philosophy of functioning.
   I state with regret that so far, the concept of creating a
``grand coalition'' government has not been accepted.
   I think that a government of such a construction would be most
appropriate today for overseeing the course of issues of the
country. That is why in forming the Cabinet on as broad a basis as
possible, I will not give up efforts to attract to it
representatives of opposition circles with a hope that in the
future a grand coalition government will be possible.
   I opt for a government of the ``roundtable.''
   I do not refer here only to the symbol of agreement and national
reconciliation, but most of all to its substantial content and ways
of shaping the process of dialogue. A vision of Poland's
development has been outlined in the roundtable accords (reached
between Solidarity and Communist authorities in April),
corresponding with social aspirations and expectations.
   The new government should work with all its effort toward
realizing this vision, especially as far as the shape of the new
economic order and political reforms are concerned.
   As co-chairman of the roundtable, I feel morally and politically
obliged to guarantee the concluded agreement of Poles. I will thus
do everything so that the directions of the government's work might
correspond with the supreme reasons of state and the nation.
   The seriousness of the internal situation, especially in the
economic sphere, imposes the necessity of quick action. I would
thus like to ask the high chamber if I could present the program of
action and makeup of the Council of Ministers within the next two
weeks.
   Thank you.
</TEXT>
