<FIRST>r a PM-CannibalismDig     08-02 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cannibalism Dig,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remains Support Story of 19th Century Cannibal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An analysis of the remains of five gold
prospectors who died in 1874 supports cannibal Alferd Packer's
claim that he killed only one, experts say.
   Packer, who had led the gold expedition in the Rockies, said one
man killed the four others with repeated hatchet blows while Packer
was away from camp. Packer said he killed that man in self-defense
and survived the winter on the flesh of the dead.
   ``Four of the five were repeatedly hacked,'' James Starrs,
professor of law and forensics at George Washington University,
said Tuesday, summing up the laboratory findings. ``If ever there
was demonstrative evidence of overkill, this is it.''
   The analysis at the Human Identification Laboratory at the
University of Arizona also concluded that knife marks on the bones
appear ``consistent with a conscious effort to deflesh the deceased
bodies,'' Starrs said.
   Packer was convicted of manslaughter in all five deaths and
served a prison term.
   Starrs recently led a team that dug up the remains from a common
grave about two miles from Lake City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
