<DOCNO> AP890802-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0933EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-Solidarity-Text     08-02 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Solidarity-Text,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Text of Solidarity Floor Leader's Statement on Kiszczak</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts of a speech by Bronislaw
Geremek, leader of the Solidarity opposition in the Sejm,
explaining why its members opposed the election of Czeslaw Kiszczak
as prime minister. The text was monitored on Polish television and
translated by The Associated Press:
   The (Solidarity) Citizens' Parliamentary Club will vote against
Czeslaw Kiszczak's candidacy for the post of chairman of the
Council of Ministers.
   We stand against this candidacy not because he is the chief of
the Interior Ministry, of which this part of the chamber so often
used to be the clientele.
   We also know in recent months that Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak can be
a negotiator and can carry on dialogue with people on the other
side of ideological and political barriers. We also appreciate the
words uttered in his statement, referring to the continuation of
the philosophy of the ``round table'' and the anticipation of
changes.
   We stand against this candidacy because no personnel reshuffle
within the present political arrangements, dictated by the monopoly
of a single party, can solve the country's problems.
   We are of the opinion that one cannot change things by
continuing the present situation of the country, that a break is
necessary, a break that will clearly say that we (Solidarity
lawmakers) have arrived in this building on Wiejska Street. And I
would like to be able to say that all of us have come in order to
change things. ...
   I think that as we sit here, a will for change can be found on
all sides of this chamber. However, in our opinion, changes in the
way of exercising power must be made so that this change could
correspond with the Polish situation.
   A political monopoly of exercising power by one party must be
discarded and destroyed. It does not serve the country.
   And this is why we think that, with the necessary amount of
confidence, the Polish opposition is capable of building a program
of change and of carrying out this program.
   Lech Walesa's statement said clearly that the Polish opposition,
all its circles, expects deep, structural changes and that the
Polish opposition is ready to form a government appropriate to the
tasks the country faces.
   It is ready to take responsibility not only for leading the
country out of crisis but also for changing the way of exercising
power. Because without this change the situation of the country
cannot improve.
   In a responsible way and with a feeling of realism we are able
to form a government of national salvation. ...
   Such a government of change could be a chance for the country.
</TEXT>
