<FIRST>r i PM-Hostages-Pope     08-02 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Pope,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Agrees to Seek Return of Higgins' Body</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II has agreed to intervene to
seek the return to the United States of the body of Marine Lt. Col.
William Higgins, the Vatican said today.
   The pope acted after a call Tuesday from President Bush, the
Vatican said in a statement.
   ``His holiness expressed the willingness of the Holy See to find
a solution to this problem,'' it said.
   Shiite extremists claimed Monday to have hanged Higgins in
retaliation for Israel's refusal to free a Shiite Moslem cleric
kidnapped by Israeli commandos July 28. Israel accused the
clergyman, Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, of involvement in terrorist
activities, including Higgins' abduction Feb. 17, 1988.
   John Paul, in the conversation with Bush, expressed hope that
``the leaders and the parties involved find the roads to
constructive accords in the higher interests of peace and full
development of the people of the Middle East and the world,'' the
statement said.
   Vatican officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
diplomatic contacts for the release of Higgins' body were already
under way using channels that the Vatican has kept open for months
during the latest round of fighting in Lebanon.
   John Paul has repeatedly appealed to all factions in the region
to halt the fighting and to help rebuild the country.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the pope and Bush
spoke for 12 minutes.
   The Vatican previously helped in the return of the body of a
U.S. pilot killed in a U.S. raid on Libya in 1986. The remains of
Maj. Fernando Ribas-Dominicci were turned over to the Vatican's
representative in Tripoli and flown to Italy in January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
