<DOCNO> AP890802-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0945EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     08-02 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Government Says It Will Welcome U.N. Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cambodia-Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a major policy reversal, Prime Minister Hun Sen
of Cambodia said today he has told his Vietnamese-backed government
to welcome a U.N. peace mission to be sent under terms of an
international accord.
   The United States and 18 other nations meeting in Paris agreed
earlier this week to send the investigation team to help prepare
for a permanent peace settlement in war-ravaged Cambodia.
   ``I have already given instructions to give all the assistance
necessary to this technical mission,'' Hun Sen said in a meeting
with reporters at his hotel near the Champs-Elysees.
   At the start of the monthlong international conference on
Cambodia on Sunday, Hun Sen had opposed the United Nations playing
any role in monitoring a peace plan.
   The world body recognizes a coalition of three Cambodian
guerrilla factions as the nation's legitimate representative _ not
Hun Sen's government.
   The Vietnamese invaded Cambodia in 1978, ousting communist Khmer
Rouge rulers and installing the current regime. Renewed civil war
quickly broke out, and the Khmer Rouge are now the strongest
guerrilla force.
   Hun Sen said he changed his mind about the U.N. mission after
receiving assurances from the foreign ministers of Canada and
Australia and U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar that
the visit of the U.N. mission would not imply future U.N.
involvement in peace efforts.
   The U.N. team will present its report to a conference committee
charged with creating a mechanism for monitoring the pullout of
Vietnamese troops.
   Hun Sen has said the Vietnamese forces in his country have
already been reduced to 26,000. Vietnam has said it will pull out
the last of those troops, once estimated at more than 50,000, by
Sept. 27.
   It was still unclear, however, when the U.N. team would leave
for Cambodia and whether the Khmer Rouge would make the
unprecedented gesture of allowing the mission to visit the refugee
camps it controls.
   The Khmer Rouge killed an estimated 1 million people with its
harsh programs after it drove out a U.S.-backed government and took
power in 1975.
   The group's role in a future government has been a sticking
point at the conference.
   Hun Sen says the Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge should be destroyed.
China says the Khmer Rouge should take part in a transitional
government.
</TEXT>
