<FIRST>r a PM-BrooklinevsDukakis     08-02 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brookline vs Dukakis,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Even Dukakis' Hometown is Mad at Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even Gov. Michael Dukakis' hometown
seems to be turning against him as the state grapples with budget
troubles.
   Brookline _ steadfast backers of the Democrat from his days as a
state representative in 1962 through his failed presidential
campaign _ sued the governor today over a plan to cut state aid to
cities and towns.
   The city is accusing Dukakis of using one formula to hand out
state aid and another formula to cut it.
   The change means Brookline faces a cut of $1.9 million in state
aid for schools, police and fire protection instead of the expected
$1.1 million reduction.
   ``To get to the point of where we're actually suing the state or
the governor over his actions is a very painful, emotional step for
me to come to,'' said Selectman Chairman Jeffrey Allen, a longtime
Dukakis backer.
   ``But I think he was wrong and I don't think his actions in
changing the local aid formula are legally defensible.''
   The state's budget troubles _ which many blame on Dukakis _ led
to a $210 million reduction in aid to cities and towns last month.
   John Hanson, an aide to the governor, defended the use of a
different formula to favor poorer communities when cutting grants.
But he added that the governor has yet to decide on whether the
formula will even be used.
   Local aid is distributed by a complicated ``needs basis''
formula; the second formula would make cuts on a per capita basis
instead.
</TEXT>
