<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1006EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 5thLd-Writethru a0530 08-02 0849</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0530,0873</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kiszczak Elected Prime Minister in Communist Party Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Kiszczak's acceptance speech. No
pickup. ^By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament today elected the interior
minister, Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, as prime minister in a victory for
the long-ruling Communist Party, whose power has been eroding.
   In his acceptance speech, Kiszczak pledged to try to bring
members of the Solidarity-led opposition into his new Cabinet. He
asked Solidarity to reverse its position that it will not accept
joint responsibility for governing Poland.
   Although it has rejected joining a coalition government,
Solidarity has not ruled out allowing members to serve in the
Cabinet.
   Kiszczak, the nation's top law enforcement officer, was elected
by Parliament's lower house, the Sejm, by a vote of 237 to 173 with
10 abstentions. The required majority was 211 votes.
   As interior minister, Kiszczak implemented the 1981 martial law
crackdown that suppressed the free trade union movement, but he
also helped initiate this year's campaign that made Solidarity
legal again.
   The vote for prime minister had been postponed Tuesday when some
deputies in the communist-allied Peasant Party sought a government
dominated by lawmakers of the Solidarity independent trade union.
   But after urgent arm-twisting Tuesday night by their party
leadership and Communist officials, most Peasant Party members
ended up voting for Kiszczak, the handpicked candidate of Communist
President Wojciech Jaruzelski.
   ``Looks like they were frightened,'' said Solidarity member Jan
Litynski following the vote.
   Solidarity's floor leader in the Sejm, Bronislaw Geremek, said
in a speech before the vote that his group opposed Kiszczak's
candidacy ``because no personnel reshuffle within the present
political arrangements, dictated by the monopoly of a single party,
can solve the country's problems.''
   In reaching out to the opposition in his acceptance speech,
Kiszczak said that ``in forming the Cabinet on as broad a basis as
possible, I will not give up efforts to attract to it
representatives of opposition circles with a hope that in the
future a grand coalition government will be possible.''
   ``I opt for a government of the roundtable,'' he said in a
reference to the government-opposition talks that led to
Solidarity's legalization this year.
   In his speech carried on Polish television, the new prime
minister also promised ``quick action'' to deal with the country's
economic problems.
   After his election, Kiszczak asked for two weeks to assemble a
Cabinet, which also must be approved by the Sejm. He said he wanted
Deputy Prime Minister Ireneusz Sekula, who handled economic policy
under the outgoing government, to perform the same function in his
Cabinet.
   Jan Bielecki, a Solidarity deputy from Gdansk, said Kiszczak's
government could be one that ``promotes a free market but retains a
strong police.''
   The election completes a two-week reshuffle of the top Polish
leadership.
   Jaruzelski, for eight years the communist first secretary,
assumed Poland's new strong presidency with control of the military
and foreign relations July 19. Outgoing Prime Minister Mieczyslaw
F. Rakowski succeeded him at the helm of the party Saturday. And
now Kiszczak, a Jaruzelski loyalist with his own base in the army
and defense ministries, has become head of government.
   Before Kiszczak was elected, the Communists lost a key
parliamentary vote for the first time in postwar Poland as
Solidarity pushed through a resolution to investigate the outgoing
government for economic misconduct.
   Solidarity believes the outgoing government of Rakowski should
be held accountable for the unraveling of the economy during its
nine months.
   Poland, convulsed by consumer shortages and triple-digit
inflation, suffered further Tuesday when price controls were lifted
on meat, sugar and other basic commodities. Prices rose 43 percent
for most goods.
   The Communist coalition holds a 299-161 majority in the Sejm,
but the Communists have just 173 seats and they had not been sure
they could count on deputies of the allied Peasant and Democratic
parties, which used to obediently follow the Communists.
   According to several deputies, the Peasant caucus leader,
Aleksander Bentkowski, had proposed that they and Solidarity
jointly form a government with a Solidarity prime minister.
   ``We have a general as president. Now they want a general as
premier. And we know they want a Communist to be deputy premier,''
said one Peasant Party member on condition of anonymity. ``What
kind of new government is that supposed to be?''
   Opposition lawmakers entered Parliament after June elections,
the country's freest in four decades, ended the Communists'
monopoly of legislative power.
   The Solidarity victory was so overwhelming _ the movement won
all but one of the seats it was allowed to contest _ that it asked
to be allowed to form the new government, but Jaruzelski rejected
the prospect as unacceptable to East bloc allies.
   Jaruzelski has promised to allow an eventual transition to
complete democracy.
   Kiszczak represented the government in talks with Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa that led to Solidarity's legalization in April
after a seven-year ban.
   Like many leading Communists, Kiszczak failed to be elected a
deputy in the June elections though he ran without opposition. He
needed 50 percent of the vote to win a seat.
</TEXT>
