<FIRST>r a PM-SovereigntyCommission     08-02 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sovereignty Commission,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Records: Businessman Led FBI to Bodies in 1964</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman was the informant who led
FBI agents in 1964 to the graves of three slain civil rights
workers in Philadelphia, Miss., according to files of the state's
old segregation agency.
   The files naming Olen Burrage were obtained by The
Clarion-Ledger. Its account Tuesday represented the first time the
tipster who purportedly led agents to the bodies in an earthen dam
has been publicly identified.
   Burrage on Monday denied any connection with the killings of
James Chaney, Andrew Goodman and Michael Schwerner and denied being
an FBI informant.
   ``I didn't have nothing to do with it,'' Burrage told the
Clarion-Ledger. ``I'm not going to have anything to do with it now.
   The state never charged anyone with the murders, which have
become the focus of renewed attention since being dramatized in the
movie ``Mississippi Burning.'' Several men were convicted of civil
rights violations in the case.
   The 1964 report to Mississippi's now-defunct Sovereignty
Commission said Burrage, on whose land the bodies were found, was
paid $30,000 by the FBI to reveal the location of the graves. The
report was prepared by commission investigator A.L. Hopkins, who
has since died, and quotes an anonymous informant.
   Joe Sullivan, who was the FBI agent in charge of the
investigation, refused to identify the informant who FBI files said
led agents to the bodies. He added in an interview from his New
York City home, ``I didn't pay any money to anybody.''
   Sullivan said a free-lance writer working on the case during the
44 days federal and state officials looked for the three civil
rights workers had offered a reward of $25,000 for information
leading to the bodies.
   The commission, created in 1956 to preserve segregation, became
inactive in 1973 and was disbanded in 1977.
   The Legislature ordered its files sealed for 50 years. U.S.
District Judge William H. Barbour Jr. on Thursday ordered the files
opened to the public, but Barbour stayed his own order pending an
appeal.
   The newspaper said it obtained the report from the personal
papers of the late Gov. Paul B. Johnson Jr.
   Documents that have leaked from the files over the years show
the agency routinely kept files on civil rights activists and
individuals friendly with them.
</TEXT>
