<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Extradition     08-02 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Extradition,0261</SECOND>
<UNK>Virginia Man Extradited but Cannot Face Death Penalty</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd has agreed to
extradite a man wanted in Virginia on murder charges after U.S.
authorities agreed not to try the man for any offense carrying the
death penalty.
   A Home Office statement Tuesday said Jens Soering, 22, a German
national whose father is the West German consul in Detroit, would
face charges of non-capital murder. No date for the extradition was
announced.
   Soering is accused of killing the wealthy parents of his
girlfriend, Elizabeth Haysom. Soering and Miss Haysom were indicted
on murder charges after they had fled to London.
   Miss Haysom, now 24, did not resist extradition from Britain and
was sentenced in October 1987 to 90 years in prison after admitting
being an accessory to the murders.
   Soering resisted extradition and took his case to the European
Court, a branch of the 23-nation Council of Europe to which Britain
belongs.
   The court found last month that extradition would contravene the
Human Rights Convention if there was a risk Soering might be
sentenced to death.
   The court said the convention would not be breached if the
possibility of a death sentence was removed.
   The Home Office said U.S. authorities agreed to drop the
possibility of a death sentence to facilitate extradition.
   The prosecution claims Soering killed his girlfriend's parents,
Derek Haysom, 72, and Nancy, 55, at their home in Lynchburg, Va.,
in March 1985. The two were found stabbed and hacked to death in
their mansion.
</TEXT>
