<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     08-02 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian-Christian Skirmish On Moslem New Year's Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian forces skirmished on
the Moslem New Year today with mortars and automatic rifles,
wounding six people, police said.
   ``There is no celebration mood. Beirut has been largely
demolished and hundreds of innocent people have been killed. Do you
expect anyone to celebrate anything?'' said Sheik Rashid, a Sunni
Moslem clergyman at the Dar al-Fatwa center.
   Four of the casualties were in Christian east Beirut and two
were in the city's western Moslem sector, most of them from sniper
fire, a police spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   By police count, the 5-month-old confrontation between Gen.
Michel Aoun's predominantly Christian soldiers and Syrian forces in
Lebanon has claimed 511 lives and wounded 2,168 people.
   Syrian troops moved into Lebanon in 1976 under a peacekeeping
mandate from the 22-nation Arab League to contain the civil war
which broke out in April 1975.
   The Syrians eventually were drawn into the strife, supporting
the Moslem side against the Christians.
   Ferocious artillery duels betwen Aoun's gunners and the Syrian
army inflicted severe damage on most of Beirut forcing 1.3 million
of its original 1.5 million population to desert the city and seek
refuge in safer areas.
   Dar al-Fatwa, the highest Sunni Moslem religious authority,
called off its traditional New Year reception today because of the
current round of violence.
   Government offices, banks, and other businesses closed in
Beirut's Moslem and Christian sectors to mark the Moslem New Year,
1410.
   The current confrontation broke out March 8, two days after Aoun
blockaded illegal ports run by Syrian-backed militias south of
Beirut for depriving the ailing state treasury of about $100
million annually in lost customs dues.
   The Syrians and their Moslem militia allied forces retaliated by
shelling and besieging the 310-square-mile Christian enclave
northeast of Beirut.
   A three-member Arab League foreign ministers' mediation
committee said Tuesday it has reached an ``impasse'' for which it
blamed Syria.
</TEXT>
