<FIRST>r w PM-US-VonKarajan     08-02 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Von Karajan,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Austrian Conductor Was Under Investigation For Alleged Nazi Past</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department was investigating
allegations that famed Austrian conductor Herbert von Karajan had
been involved in Nazi persecutions, but the probe was dropped when
he died last month, a government lawyer said today.
   The investigation was started several months ago after the
department was informed ``of certain allegations'' about the
conductor, said Neal M. Sher, who heads the Justice Department's
Office of Special Investigations.
   ``We were looking at what his role in Nazi persecution might
have been,'' said Sher, whose office has investigated thousands of
such cases over the years. ``I don't know where the investigation
would have led, but there might have been a question of the
watchlist,'' Sher said, referring to a list of people banned from
the United States for their Nazi pasts.
   Von Karajan, who died of heart failure at the age of 81, was a
member of the Nazi Party and was banned from performing for two
years after World War II ended in 1945. Violent demonstrations were
held during his first U.S. tour in 1954 with the Berlin
Philharmonic, which he conducted for 34 years.
   Von Karajan was born in Austria but moved to Germany in 1934.
His career flourished under the patronage of Hermann Goering, the
field marshal who established the feared Gestapo and was one of
Adolf Hitler's closest aides.
   ``There were allegations that he also worked for the SD,'' the
Nazi security police, Sher said.
   ``There were many questions about him that deserved answers,''
he said. Sher declined to reveal any further information about the
allegations.
   The last prominent person placed on the watchlist was Austrian
President Kurt Waldheim, who was found to have been involved in
atrocities committed by Nazi troops in the Balkans during World War
II.
</TEXT>
