<DOCNO> AP890802-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1131EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia-Movie 1stLd-Writethru   08-02 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-Movie, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0545,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Killing Fields' Movie to be Shown in Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS Schanberg's name in 2nd graf to Sydney, sted Sidney.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Killing Fields,'' the movie that
showed the brutality of Khmer Rouge rule in the 1970s in Cambodia,
will be shown in a Cambodian theater Friday for the first time, the
director said.
   Among those attending the screening will be Sydney Schanberg,
the American journalist depicted in the 1984 Academy Award-winning
film, who will make his first visit to Cambodia since he left there
14 years ago.
   Director Roland Joffe said today it is time to show the film
there because diplomatic events have created optimism that peace
will return to the country.
   ``It is important that Cambodians see this film so that they can
actually feel that there is a chronicle of their own history,'' the
British director told a news conference in Bangkok.
   The showing of the film in the National Theater in Pnomh Penh,
the Cambodian capital, is being organized by Operation California,
a U.S.-based relief agency.
   One of its co-founders, Richard Walden, said the premier of the
Vietnamese-backed government in Cambodia, Hun Sen, gave the
go-ahead in March.
   The film depicts how Schanberg, then a reporter for The New York
Times, and his Cambodian assistant, Dith Pran, were separated as
the Khmer Rouge entered Phnom Penh in April 1975 and began its
fanatical revolution.
   Hundreds of thousands died in torture chambers and slave labor
camps, but Dith Pran made it out in a trek to the Thai border
through fields littered with human bones.
   Vietnamese troops invaded in 1978 and installed a new
government, which is fighting a three-party resistance that
includes the Khmer Rouge.
   Schanberg, who now writes for Newsday, said there was a growing
fear the Khmer Rouge could return to power as Vietnam carries out a
pullout it has promised will be completed by late September.
   That, he said, ``is a pretty horrible and awesome thought.''
   Peace talks in Paris this month are aimed at setting up an
interim government.
   Walden said the film has been available in videocassette in
Phnom Penh but this would be the first screening in a theater and
with official sanction.
   A Cambodian film on the Khmer Rouge rule, ``Shadow of
Darkness,'' also will be shown in the theater on Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
