<FIRST>u i PM-China-Underground     08-02 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Underground,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leading Intellectual Flees China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading intellectual, suspected of acting as
a key link between deposed Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang of
China and that nation's crushed student movement, has escaped to
the West, an activist said today.
   The intellectual, Chen Yizi, fled from China to France several
weeks ago on an ``underground railroad,'' the Hong Kong activist
said. Chen, who is about 50, was director of the Institute of
Restucturing the Economy, an influential think tank when Zhao was
in power.
   While in Paris, Chen participated in meetings to form an
overseas organization to push for democracy in China. However, he
did not meet the press nor was his identity revealed to reporters.
   Indeed, some Western reports said he had been arrested in
Beijing.
   The Hong Kong activist, who demanded anonymity, said Chen
remained in the West but declined to reveal his current
whereabouts. There was no way to immediately confirm the report,
but the activist has been reliable in the past.
   So far, the activist said, about 30 people have fled China via
the ``underground railroad'' set up to help pro-democracy leaders
escape a government crackdown. They include essayist Yan Jiaqi and
student leader Wu'er Kaixi, who were in Paris with Chen but have
since gone to the United States.
   A Western diplomat in Hong Kong has said Communist authorities
apparently wanted to establish direct ties between Chen and Zhao to
prove the purged party leader secretly backed the student movement.
   Chinese authorities began their crackdown on the spring protests
by sending troops into Beijing on June 3-4 to sweep away
demonstrators.
   The official Chinese news agency Xinhua has said nearly 100
soldiers and police died and that thousands were injured, while
about 100 civilians died and nearly 1,000 were injured. Chinese
witnesses and Western intelligence sources said the death toll may
have been as high as 3,000.
   It is unclear to what extent Zhao may have been secretly
supporting the pro-democracy movement. So far, the official charges
against him have been vague.
   Zhao, officially purged after the June 4 crackdown, has been
accused of supporting the movement and ``counterrevolutionary
turmoil.'' However, his specific wrongdoings have not been spelled
out.
   More recently, the state-run media have accused him of
responsibility for high prices and widespread corruption.
   Thousands of students and other supporters of the pro-democracy
movement have been arrested in past months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
