<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1155EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   08-02 0912</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0950</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the country:
   Aug. 1
   The Arizona Daily Star, Tucson, Ariz., on Israel's kidnap of
Sheik Obeid:
   An unnecessary gamble by Israeli security forces has apparently
backfired into a grisly execution. A violent seizure ended in
violent death, if a news report is true, and Israel cannot justify
a means that provokes a tragic end, regardless of the intent.
   The casualty of this risky kidnapping was not just a failed
negotiation, but a human being, Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins, a
man assigned to the United Nations' peacekeeping force in the
region.
   Israelis didn't take Higgins prisoner in February of 1988, nor
did Israelis cruelly string him up and strangle him. Yet Israel has
to bear some of the responsibility for what happened.
   The tactic of kidnapping Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, an influential
Shiite Moslem cleric, was apparently done in hopes of exchanging
three captured Israeli soldiers and other foreign hostages. Obeid
is considered by Israeli officials as a spiritual leader of the
Shiite Moslem Hezbollah militia, an umbrella group for factions
believed to be holding 17 hostages, nine of them Americans. Obeid
is also tied to the Higgins kidnapping. ...
   The risks were tremendous. If the mission had succeeded and the
hostages and soldiers were handed over in return for Obeid,
criticism of Israel would be muted, but it still ought to occur.
The tactic itself is open for judgment.
   Much of the world supports Israel's struggle for survival. But
Israel ought to examine this aspect of its struggle.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 28
   Owatonna (Minn.) People's Press on delaying production of the
B-2 bomber:
   Money for bombers, money for ag research, money for ...
   Based on several decisions reached the past few days, we can't
help but wonder whether the U.S. Senate plans to print its own
money.
   The Senate overwhelmingly agreed to back President Bush's costly
stealth bomber request. The House, on the other hand, decided to
delay production of the B-2 bomber for one year. The majority of
House members considered the $70 million B-2 bomber program too
costly in light of the $150 billion budget deficit.
   We agree with the House.
   Spending more for defense and more for ag research might be OK
if lawmakers were dealing with a balanced budget. But they are not.
   This nation's checkbook is overdrawn. It's been overdrawn for
some time. And it will remain overdrawn if the Senate continues to
spend as though our coffers were flush.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 28
   The Durham (N.C.) Sun on the crash of Flight 232:
   Capt. Al Haynes, the pilot of the United Airlines jet that
crashed July 19 in Sioux City, Iowa, says there is no hero in the
horrifying accident. The 185 people who survived the crash of the
DC-10 may disagree.
   In his first news conference since the crash, Haynes said he
heard a loud noise and began shutting down (the plane's tail
engine) ... A short time later, he said, the crew realized the
plane had lost all its hydraulic fluid.
   When he asked another crew member what the flying procedure for
those circumstances would be, he learned there was none. So the
crew had to develop one as it tried to guide the stricken aircraft
to the Sioux City airport.
   The plane crashed landed just short of the runway, flipped and
broke apart.
   Haynes reminded reporters and others of the 111 people who died
in the crash and the importance of determining the cause and trying
to avoid such disasters in the future. He modestly said the four
crew members just ``did their job.''
   He should also remember that in doing so, they saved 185 lives.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 29
   Ocala (Fla.) Star-Banner on paying for the drug war:
   With (President) Bush insisting he will not approve a tax
increase, finding the kind of money to wipe out or at least
drastically reduce the drug problem and remain within the
Gramm-Rudman budget deficit parameters is certain to pose a
difficult problem for Congress and the administration.
   Comes now U.S. Sen. Bob Graham with a novel way to help pay for
the drug war. Florida's senior member in the upper chamber is
proposing that a modern version of World War I and II war bonds be
sold. ...
   If Graham's proposal fails to win the enthusiastic endorsement
of Congress and the administration, there's no alternative but to
raise taxes to produce the needed revenue.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 31
   The Portsmouth (N.H.) Herald on President Bush's space proposal:
   The president's efforts to restore a sense of mission to
America's space program are certainly long overdue. But is he
serious?
   In calling for the establishment of a space station followed by
manned expeditions to the moon and then to Mars, George Bush
offered not a clue as to how he proposed to pay for any of it.
   Experts differ as to the scientific value of each of those
objectives. But there's no doubt that accomplishing any of them is
going to require a commitment of hundreds of billions of dollars.
As one congressman pointed out, there's no such thing as a free
launch.
   If the president's vague declarations of intent the other day
manage to set off the kind of national debate on our objectives in
space that American leaders have been avoiding for the past 20
years, that will be one small step in the right direction.
</TEXT>
