<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   08-02 0928</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0969</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: right direction.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 1
   Kennebec Journal, Augusta, Maine, on the Bloch spy case.
   We don't have to make a judgment as to (spy suspect Felix S.)
Bloch's guilt or innocence to recognize that this Keystone Kops
surveillance raises civil rights questions: how can he defend
himself against non-existent charges?
   But even granting that Bloch may require close watching, is this
the way to accomplish the task?
   It has been suggested that the FBI was so embarrassed at the way
Edward Howard escaped the country while under the agency's
around-the-clock surveillance, that this time it felt it needed the
media's help.
   Strange stuff, any way you look at it. Even if John le Carre
wrote it, we probably wouldn't believe it.
   Felix Bloch may well be a spy, as the government believes. But
before making an international cause celebre, it would be wise to
collect the evidence first, and make the announcement later.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 31
   Delta Democrat-Times, Greenville, Miss., on the crash of Flight
232:
   Investigators continue to look into the crash of United Flight
232 in Sioux City, Iowa, but we've already learned about the
heroism displayed by many of the people involved. In these times of
contagious cynicism, such actions remind us that humans have a
greater calling.
   The heroism begins with the crew of Flight 232. Only great
courage, skill and decisive action prevented a total disaster, and
saved at least 180 lives ...
   After the flaming crash, passengers selflessly helped one
another out of the rubble. One father rushed to find his baby. He
moved several times toward the infant's cries, only to be driven
back by the smoke. He and the mother later discovered that another
survivor had rescued the baby. ...
   Ministers, priests and rabbis immediately attended the
passengers, blessing and comforting the dying, giving hope to
survivors and rescue workers.
   United Airlines notified relatives, and flew them in to be with
survivors. Local restaurants provided free food to survivors and
rescue workers.
   Flying remains the safest way to travel, but such accidents
remain a risk. Amid the tragedy, they also can give us a glimpse of
what the human spirit can accomplish at its best.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 29
   The Indianapolis Star on names in the abortion issue:
   In a hot controversy, names can mean a lot.
   In the abortion controversy, one side calls itself
``pro-choice'' and the other side calls itself ``pro-life.''
   An Eastern newspaper has issued a rule that its writers ... quit
using the term ``pro-life'' and substitute the grittier term
``anti-abortion.''
   That's one way of giving a new slant to stories about the
abortion controversy.
   But is it nice? Is it courteous? Is it fair? How would the
new-labelers like it if the side that wants to be called
``pro-life'' got even by calling the other side ``pro-death''?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 31
   The Philadelphia Inquirer on Congress and art:
   Members of Congress have found another small item on which to
spend an inordinate amount of time and rhetoric. They have been
waxing apoplectic about $30,000 in federal arts funding for an
exhibit of photographs by the late Robert Mapplethorpe. ...
   Their outrage is understandable. One of the photos was of a man
urinating into another man's mouth.
   A $15,000 grant to photograher Andres Serrano, now notorious for
his shot of a crucifix in urine, is also getting panned.
   All that these politicians needed to say was that some artistic
expressions are so revolting to most Americans that tax dollars are
not going to subsidize them. ...
   But Congress wouldn't leave it at that. The Senate voted last
week to place a five-year ban on federal grants ... while the House
wants to cut overall funding for the arts by $45,000. This amounts
to sophomoric retaliation.
   The (National Endowment for the Arts) has received a strong
message from Congress ... and no doubt will be more careful in what
it approves (for financial support) in the future.
   As House and Senate negotiators talk over the differences, they
should know that the sensible part of Congress' message has already
been sent and that what's left in both bills is a rabid
overreaction.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 30
   Los Angeles Herald Examiner on cutting the capital gains tax:
   Last year, Democrats blasted candidate ... (George) Bush's
ill-advised call for cutting the tax on capital gains, which have
been treated as ordinary income since the passage of federal tax
reform in 1986.
   Supply-side economics argues that ... cutting the capital gains
tax should spur the kind of investment that contributes to the
overall growth of the economy, such as forming pools of venture
capital and modernizing factories.
   However, a lot of capital gains are realized on activities that
contribute nothing more to the economy's productive capacity: sales
of art and antiques; stock and real-estate speculation; and tax
shelters.
   Worst of all, from the standpoint of tax fairness, the primary
capital gains earners already tend to be the wealthiest of the
taxpayers _ the top 5 percent, by most estimates.
   Democratic opposition to the tax cut, however, is now flagging.
... A Democratic ``Gang of Six'' on (the House Ways and Means
Commitee) recently defected. Added to the 13 Republicans supporting
the Bush proposal, those committee members who want to cut the
capital gains tax now comprise a working majority. ...
   The crowning irony here is that the current capital gains deal
now under consideration by the committee, sponsored by a Democrat,
would favor the wealthy even more than the original proposal first
advanced by George Bush.
</TEXT>
