<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   08-02 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: George Bush.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   July 27
   The Greenville (S.C.) News on the crash of Flight 232:
   Alfred C. Haynes, the United Airlines captain, is a reminder
that ordinarily able people are capable of extraordinary competency
and courage. This was an indomitable man at the press conference at
Sioux City, Iowa, a man you'd guess hasn't yet counted his cuts and
bruises, and used a wheelchair only to humor his doctor.
   The mid-air crisis that crippled Captain Haynes' jumbo jetliner
held him and his crew in tortured suspension for nearly an hour.
The challenge to stay aloft, to reach an airport, to attempt a safe
landing, was beyond the imagining of most of us.
   He did it with mental toughness, methodically, calmly, with
knowing trust in his own ability and intuition.
   And he made it all work until seconds before touch down, when
lack of precise control, or perhaps a runway crosswind, dropped one
wing into the ground. The aircraft cartwheeled and the fore and aft
section disintegrated among trailing flames.
   But 185 of Captain Haynes' passengers survived. Air safety
authorities labeled it a heroic and miraculous piloting job. His
own matter-of-fact declaration that there was no hero, only people
doing their jobs, fit him becomingly.
   Not many people are capable, but he gives the impression that
many more could be.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 28
   Daily Record, Morristown, N.J., on a national environmental
policy:
   If President Bush really wants to be the ``environmental
president,'' he could start by developing an environmental policy.
   What we have now is federal regulatory bureaucracy pushing
stringent environmental standards in response to public concern,
while the economic facts of life make meeting those standards near
impossible.
   Mayor John Bullard of New Bedford, Mass., speaking before a
joint session of the environmental and public works subcommittees
on environmental protection, said his city is under court order to
spend $560 million on clean water projects to meet federal
standards.
   Disarray can also be seen in comparing Bush's June 12 clean air
proposal with the administration bill that followed it. Critics
contend the bill falls short of the rhetoric on almost every point.
   We need a national policy that commits us to a goal of reduced
pollution and cleaning up existing pollution. It needs to be
realistic, too, recognizing that while cost of not cleaning the
environment is our eventual destruction, the cost of cleaning up is
no small potatoes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 27
   Times-West Virginian, Fairmont, W.Va., on a Florida rape case:
   Sometimes the system goes haywire.
   Take the case of the Fort Lauderdale woman who was raped and
then jailed because she was reluctant to testify against the
alleged rapist.
   The judge authorized police to take her into custody. She was
apprehended by police, screaming and struggling as three
plainclothes detectives jumped from a car and grabbed her.
   Keep in mind that this was the victim of the crime, not the
suspect.
   The woman thought she was being kidnapped again.
   She spent six days in prison and when she finally appeared
before the circuit judge, he scolded her for ignoring her
``obligation to appear in court.''
   The woman was victimized not only by the rapist, but also by the
system.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   July 30
   The Milwaukee Journal on using aluminum baseball bats:
   The same baseball fans who objected to lights in Wrigley Field,
domed stadiums and artificial turf are sure to get up in arms over
reports that aluminum bats may be introduced into the big leagues.
Aside from whatever value preserving tradition may hold, keeping
metal bats away from major league baseball makes common sense.
   Despite its many changes in recent years, baseball remains
pretty much the same game it has always been. For that reason, fans
can reasonably argue whether Wade Boggs is a better hitter than
Rogers Hornsby was and whether Bob Feller could make it in today's
big leagues.
   But aluminum bats would change the game much more drastically
than even the designated hitter has changed it. Because they have a
larger sweet spot than wooden bats, aluminum bats can turn mediocre
hitters into good ones and good ones into superior ones. Thus,
aluminum bats would change baseball in a fundamental way.
   But they wouldn't improve it. On the contrary, giving hitters
unprecedented new clout would upset the delicate balance between
pitcher and batter that gives baseball some of its drama and makes
it so much fun.
   Aluminum bats don't break, and that makes them suitable for
sandlot leagues, which have to worry about money. But they don't
belong in the senior circuit.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
