<SECOND>PM-Namibia,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Kill Suspected Guerrilla in Namibia, Capture Arms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today shot and killed a black
man during a raid on his house and said the Soviet-made arms they
found there indicate that SWAPO guerrillas are smuggling arms into
Namibia from Angola.
   Kierie du Rand, chief inspector of the South African-ruled
territory, said the suspected guerrilla, Petrus Joseph, was shot in
the northern border town of Rundu when he brandished a pistol while
trying to escape after his arrest.
   Du Rand said police found Soviet-made explosives, a detonator
and a hand grenade in Joseph's home in the town 180 miles northeast
of Windhoek.
   Members of the United Nations contingent monitoring Namibia's
transition to independence could not be located to accompany the
police patrol on its mission, Du Rand said.
   He said the incident proves SWAPO guerrillas are crossing the
border from Angola, where their bases are, to establish arms caches
in northern Namibia and that U.N. troops are unable to monitor the
situation.
   Under a multinational agreement linked to the U.N. independence
plan, SWAPO guerrillas are to remain at bases at least 100 miles
inside Angola or return to Namibia as unarmed civilians.
   Leaders of the South-West Africa People's Organization have
accused the South African-led territorial police of harassing and
intimidating the movement's supporters.
   More than 5,000 U.N. military and police personnel have been
deployed in Namibia to supervise the campaign leading to
pre-independence elections in November. SWAPO, which began a bush
war against South African rule in 1966, is favored to get the most
votes in the election.
