<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-PEN 1stLd-Writethru a0556 08-02 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-PEN, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0556,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rulers Let PEN Club Restart in Prague</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to ADD background on the PEN organization
and background on PEN group in Soviet Union. Pickup graf 14 pvs, `Klima
said...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's hard-line Communist
rulers have allowed the domestic branch of the PEN writers' club to
reopen, and its board will include banned and officially-sanctioned
authors, participants said today.
   Ivan Klima, a dissident writer, said he and about 20 colleagues
gathered Tuesday in Prague and elected a new club governing
committee. He said both he and banned playwright Vaclav Havel are
included in the panel.
   Klima himself was banned after the 1968 reforms known as the
``Prague Spring'' were crushed by a Soviet-led invasion. The Czech
branch of the international writers' club became dormant around
1971 in the wake of broad purges of party members, including many
writers.
   Police detained Havel for about three hours Tuesday but released
him in time to allow him to appear at the end of the meeting, Klima
and another participant said.
   Two members of the human rights group Charter 77, Eva Kanturkova
and Milan Simecka, were summoned to police for questioning to
coincide with Tuesday's meeting, thus preventing their attendance,
Klima said.
   However, the official news agency, CTK, signaled authorities'
approval of the PEN club project by briefly reporting that it was
being formed again.
   Klima said 10 writers were elected to the club's governing
committee, or board of directors: six dissident or non-conformist
writers and four older, officially-backed writers. The CTK report
did not discuss the board's makeup.
   One of the official writers, Jiri Mucha, was elected chairman in
what Klima described as a compromise between the official and
banned writers.
   The efforts to restart the PEN club are the first such joint
initiative in Czech literature in almost 20 years.
   Klima said he saw it as ``a very good sign'' that the club was
permitted to resume activity. He said he hopes it can negotiate
with authorities on publishing previously banned books and lifting
curbs on banned writers.
   Over the past year, authorities have made small shifts toward
liberalizing the arts. Books by Franz Kafka have appeared for only
the second time in 20 years, and a number of previously banned
films, plays and rock bands were allowed to be seen.
   Writers such as Havel, however, have remained banned because of
their refusal to renounce political activities, according to
officials.
   In May, the 60-chapter international PEN association voted
unanimously to admit a Russian chapter, ending a long quarrel with
Moscow.
   Soviet participation in the 10,000-member group has been an
issue ever since PEN _ an acronym for Poets, Playwrights, Editors,
Essayists and Novelists _ turned down an application by the Soviet
state in 1924.
   PEN, which champions freedom of speech for writers, had kept out
the Soviet Union because of its persecution of writers and other
intellectuals.
   Klima said the Czech club will hold its first annual meeting
next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
