<SECOND>AM-Iran,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani to be Sworn in as President Thursday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hashemi Rafsanjani will be sworn in as
the Islamic Republic's fifth president on Thursday, Tehran radio
reported Wednesday.
   The broadcast said Rafsanjani's credentials will be presented in
a ceremony to Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, the incumbent president who
took over as the country's spiritual leader after Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini's death June 3.
   Although Khamenei's second four-year term doesn't expire until
October, he had been expected to step down sooner.
   The state-run radio report, monitored in Cyprus, did not say
whether Thursday's ceremony meant that Rafsanjani would start his
duties as president immediately.
   Rafsanjani, the 54-year-old speaker of parliament, won a
landslide victory in Friday's presidential elections, capturing
94.5 percent of the vote.
   Constitutional reforms approved in a referendum alongside the
election give him considerably enlarged powers by scrapping Prime
Minister Hussein Musavi's post.
   Earlier this week, Khamenei told Musavi to continue his duties
as prime minister until a new cabinet is set up by Rafsanjani.
   Rafsanjani is considered a pragmatist who would like to ease
tight governmental control of the economy, and resume ties with the
West.
   The presidential elections, originally due to be held Aug. 18,
were moved up about three weeks to hasten the transfer of power
after Khomeini's death.
   Khamenei's decision to step down as president before the end of
his term appeared aimed at allowing Rafsanjani move quickly to
start reforming Iran's sluggish economy.
