<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Prices     08-02 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Prices,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poles Horrified By Price Increases; Stores Emptied By Panic Buying</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shops were empty today, the day after the
government introduced a controversial ``marketization'' plan that
raised some food prices by 300 percent by cutting subsidies,
newspapers reported.
   ``The first day after `marketization' was a day of rest for the
sales clerks in the majority of stores,'' reported the opposition
daily Gazeta Wyborcza in an article entitled, ``Much More Expensive
on the Empty Shelves.''
   The government on Tuesday announced the highest official meat
price increases in recent memory and the cost of other key food
items also skyrocketed. Shoppers had stripped shops in late July in
anticipation of the increases and August deliveries have been
meager.
   A report today in Zycie Warszawy, an official daily in the
capital, said sales clerks hoped deliveries would improve in the
next two to three days. But the report added that farmers were
still waiting for higher prices before delivering goods to market.
   ``Where is the meat?'' cried out an old man in a store on
Tuesday.
   ``There is no meat, just the price list,'' a woman complained.
   In a speech to parliament today, to present his economic plan
before he was elected prime minister, Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak said
drastic measures would have to be adopted to prevent the danger of
economic destabilization.
   Solidarity lawmakers charge that the policies of the previous
government of Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski, elected first secretary of
the Communist Party over the weekend, are responsible for the
current economic chaos.
   Authorities said the increases are needed to prompt farmers to
deliver their meat and produce to the market and to stabilize the
level of state subsidies to the food industry.
   Price increases occur regularly in Poland, but the scale of the
latest boost drove many customers to despair. In the past, major
price increases on food have led to rioting in Poland.
   The price of pork roast, an expensive and popular cut, rose from
$1.18 to $4.64 a kilogram (2.2 pounds). Sugar went up from 42 cents
to 60 cents a kilogram, but was unavailable in many shops. Butter
was up from 27 cents for a quarter kilogram to 48 cents. Flour
increased from 7 cents a kilogram to 12 cents. The average monthly
income in Poland is $127.
   Parliament on Monday passed legislation designed to cushion
consumers from the impact of price increases, and inflation now
rising at an estimated 160 percent rate annually.
   The law calls for incomes of workers, farmers and pensioners, to
be automatically conmpensated by 80 percent of the rise in the cost
of living.
</TEXT>
