<FIRST>r a AM-SmokerSuit     08-02 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smoker Suit,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delta Won't Appeal Award To Man Prevented From Smoking On Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASCO, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Airlines won't appeal a $399 award to
Mayor Ed Hendler who complained he wasn't allowed to smoke on a
flight.
   ``We'd basically just like to forget about it,'' Delta spokesman
Jim Lundy in Atlanta said Tuesday. ``It would be more trouble and
more expensive than it's worth to go through the appeal process.''
   Hendler sued Delta after his March flight from Salt Lake City to
Washington, D.C., was declared non-smoking just before takeoff to
accommodate two passengers.
   In small claims court in Pasco last month, Hendler was awarded
the ticket price of $376 and $23 for court costs. Hendler
originally sought three times the ticket price.
   Delta does not fear Hendler's victory will inspire similar
lawsuits, and does not plan to change its policies, Lundy said.
Federal law says airlines must provide ``a sufficient number of
seats in the no-smoking sections of the aircraft for all persons
who wish to be seated there, and expansion of no-smoking areas to
meet demand.''
   About 15 percent of Delta's seats typically are for smokers,
Lundy said. The carrier occasionally cancels smoking sections, but
Hendler was the first to sue, Lundy said.
   Hendler said that if the airline reserves seats for smokers, it
should honor that commitment. ``The principle is breach of
contract. That is the basis of the suit,'' he said.
</TEXT>
