<FIRST>r a PM-BoeingTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0529 08-02 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing Talks, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0529,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing and Largest Union Begin Contract Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with talks under way; PICKS UP
3rd graf pvs, `Aerospace industry ...'; A longer version moving on financial
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co., halfway through a record year,
opened contract talks today with union leaders who say they want a
wage increase to replace all or some of the productivity bonuses of
the past six years.
   Negotiations between Boeing and the Machinists union, which
represents 57,800 workers in Seattle, Wichita, Kan., and Portland,
Ore., began by tradition in Wichita.
   ``All we want is our fair share,'' said Ron Eldridge, a
Machinists business representative in Wichita.
   Aerospace industry analysts say the union is in a strong
position because of a $67 billion backlog of commercial airplane
orders, $346 million in profits in the first half of 1989 and a
shortage of skilled workers that forced Boeing to borrow 600
Lockheed Corp. employees earlier this year.
   Analysts said the chance of a strike is small among Boeing
workers.
   ``This is the opportunity of a lifetime to get all the overtime
they can,'' said William Deatherage, analyst at Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. in New York.
   Union officials say they want a wage increase, likely to be in
the double-digits, to replace all or some of the yearly bonuses
that have ranged from 3 percent to 12 percent since 1983. The
current three-year contract expires Oct. 3.
   Except for welders, the people who make Boeing planes earn $8.88
to $18.42 an hour. The average wage is $13.50 to $14 an hour.
   ``All the signals are that it looks good for us. Boeing can well
afford to pay an increase in wages and increase benefits,'' said
Machinists union District 751 president Tom Baker of Seattle.
   Boeing spokesman Paul Binder refused to comment on the
negotiations.
</TEXT>
