<FIRST>r w AM-Cavazos-Education     08-02 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cavazos-Education,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cavazos Gets Cool Reception from Hawkins on Education Initiatives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary Lauro F. Cavazos got a
cool reception from a House committee chairman Wednesday when he
sought support for proposals emphasizing parental involvement that
he said are needed to revitalize school systems.
   Although initiatives outlined by Cavazos have been embraced in
principle by the Senate education panel and the House
Appropriations Committee, Rep. Augustus F. Hawkins, D-Calif., made
clear he was not impressed.
   Hawkins, chairman of the Education and Labor Committee, told
Cavazos he sees ``some dangerous trends in the proposals being
advocated.''
   For example, he characterized what he called a ``so-called
parental choice'' approach to school selection for their children
as ``a very dangerous idea that has not been fully scrutinized.''
   On the administration proposal to encourage a new category of
magnet schools targeted at school systems with major dropout and
drug abuse problems, Hawkins said that ``takes us far afield from
trying to improve schools for all children rather than a few.''
   ``The selling of choice reminds me of the medicine man selling
snake oil,'' said Hawkins.
   The veteran committee chairman has been a major force in most of
the federal education legislation passed in recent years.
   Cavazos said:
   ``We have been aware of (problems) for a long time, but nothing
has happened. We have got to start changing the system itself. What
I'm trying to do is open up to this nation the whole idea of
restructuring our education system and I think choice is a major
part of that.''
   In his prepared testimony, Cavazos had said, ``The fact that we
now outspend most countries in education does not, in any way, make
up for the fact that when it comes to solid results, our students
and our schools overall simply aren't cutting it.''
   While not disputing committee figures that the federal share of
education spending has dropped from 8 percent to 6 percent over the
past decade, Cavazos said inflation-adjusted spending by all levels
of government is up 26 percent since 1982 _ to $199 billion last
year on elementary and secondary education alone.
   Outlining the federal role as mainly one of stimulating
education approaches with the best chance of working, Cavazos said:
``We have not made progress by putting in more money. We need to
totally change the system. We just cannot go on doing it the way we
are doing it now.''
   Rep. Dale E. Kildee, D-Mich., said he was concerned about many
administration proposals because ``I think what we're talking about
is reversing our commitment to desegregation.''
   While not attacking Cavazos' proposals specifically, Kildee
cited the Senate Judiciary Committee's rejection Tuesday of William
Lucas of Detroit for the top civil rights job at the Justice
Department as the Senate ``reading signs'' in the executive and
judicial branch of a general relaxation of devotion to civil rights.
   ``This a great worry to Congress,'' said Kildee.
   The main program in the proposed legislation that drew Hawkins'
criticism would authorize $100 million a year to promote what
Cavazos called ``open enrollment through parental choice'' as a new
category of magnet schools that would not necessarily be intended
to promote desegregation or attract only top scholars.
   ``Magnet schools work,'' said Cavazos, and ``George Bush and I
want to find ways to expand magnet schools and other examples of
choice all across this country.''
   The legislation also would enable the Education Department to
study other ``choice'' programs and recommend those that work best.
   The secretary complimented Hawkins' home state and said,
``Several models of choice are being implemented in California,
including schools-within-a-school and special schools with a
subject matter focus. Interdistrict choice is allowed if both
school districts involved agree.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
