<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     08-02 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Rebel Goes to India to Work on Sri Lankan Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Tamil rebel leader traveled
to New Delhi on Wednesday to help negotiate an accord on
withdrawing Indian peacekeeping troops from Sri Lanka.
   In New Delhi, a government spokesman said Foreign Minister
Ranjan Wijeratne of Sri Lanka met with Indian Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi for two hours.
   The spokesman said the former Tamil rebel, Vartharaja Perumal,
and five other ethnic Tamils from Sri Lanka would be in New Delhi
on Thursday for consultations but would not take part in the talks.
Perumal is chief minister of the Northeastern Provincial Council in
Sri Lanka.
   On this island off India's southern coast, more ethnic violence
was reported. In central and southern Sri Lanka, Sinhalese
extremists have killed seven people since Tuesday, military sources
said.
   Sinhalese radicals have carried out an anti-India campaign to
protest the presence of about 45,000 Indian peacekeepers in the
Tamil-dominated north and east.
   In Colombo, fire destroyed 25 shops owned by Tamils of Indian
descent, police said. No casualties were reported from the Tuesday
night fire, the cause of which was under investigation.
   Wijeratne and a six-member delegation came to New Delhi on
Saturday to discuss a timetable for the pullout of the troops. They
were deployed under a failed 1987 peace accord sponsored by India.
   India says more power must be transferred to the Tamil-dominated
provincial council to fulfill the terms of the 1987 accord before
its troops leave.
   Sinhalese extremists say the Indian troops have compromised this
country's independence. They also say the government in Colombo has
granted too many concessions to the Tamils.
   The government has blamed the extremists for killing at least
4,000 people, mostly officials of the government and its
supporters. About 11,000 other people have died in the Tamil
insurrection that began in 1983.
   In an effort to quell the violence, President Ranasinghe
Premadasa's government asked India to withdraw its soldiers by July
29.
   On Saturday, India pulled out a small number of troops, and the
two countries agreed to negotiate a withdrawal for the remaining
soldiers.
   The Tamil guerrillas are fighting for an independent homeland in
the north and east.
   India became involved because its own 60 million Tamils are
sympathetic to the demands of Sri Lankan Tamils, who account for 18
percent of this country's 16 million people.
   Tamils contend they are discriminated against in jobs and
education by the Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of the
population and control the government and the military.
</TEXT>
