<FIRST>u a PM-HSN-GTE     08-02 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HSN-GTE,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>GTE Wins $100 Million Libel Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury today ruled that Home Shopping
Network libeled GTE Corp. in blaming the telephone equipment
company for lost sales, and it awarded GTE $100 million.
   HSN had charged that GTE didn't give it adequate equipment to
handle a large volume of calls in 1986 and 1987 as the TV network
expanded into 11 new markets. But the six-member Circuit Court jury
disagreed.
   The jury awarded $50 million each to GTE Florida and GTE
Communications after five hours of deliberations. The jury said $20
million should by paid by HSN and $40 million apiece by its
chairman and its president.
   HSN, which offers items for sale to TV viewers, had sued in
1987, claiming it lost millions of telephone calls and about $500
million in potential sales because its GTE equipment was
insufficient for the volume of calls.
   GETE, based in Stamford, Conn., countered with a slander and
libel suit blaming HSN's troubles on its own mismanagement.
   GTE lawyer Roy Reardon said HSN had failed to mention its plans
to buy 11 UHF stations in 1986, which, combined with its entry into
the cable TV market, caused subscribers to soar from 9 million to
46.5 million in one year.
   Competition from similar retailers also hurt HSN, Reardon said.
</TEXT>
