<SECOND>AM-Italy-Beaches,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Approves Funds for Adriatic Beaches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament on Wednesday approved $1 billion in
emergency funds to battle algae that is fouling beaches on the
Adriatic coast and driving tourists away.
   Part of the money will be used to build water purifiers and
sewage treatment plants along the coast and to reduce the amount of
agricultural pollutants coming from the Po River.
   The decree, approved by the Senate earlier this month, passed
the Chamber of Deputies by a 320-19 vote, with 17 legislators
abstaining.
   The algae has dealt a serious blow to the Adriatic tourism
industry, creating a dirty sea and deserted beaches. The Federation
of Italian Hotel and Tour Operators has predicted that the 1989
season's losses could total $197 million and the number of tourists
could fall 30 percent from last summer.
   The enviromentalist Greens Party voted against the decree,
criticizing the funds as insufficient.
