<FIRST>r a AM-People-Joel     08-02 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Joel,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Billy Joel Talks Shop With Music Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock star Billy Joel says he no longer cares for
his early 1970s cult hit ``Captain Jack'' or his popular song ``My
Life,'' which he describes as childishly redundant.
   ``My Life'' is ``a song that turned out sour for me ... just
like some of your kids turn into bums,'' he told a master class at
the Performing Arts Center of Long Island University's Southampton
campus on Monday.
   ``Captain Jack,'' a song about adolescent drug abuse, ``kind of
burned me out quick,'' he added.
   The master class was open to the public and included Art
Garfunkel. Joel made it clear his professional career, not his
private life, was the topic of the day.
   ``Usually, somebody wants to know, `What does Christie look like
in the morning?''' he said, referring to his wife, model Christie
Brinkley. ``She looks good, so let's get that out of the way.''
   Joel said he writes his music first, composing the melody to
what he called ``bail-out lyrics'' that establish a song's phrasing.
   As he was working on the first verse of ``Just the Way You
Are,'' he said, the lyrics went:
   ``Don't be crazy, don't be lazy
   Don't bring me chicken soup alone.
   I'm not hungry, I'm not thirsty...''
   Later, when he wrote the real words, Joel said, he thought the
phrase ``What will it take 'til you believe in me _ The way that I
believe in you'' was essential to its success.
   ``That edge of anxiety made it a more meaningful song,'' he said.
   Joel, who signed a contract as a young musician that gave away
his rights to his early songs, said his advice to newcomers to the
field was ``to get a lawyer.''
   ``Then I'd tell them to hire another lawyer to watch the first
lawyer.
   ``There's a great deal of dishonesty and greed, and musicians
tend to be naive about this business,'' he said.
</TEXT>
