<FIRST>r a AM-People     08-02 0872</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0904</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rob Lowe's insurance company says the actor's
liability insurance doesn't cover sex tapes.
   Chubb Custom Insurance Co. of New Jersey filed papers in U.S.
District Court this week asking a judge to free it of any
obligation for claims in the lawsuit over Lowe's alleged
videotaping of a sex act involving a teen-age girl.
   Lowe is being sued by Lena A. Wilson of Marietta for allegedly
videotaping her daughter, Jan Parsons, then 16, in a sex act with
another female while Lowe was in Atlanta for the 1988 Democratic
Convention.
   Court documents indicated Lowe wrote Chubb on June 7 claiming
his $300,000 personal liability insurance policy requires the
company to ``provide a defense and to pay any judgment which might
be returned'' against him.
   Lowe, star of several movies including ``St. Elmo's Fire,'' was
covered for any bodily injury he caused another person and any
damages as a result of any injury, but not ``damage which is either
expected or intended,'' the company said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Malcolm S. Forbes, publisher, motorcycle maven
and hot-air balloonist, plans to launch a magazine aimed at
``zestfully awake'' people who live in big cities.
   The takeoff of Egg is set for spring, Forbes announced Tuesday.
   ``Symbolically,'' said Forbes, chairman of Forbes Inc., ``the
egg is the source of everything new.''
   ``Part of the essential nature of the magazine is going to be
the thrill of discovery,'' he said. ``Psychologically, you can
never be sure what's inside an egg. You have to open it. It might
be a Faberge egg.''
   Forbes is a collector of Faberge eggs.
   Egg is to appear 10 times a year and cover music, film, theater,
fashion, design, celebrities, society, food, wines and nightlife.
   It will be ``about the vibrant culture of those alive to the fun
of being alive,'' said Forbes.
   Hal Rubenstein, a regular contributor to magazines including
Details, 7 Days, Elle and The New Yorker, has been named editor of
Egg, Forbes said.
   Forbes' youngest son, Timothy, will be president of Egg. He is
president of American Heritage, another magazine published by the
company best known for its business biweekly, Forbes magazine.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AMARILLO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Cosby has accepted an invitation to
perform a benefit concert for a new elementary school this
Panhandle city feared it couldn't afford.
   Oilman T. Boone Pickens said his wife, Bea, got the idea to
invite Cosby when his company was trying to find ways to fund the
``magnet'' school, which would aid integration using computer
programs to attract pupils to a mostly black neighborhood.
   ``He's well-known for his generosity, and he said he'd be glad
to help,'' Pickens said. ``We're glad we could be a part of it.''
   The concert will be Oct. 16 at the Amarillo Civic Center
Coliseum and all proceeds will go to the new elementary school.
   Plans to establish the school in a refurbished former high
school building had been scrapped as officials struggled to make up
a $5 million budget deficit. But Pickens' company announced it
would fund up to half of the school's cost for the first two years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLARKSTON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recent Rod Stewart and Beach
Boys-Chicago concerts drew overflow crowds to the 10,000-seat lawn
of the Pine Knob Music Theater, to the dismay of fans who got
jostled and had drinks spilled on them.
   ``We made a mistake, we oversold it and we shouldn't have done
it ... and we're sorry,'' Pine Knob operator Joseph Nederlander
said Tuesday.
   He said lawn seats were oversold to the tune of 1,500 to 2,000
spaces at each of the concerts last month. Pine Knob has been
selling as many lawn tickets as possible because of economic
pressures from other Detroit-area concert venues such as the
Palace, Joe Louis Arena and Meadow Brook, he said.
   Some of the patrons at the oversold shows reported receiving
refunds.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hedda Nussbaum, the battered woman known for her
testimony at the televised Joel Steinberg murder trial, will
display her photographs at a gallery this month in what her
psychiatrist calls ``a return to her identity.''
   Her 12 black-and-white nature photographs will be exhibited in
Sag Harbor on Long Island and will sell for $125 to $275. Ms.
Nussbaum calls the collection, including photos of a soft, white
rose and a rabbit, ``Signs of Life.''
   She and Steinberg were arrested in November 1986 in the beating
death of the 6-year-old girl they had raised in their Manhattan
home. Charges were dropped against Ms. Nussbaum, herself a beating
victim, but Steinberg was sentenced to up to 25 years in prison for
first-degree manslaughter.
   Samuel Klagsbrun, her psychiatrist at Four Winds Hospital, said
Ms. Nussbaum's ``artistic side began years ago when she wrote
children's stories. What happened is that during the worst time of
her life _ during her relationship with Joel Steinberg _ that part
of her life was squashed. This is a return to her identity.''
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, took the picures during the 18 months she was
in rehabilitation at Four Winds. She now lives a quiet life in
upstate New York. She works at home, developing her own prints.
</TEXT>
