<FIRST>r a AM-FiresRdp     08-02 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fires Rdp,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wildfires Threaten Idaho Hamlets, Burn 215,000 Acres in West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB FICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flames pushed within 300 yards of the rustic
Sourdough Lodge and theatened two Idaho hamlets Wednesday, but
cooler weather was turning the tide against some of the wildfires
buring in five western states.
   ``It all depends on the wind,'' said Sourdough owner Bob Ahern,
who refused to leave his inn outside Lowman. ``If we don't get any
wind, we could walk away from this thing heads high. If the wind
changes, my friend, this is going to be one big black hole.''
   Wildfires have consumed more than 215,000 acres _ or 335 square
miles _ of timber, brush and grassland in the West since the middle
of last week, according to the Boise Interagency Fire Center, the
government's wildfire command post. Most were ignited by lightning.
   Big fires continued to burn Wednesday in Idaho and Oregon, while
smaller blazes were fought in California, Montana and Washington.
   In Idaho and Oregon, moist, cool air slowed the flames' advance.
   ``Those conditions really help suppression,'' Boise National
Forest spokeswoman Lynette Davis said. ``But then its supposed to
get hotter again by the weekend so we've got to get something done
before then.''
   More than 15,000 firefighters were on the lines throughout the
West, and reinforcements continued to arrive from outside the
region and from the military.
   Fifteen buses carrying 500 soldiers left the Army's Fort Lewis
on Wesdnesday to join the battle in eastern Oregon. The soldiers,
who got a crash course in fire safety, were to be joined by 500
more troops Thursday, said Capt. Don Herzog, spokesman for the fort
south of Tacoma, Wash.
   In Idaho, where 94,000 acres of timber and range have burned,
crews had to concentrate on protecting structures scattered
throughout the Boise, Payette and Nez Perce national forests rather
than on containing the flames.
   ``They save the structures first and fight the fires second,''
Ms. Davis said.
   Air tankers were dumping flame-retardant chemicals at a rate of
one-quarter of a million gallons of retardant a day on the most
stubborn of the blazes.
   Lowman, population 15, was largely leveled by flames over the
weekend, and shifting winds Wednesday renewed the threat to cabins
scattered near the town 70 miles northeast of Boise.
   Ahern at the Sourdough Lodge was one of the few to ignore the
Forest Service advice to leave. Fire crews poured so much soap-like
foam on the building that it took on a mid-winter snowy look. Even
the tops of the surrounding firs were white.
   The fire was so hot it melted asphalt on the highway, Idaho 21,
east and west of Lowman.
   Fire also neared the small mining town of Warren, 120 miles
north of Boise, where 16 of the 36 residents fled and the rest
prepared to move to an open area if the threat increased.
   Hundreds of firefighters ringed the town with 1,000 feet of
hose, putting sprinklers on each building as wind sent the fire
racing to within a mile of the buildings.
   The situation Wednesday elsewhere in the West:
   _ In eastern Oregon, where 85,000 acres have been blackened,
cool weather gave firefighters hope they could turn back several
big timber and range blazes, said U.S. Forest Service spokeswoman
Wendy Evans in Portland.
   Several smaller blazes were contained, and the spread of the
bigger fires around the towns of John Day, Baker and Enterprise had
stopped, she said.
   _ In California, a brush fire in the Cleveland National Forest
that has blackened 8,200 acres destroyed a house and a mobile home
was 50 percent contained Wednesday. More than 1,300 firefighters
supperted by air tankers and helicopters struggled in sporadic wind
and tough terrain to contain the blaze 90 miles southeast of Los
Angeles.
   In the Sierra Nevada foothills in central California, 3,000-acre
fire burned out of control in grass and brush, but didn't pose a
theat to structures.
   _ In Montana, firefighters were close to containing an 800-acre
grass and timber fire in the Custer National Forest. About 300
firefighters were working to cut lines around the blaze in the
southeastern corner of the state.
   _ In Washington, firefighters were mopping up the 850-acre
Lodgepole fire in the North Cascades near the Canadian border.
</TEXT>
