<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1504EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChineseOpera     08-02 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chinese Opera,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arts Director Says Eight Chinese Performers Will Not Seek Political
Asylum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of a Chinese-American arts
organization in New York City said Wednesday that none of the eight
Chinese opera performers who vanished last week plans to apply for
political asylum.
   The entertainers are ``scared to death'' by the publicity their
disappearance has caused, said Alan Chow, executive director of the
Chinese American Arts Council.
   The fate of the entertainers, including seven opera stars and a
popular actor, has been unknown since the group fled the 28-member
Kun Opera company last week.
   Immigration officials in San Francisco said Wednesday they had
no connect with the performers.
   Chow, who would say only that he has ``some connection'' with
the performers, reported that four remained in San Francisco, two
are in New York City and two are in Washingon, D.C.
   All are staying with relatives or friends, said Chow, adding
that he was uncertain whether the performers had planned to flee
the opera group or acted spontaneously.
   Observers have speculated that the eight might be seeking
democratic and economic freedoms in the wake of the student-led
pro-democracy movement in China this spring.
   But Chow insisted that the artists will not seek asylum. It has
been common for performers from China, Hong Kong and Taiwan to
arrive in the United States with a working visa and then apply for
a student visa to enable them to study in this country, he said.
   ``Those things always happen,'' said Chow. ``It's not too hard
to change their visa to a student visa in a regular case. Now it's
very bad.''
   The performers did not know the risk they faced in seeking such
a change following the government crackdown on the student
movement, Chow said. ``Now they found out and they're scared to
death.''
   Chow met the entertainers when they performed in New York last
month.
   Now, he is worried for their safety. ``It's a very bad position
if you just disappear. This timing is not right. You hurt not only
yourself, you hurt China.''
</TEXT>
