<FIRST>r p AM-Pepper'sSeat     08-02 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepper's Seat,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Nominee Wins Landslide; Tense Democrats In Runoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Party leaders rallied Wednesday around
their landslide nominee to succeed the late U.S. Rep. Claude
Pepper, while two Democrats began a tense runoff campaign.
   The winner in the GOP primary Tuesday, state Sen. Ileana
Ros-Lehtinen, was born in Cuba, a significant factor in a city
where politics, often is influenced by tensions among whites,
blacks and mostly Cuban-born Hispanics.
   Many look to the special vote to fill the 18th District seat as
a chance to elect the first Cuban-born member of Congress.
   On the Democratic side, attorney Gerald Richman claimed he had
momentum and his opponent, former Miami City Commissioner Rosario
Kennedy, was suffering backlash from negative campaigning as they
headed to an Aug. 15 runoff.
   Richman finished 146 votes ahead of Ms. Kennedy in Tuesday's
primary, with Pepper's niece, Jo Ann Pepper, third in the
seven-candidate field.
   Ms. Kennedy's supporters said nominating another Cuban-born
woman to oppose Ms. Ros-Lehtinen would negate ethnic factors. But
Richman called the 18th District ``an American seat'' and said he
could unite the multi-ethnic community.
   Pepper, a liberal champion of the elderly and poor who held the
seat for the Democrats since 1962, died May 30 at age 88.
   Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, who won the GOP nomination with 83 percent of
the vote, welcomed Republican Party help campaigning for the Aug.
29 special election. Vice President Dan Quayle headlined a luncheon
Wednesday to benefit her and other state Republican candidates.
Republicans are hoping to add to their unprecedented 10-8 majority
in Florida's congressional delegation.
   ``We're going to go all out,'' said state Republican Party
Chairman Van Poole. ``We have the better candidate and we're
unified.''
   Jeb Bush, the president's son, was at her victory party Tuesday
night, and U.S. Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., telephoned
congratulations.
   ``I'm particularly grateful that the primary campaign was one
that did not open wounds among Republicans,'' said Guy Vander Jagt,
chairman of the National Republican Congressional Committee.
   ``I think the bloody fight is going to be between the Democrats.
We're sailing on,'' said Ms. Ros-Lehtinen, a 37-year-old educator
with seven years in Florida's Legislature. She's married to U.S.
Attorney Dexter Lehtinen.
   Richman, 48, and Ms. Kennedy, 44, were already arguing early
Wednesday over whose campaign was ethnically divisive.
   Richman took Ms. Kennedy to task for agreeing with Republican
National Committee Chairman Lee Atwater's remark that it was time
to elect a Cuban-American to Congress.
   Ms. Kennedy said Richman was taking her remark _ she said ``I am
that Cuban-American'' _ out of context.
   ``He (Richman) was there when I said it,'' she said. ``I meant
it as Republican vs. Democrat. I am a Cuban-American. I'm also a
woman. And I have represented all of the people of the City of
Miami.''
   Richman was angered by late Kennedy mailings that attacked him
for representing an international arms dealer, Sarkis Soghanalian,
who was charged with illegally conspiring to smuggle combat
helicopters to Iraq. Richman called Soghanalian a patriot who
helped U.S. causes.
   ``There has been some nasty negative campaigning that had me
extremely upset,'' Richman said.
   Ms. Pepper, also attacked in Kennedy campaign mailings, hadn't
announced a decision Wednesday on whether she would back Richman.
   In unofficial returns from all 146 precincts, Ms. Ros-Lehtinen
had 83 percent of the Republican vote; fellow Cuban-American Carlos
Perez, 57, had 11 percent; insurance broker David Fleischer, 54,
had 3 percent, and evangelist John Stembridge, 51, had 3 percent.
   For the Democrats, Richman had 28 percent of the vote, Ms.
Kennedy had 27 percent, and Ms. Pepper, 39, had 24 percent.
   Far out of the running were professor Marvin Dunn, 48, and real
estate agent Sonny Wright, 54, and businessman Bernard Anscher, 67,
and striking Eastern Airlines pilot John Paul Rosser.
</TEXT>
