<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     08-02 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq Calls for Arab Summit on Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq on Wednesday called for an emergency
Arab summit to find a solution to Lebanon's war after a committee
appointed to do so declared itself at an impasse.
   Eight people were wounded in the latest Syrian-Christian
fighting.
   Police said occasional bursts of machine-gun fire and mortar
explosions echoed on both sides of the Green Line, which divides
the capital into Moslem and Christian sectors.
   The skirmishes were much lighter than confrontations have been
in the past week and coincided with the Moslem new year, an
official holiday throughout Lebanon.
   Government offices, banks and other businesses closed in Moslem
and Christian sectors to mark the day, but there was little revelry.
   ``There is no celebration mood,'' said Sheik Rashid Anouti, a
Sunni Moslem clergyman. ``Beirut has been largely demolished and
hundreds of innocent people have been killed. Do you expect anyone
to celebrate anything?''
   According to police figures, 511 people have died and 2,170 have
been wounded in the latest round of fighting, which broke out March
8 between Gen. Michel Aoun's 20,000 mainly Christian troops and
Syrian soldiers and their Moslem allies.
   Many city streets have been reduced to rubble, and hundreds of
thousands of residents have fled.
   A three-member Arab ministerial committee, trying more than two
months to solve Lebanon's crisis, said Tuesday it reached an
impasse and blamed Syria, which keeps about 40,000 troops in
Lebanon under an Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   During an Arab League summit in May, King Hassan II of Morocco,
King Fahd of Saudi Arabia and Algerian President Chadli Benjedid
were asked to find a settlement by November to the war.
   At the summit, Syria blocked proposals to replace its troops
with a pan-Arab force.
   The leftist daily newspaper As-Safir, which is close to the
Syrian government of President Hafez Assad, described the
committee's report as ``very serious because it reflected a hostile
attitude toward Syria.''
   Farouq Abillama, an aide to Aoun, described the committee's
report as an ``indictment of the Syrian presence in Lebanon.''
   Aoun, a Maronite Catholic, has declared a ``war of liberation''
against Syria's troops in Lebanon. He said they undermined their
peacekeeping mandate by fighting on the Moslem side.
   Iraqi Foreign Minister Tareq Aziz told the official Iraqi News
Agency that an urgent session of the Arab summit was necessary to
solve the crisis.
   ``An emergency Arab summit bears the responsibility of dealing
with the situation in Lebanon and saving this Arab country from
occupation, terrorism, and blackmail,'' said Aziz, who is also
deputy prime minister.
   Syria is Iraq's main Arab foe and considers Lebanon within its
sphere of influence. It has refused to lift a blockade on Lebanon's
Christian enclave until it receives assurances Iraq has stopped
sending arms to Aoun's troops.
   Aziz called for a collective Arab stand against Syria and said
the Arabs should identify Syria as ``a major cause behind Lebanon's
civl war.'' He reiterated Iraq's demand for an immediate Syrian
withdrawal from Lebanon.
</TEXT>
