<FIRST>u w AM-Food-GarbageTrucks     08-02 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Food-Garbage Trucks,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Truckers Say Refrigerated Food Trucks Also Carry Garbage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Truckers testifying behind a screen to conceal
their identities told a House panel Wednesday that they carried
garbage in the same refrigerated trucks used for food hauls, a
legal practice a lawmaker called ``more than disgusting.''
   ``Would you serve potato salad from your cat's litter box?''
Penn State University food science professor Manfred Kroger
rhetorically asked a House Public Works and Transportation
subcommittee during an all-day hearing.
   The investigations subcommittee released correspondence showing
that Campbell Soup Co., Geo. A. Hormel &amp; Co., Michigan Sugar Co.,
and other food manufacturers had taken steps in the last two months
to ensure that their products were not placed in the same trailers
that hauled waste to landfills.
   None of the food firms said it knew of such a practice, but all
said they wanted to safeguard against it.
   The Food and Drug Administration said an investigation had found
no contaminated food.
   The vice president and driver for a small, family-owned trucking
firm specializing in hauling meat products from the Midwest to the
East told the subcommittee food-garbage hauling appeared widespread.
   ``Of the ten largest carriers in my area that haul refrigerated
food products to the East Coast, six of them I know have loaded it
(garbage),'' he said.
   A woman trucker told the panel her firm hauled two loads of
garbage on return trips by food trucks to the Midwest. She said she
refused other loads because ``I just didn't want to put it in the
trucks.''
   Both truckers who testified were hidden by a partition on three
sides because they did not want their identities made public,
according to the committee, which also would not divulge their home
states.
   Part of the problem is that trucks making trips East cannot
afford to return to the Midwest empty, the male trucker said. He
said garbage is ``a dream commodity'' to return home with because
``you're not responsible for anything. How could you destroy it?''
   Still, he said he felt there could be sanitary problems, even
though his trucks are steam-cleaned. ``I'm not a bacteriologist,''
he said.
   He said his meat-hauling trucks used to carry bales of waste to
a landfill near Youngstown, Ohio, but stopped in June at the
request of customers.
   The Interstate Commerce Commission in an inquiry last month
confirmed the practice of food trucks carrying garbage, according
to testimony.
   In one instance, a food truck emptied at an Ohio landfill
``emanated powerful garbage odors'' despite just being washed, said
Bernard Gaillard, director of the ICC's Office of Compliance and
Consumer Assistance.
   Before the garbage haul, the truck had carried avocadoes from
California to New York City, Gaillard said.
   Rep. William Clinger, R-Pa., organized the hearing after a
Centre Daily Times newspaper reporter in his district observed
trailers and refrigerator trucks in May either carrying or being
loaded with municipal solid waste at a transfer station, and being
unloaded at an Ohio landfill.
   ``The idea of garbage being hauled in food trucks seems more
than disgusting,'' Clinger said Wednesday. ``It seems dangerous.''
He said a new law was needed because existing regulations are
ambiguous.
   The American Trucking Association, a trade group, said in a
written statement that, ``It would seem appropriate to ATA to
require that trailers be properly cleaned _ by steam or other
effective process _ before they leave a landfill site.''
   Refrigerator trailers, with their ribbed, stainless-steel
floors, normally carry meat, poultry, dairy products, fresh fruits
and vegetables to market.
   Penn State's Kroger said there were chemical and microbiological
arguments against food-garbage hauling.
   ``Food trucks that back up into filthy dump sites presumably can
easily be infected all over and later spread disease-causing
bacteria into the truck bodies and into food factories during
loading,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
