<FIRST>r a AM-NunReleased     08-02 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nun Released,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Nun Shot in El Salvador to be Released from Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors are amazed at the quick recovery of a
73-year-old American nun who was seriously wounded when she was
shot in the head during an apparent robbery attempt in El Salvador
six weeks ago.
   Sister Mary Stanislaus Mackey, a member of the Sisters of
Charity of the Incarnate Word, will be moved to a Houston convent
this week to continue her recuperation, doctors at Houston's St.
Joseph Hospital said Tuesday.
   ``I think the outcome approaches miracle stage when one
considers she was shot in the head at close range with a
large-caliber handgun,'' Rob Parrish, the nun's neurosurgeon, said.
   `Sister Stan,' as she is called, was hit by a .38-caliber bullet
June 21 as she and two other nuns rode in a pickup truck in
Zaragoza, El Salvador. The sisters are unsure of the motive for the
attack, but speculate the gunman, one of several men in a pickup
truck, wanted to rob the nuns, who had just been to a bank.
   Sister Mackey worked in the town 10 miles south of San Salvador
in an orphanage for children whose parents have been killed in the
nine-year civil war between leftist guerrillas and the government.
   The bullet shattered her cheekbone. After initial treatment in
San Salvador, she was flown to Houston, where her religious order
is based.
   Doctors operated June 26 to remove a bullet fragment lodged in
her brain and to relieve swelling in her brain. A second operation
was performed July 8 to reattach the retina in her left eye.
   ``There appears to have been some damage to her optic nerve and
we're not sure how much sight she will recover in her left eye,''
Dr. James Baker said.
   Sister Mackey, accompanied by a nurse and using a cane for
support, read a brief prepared statement at a news conference
Tuesday but declined to take questions.
   ``I want to thank everyone for their interest and their
prayers,'' she said. ``God has taken me completely into His hands,
and I thank everybody who has played a part in my recovery. I
especially appreciate the good work of my doctors, the nurses,
priests, bishops and the sisters of the congregation.''
   Baker said he anticipated no long-term problems with motor
functions although she had some problems with short-term memory.
   Five or six men accused of the shooting were taken into custody
within the past week, said Sister Ann Mary Brangan, one of the
other nuns in the pickup truck, but she has been unable to identify
them for police.
   Sister Mackey, a registered nurse, had worked in Central America
since 1963 and in El Salvador since 1983.
</TEXT>
