<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 2042EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Drought     08-02 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dryness in Some Regions Continues Pattern of the Decade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It may surprise some soggy Easterners, but
drought _ the big 1988 weather story now getting little national
attention _ is still a hot item in parts of America.
   True, the East and South which baked a year ago are now stuck in
a summer of excessive wetness. But the Southwest, relatively moist
in the summer of 1988, is parched this year.
   And parts of the Corn Belt in the nation's middle, as well as
sections of California, have been dry in both summers.
   The Western and Midwestern dryness this summer continues a
pattern of the decade, which have seen serious regional drought
somewhere in the United States every year except 1982.
   More than half of the nation is undergoing either severely dry
or excessively wet conditions, an indication that the upper air
flow patterns are allowing conditions to remain in place for long
periods, federal climate researchers report.
   The 30-day outlook for August contains some hope for the
Southwest, although the heavier than normal rainfall expected this
month isn't likely to continue over the upcoming 90 days, the
federal Climate Analysis Center reports.
   As for California, dryer than normal conditions are forecast in
August with the outlook mixed over the three-month span.
   Even so it isn't as bad as last summer, one of the driest years
overall in this century.
   In June, for example, the U.S. Geological Survey found 27
percent of the nation's streams and rivers running below normal. In
June 1988, some 60 percent of rivers and streams were below normal.
   A compromise disaster-relief proposal seems near in the Senate
as members of Congress seek to help farmers cope with the
crop-wilting weather in some areas and drowned fields in other
regions.
   From May 1 to mid-July less than half of the normal rain fell in
Arizona, New Mexico and parts of Texas, California, Colorado,
Nevada, Oregon, Idaho, Wyoming, Montana, the Dakotas, Nebraska,
Wisconsin, Illinois and along the eastern edge of Florida.
   The excessive heat and dryness in the West has contributed to
the extreme fire danger in many areas, with dangerous blazes raging
in Idaho, Oregon, California and other regions.
   In the Midwestern farm belt, crops are suffering not only by
lack of rain this year but with lack of soil moisture due to last
year's drought. Corn, soybean and grain crops are affected, among
others.
   Some recent rains have helped the topsoil, but so far have been
too light to improve moisture conditions below the surface.
   ``Since May 1, below normal rainfall has persisted from southern
California northeastward to the upper Plains and Illinois. In
extreme southern Minnesota, eastern Iowa and western Illinois,
deficits exceed 10 inches,'' the Climate Analysis Center reports.
   June, normally the wettest month in the Midwest, saw only 60
percent of normal rainfall in parts of Illinois, Minnesota and Iowa.
   The Army Corps of Engineers has had to release impounded water
to maintain navigation on parts of the Missouri River, and sections
of the Mississippi are carrying only about one-third of the usual
flow for this time of year.
   Meantime, the Southeast was drenched with rains spawned by
tropical storm Allison in late June and early July, the wetness
extending as far as the Middle Atlantic states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 2044EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     08-02 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official: Communists Could Enact Own Multiparty Law Without Opposition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior communist official indicated
Wednesday that his party could enact its own legislation on
political reform if talks founder with the opposition, but a
communist negotiator urged patience.
   The comment by Deputy Justice Minister Geza Kilenyi came hours
after members of the opposition accused the ruling communists of
dragging their feet in negotiations that broke down last week.
   The negotiations broke down over the wording of a new
constitution, a new party law, party finances and the office of a
new president with wide powers. The first multiparty elections in
Hungary since the 1948 communist takeover are slated to be held
next year.
   Kilenyi indicated legislative measures already drawn up by the
communists, but tabled for review in talks with the opposition,
could be considered in Parliament without discussion if the
negotiations remain inconclusive.
   ``If there is no suitable progress made, we will simply take
those items of draft legislation and put them back on the table
again in Parliament,'' he said.
   Kilenyi criticized the Opposition Round Table, which includes
nine opposition groups, for what he called their inflexibility.
   But Central Committee secretary Gyerogy Fejti, a leading
communist negotiator, said he still seeks an agreement.
   ``It does not help the achievement of a compromise if differing
views are made public too early,'' Fejti said. ``Compromise
requires an atmosphere of patience and calm.''
   Imre Pozsgay, a top reformer on the Executive Political
Committee (Politburo), has promised an agreement regardless of how
long it takes.
   At an earlier news conference, Janos Kis of the League of Free
Democrats alleged the Hungarian Socialist Workers (Communist) Party
``is trying to suggest to the nation that the choice is between
that party and chaos.''
   Peter Toelgyessy of the League of Free Democrats said the
communists want to retain in the constitution the paragraph on the
working class as the leading social force in the nation ``and other
such holdovers from the present constitution based on the Stalinist
model.''
   He said the communists want ``to use the constitutional state as
a smokescreen and continue business as usual under the same
management.''
   The opposition groups disagree on the need to have a law on
parties, contending that the existing law on association is
sufficient and only a law on party financing and operation is
needed.
   A major obstacle in the talks is whether the wealth of the
communist party should be distributed to other groups.
   On July 27, the communists, who had been amenable to discussing
the issue, reversed their position. They said the party acquired
its assets legally and that distribution of the money is an
internal party affair.
   On Wednesday, Fejti sidestepped a question on his party's
financial holdings.
   There is also disagreement on who may field candidates in first
multi-party elections next year and how many signatures will be
required to get on the ballot and where and how such signatures may
be collected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
