<FIRST>r w AM-FactoryOrders     08-02 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Factory Orders,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Orders Rebound in June</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders for manufactured goods edged up a
slight 0.4 percent in June, reflecting a rebound in demand for
military hardware, the government said Wednesday.
   The Commerce Department said new orders for manufactured goods
totaled a seasonally adjusted $234.6 billion in June following a
sharp 2.6 percent plunge in May.
   Many analysts said they were unimpressed by the slight rebound
in June, pointing out that the big drop in May was the third
setback so far this year. They also noted a report Tuesday that the
Purchasing Managers' Index, a widely watched barometer of economic
conditions, fell in July to its lowest point in 6{ years.
   ``The industrial sector is losing ground,'' said Bruce
Steinberg, senior economist at the New York brokerage firm of
Merrill Lynch. ``We are seeing a mild recession developing in the
United States right now.''
   Steinberg predicted that the economy would contract in both the
current quarter and in the fourth quarter of this year before
beginning to recover in early 1990.
   However, other economists were not as pessimistic, noting that
the housing industry, which had been in a slump earlier this year,
is beginning to rebound. Another government report Wednesday showed
that new homes sales climbed 5.5 percent in June, the third monthly
increase.
   Cynthia Latta, an economist with DRI-McGraw Hill, said the
pickup in housing should spill over into manufacturing, helping to
bolster sales of home appliances and building materials.
   Ms. Latta and other economists said one reason they believed the
country would be able to escape a recession is that unsold
inventories have not built up to such high levels that they would
trigger sharp cutbacks in production over the months ahead.
   Those economists also noted that the backlog of unfilled orders,
considered a good indicator of whether production cutbacks will be
needed, continued to rise in June, climbing by 0.5 percent to
$490.3 billion. The orders backlog has not declined since February
1987.
   In June, new orders for durable goods, items expected to last
three or more years, rose 0.4 percent to a seasonally adjusted
$124.2 billion. This represented a slight upward revision from an
advance report a week ago that put the increase at 0.3 percent.
   Orders for nondurable goods rose 0.4 percent as well, with
various consumer categories showing strength.
   Much of June's overall advance came from an 18.3 percent surge
in orders for military equipment, a rebound from an 11.4 percent
drop in this volatile category in May.
   Orders in the key category of non-defense capital goods edged up
0.3 percent in June following a 7.7 percent decline in May. This
category is closely watched for signs of industry plans to expand
and modernize.
   Many economists said they believed that business investment,
which has been strong over the past year, will weaken in the last
half of 1989. But the Bush administration is counting on continued
strength in investment to support its optimistic forecast that the
overall economy will grow by 2.9 percent, as measured by the gross
national product.
   Shipments of manufactured goods fell 0.5 percent in June to
$231.9 billion. The trend in shipments has been flat this year,
averaging $231.2 billion, about 1.5 percent less than orders each
month.
</TEXT>
