<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Britain-Art     08-02 0120</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Britain-Art,0123</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landlord Sold Sculptures for Scrap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DERBY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven metal sculptures, representing one
year's labor by artist Denis O'Connor, were sold as scrap for $16
by his landlord while he was on vacation, the artist told a civil
court hearing Wednesday.
   Vivian Lovell, a Public Arts Commission official, said he valued
the works at up to $10,400. They included images of a bird and a
train.
   Landlord Peter Ward, who said he thought the sculptures were
junk, was ordered by Derby County Court to pay O'Connor $6,900
damages and interest plus legal costs. The court found he had
unfairly evicted the sculptor from his studio.
   O'Connor, also a college lecturer, has sold more than 400 works.
</TEXT>
