<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1607EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Hostages-Pentagon     08-02 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages-Pentagon,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>6th Fleet Flagship Cancels Soviet Port Call</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The flagship of the U.S. 6th Fleet canceled a
ceremonial visit to a Soviet port, and it and other warships were
put ``at the beck and call'' of President Bush on Wednesday in case
they're needed in the hostage situation, Pentagon officials said.
   The aircraft carrier USS America and eight escort ships also cut
short a port call in Singapore, other officials said, but the
Pentagon refused to reveal the carrier's destination or the reason
for the battle group's early departure.
   Military officials, speaking privately, emphasized that the ship
movements were not ``bellicose'' actions and noted that the forces
in the Mediterranean area remain at the normal peace-time level.
   But the announcements highlighted the type of ``show-the-flag''
movements designed to give the impression that U.S. forces are
ready to act if the president decides to use them.
   ``We're positioning ourselves at the beck and call of the
president,'' said one Pentagon official familiar with the tactics.
``These are not necessarily bellicose moves _ but we want to be
ready in case we are needed. ... These are prudent measures,'' the
official said.
   The Pentagon official stressed that ``extensive on-scene
diplomatic efforts'' are under way, and that emphasis is not being
placed on a possible military strike.
   ``We are just giving the president what he might need,'' the
official said.
   But, the official also pointed out, in case a strike is ordered,
U.S. ships are ready with their long-range guns, aircraft and
missiles, even if they remain some distance from a possible target.
   ``You don't have to be near the shore to do what may be
necessary,'' the official said.
   In a statement, the Pentagon announced that the USS Belknap, the
Navy flagship in the Mediterranean, canceled a four-day call at the
port of Sevastapol.
   Two other ships, the USS Thomas S. Gates and the USS Kauffman,
were slated to keep to the scheduled visit, set for Aug. 4-8.
   The Belknap, a guided missile cruiser with fleet commander Vice
Adm. James D. Williams aboard, had been scheduled to call at the
Black Sea port as part of a long-planned exchange worked out
between the superpowers.
   Three Soviet ships just departed Norfolk, Va., after conducting
the first such visit to a U.S. port in 14 years.
   Williams and his ship ``are required elsewhere and will not be
able to visit Sevastopol,'' the Pentagon statement said.
   The statement made no mention of the reported execution of Lt.
Col. William Higgins, or of threats by Shiite Moslem factions to
execute another U.S. hostage.
   The cancellation of the Belknap's visit allows Williams to
remain in the Mediterranean in case his services are needed there,
said other officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   On Tuesday, the only U.S. aircraft carrier in the 6th Fleet, the
USS Coral Sea, had left Alexandria, Egypt, ``several hours
earlier'' than planned, Navy sources said.
   The Pentagon, following normal policy, refused to divulge the
destination of any of the carriers or their battle groups.
   One official pointed out that if the America is headed in the
direction of the Middle East, it will take nearly a week for the
carrier to cross the Indian Ocean from Singapore.
   Overall, there are between 20 to 25 U.S. ships in the
Mediterranean at this time, with approximately 20 others in the
Persian Gulf and Indian Ocean region, Pentagon officials said.
   The battleship Iowa, which is not allowed to use its 16-inch
guns pending the outcome of a Navy inquiry into the April explosion
in one of its three turrets, ended its port call in Marseilles,
France, and is in the Mediterranean, the sources said.
   The ship has a variety of weapons, including cruise missiles,
that could be used if necessary, sources said.
   Also on permanent station in the Mediterranean is a three-ship
amphibious landing group composed of 2,400 Marines, officials said.
   ``This is very typical of the Mediterranean,'' said one Navy
official. ``There is nothing unique about our deployment there.
It's our normal peace-time position,'' he said.
   The official added that the Navy's duty is to provide a U.S.
presence around the world and the ship movements allow routine
patrols as well as for training.
   ``We have to train as if we were at war, and you can't do that
in port,'' he said.
</TEXT>
