<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1623EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Methadone     08-02 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Methadone,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>HHS Head Says Methadone Programs Not Perfect, But Helpful</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health Secretary Louis Sullivan told Congress
Wednesday that while methadone programs are ``not ideal,'' they are
better than doing nothing to help heroin addicts quit their habit
and avoid AIDS.
   Sullivan, testifying before the House Select Committee on
Narcotics Abuse and Control, defended his department's proposal to
make methadone available to more addicts to prevent needle-sharing
and help curb the spread of AIDS.
   ``This is not ideal,'' he said in response to two studies
critical of the plan. ``But this, we feel, is better than nothing
for those individuals.''
   He emphasized that the program proposed in March would be an
``interim step'' that would allow heroin addicts to receive
methadone while they wait for an opening in a comprehensive
methadone treatment program.
   The General Accounting Office and Drug Enforcement
Administration, in separate studies presented to the committee,
questioned the wisdom of the Department of Health and Human
Services' plan. They cited continued drug abuse by many patients in
treatment and illegal diversion of the methadone.
   Under the HHS proposal, heroin addicts unable to get into a
comprehensive treatment program would be able to receive methadone
daily at outpatient clinics and from mobile medical units. The
synthetic narcotic would not be provided for take-home use and
addicts would be counseled on avoiding AIDS.
   Heroin addicts often share needles and, in doing so, can spread
or contract the AIDS virus. Methadone, which is used to help
relieve an addict's craving for heroin and is less addictive, is
taken by mouth, eliminating the risk from needles.
   About 100,000 people were undergoing methadone treatment last
year; the government estimates there are about 500,000 heroin
addicts nationwide.
   Preliminary results of the GAO study of 15 methadone programs in
five states indicate that as many as 47 percent of patients in
treatment for more than six months at one clinic continued to use
drugs. Forty percent of patients at another clinic used cocaine.
   ``Results of our work indicate that most clinics have not been
able to deal effectively with the drug problems of many of their
patients,'' Janet L. Shikles, director of national and public
health issues for the GAO, an arm of Congress, said in testimony
submitted to the panel.
   ``It is unclear how effective the interim maintenance program
would be in reducing the spread of AIDS,'' she said. ``GAO believes
that additional information is needed before the program is allowed
to be implemented nationwide.''
   The GAO reviewed methadone clinics serving more than 3,300
patients in New York, California, Washington, Florida and Texas.
Most clinic officials GAO investigators interviewed did not support
the HHS plan allowing interim methadone maintenance programs, she
said.
   Gene R. Haislip, deputy administrator of the DEA's Office of
Diversion Control, said an investigation conducted in the New York
metropolitan area between Aug. 21 and Sept. 16, 1988, found ``there
is significant selling of take-home dosages of methadone.''
   Haislip said many of the programs monitored by DEA have lax
safeguards and ``routinely ignore'' test results that show patients
are using other drugs rather than take taking their methadone.
   ``There is little incentive for individuals to become drug-free
because their steady supply of methadone provides them with a
constant source of illicit income with which to purchase other
drugs, primarily cocaine,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
