<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1631EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Hostages-Diplomacy     08-02 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages-Diplomacy,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Somewhat More Encouraged about Hostage Situation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Hostages Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The international uproar over the reported
killing of Lt. Col. William Higgins, including criticism from
Iran's president-elect, left U.S. officials somewhat encouraged
Wednesday about the fate of the second American hostage facing a
death sentence in Lebanon.
   Two days after a militant Shiite group in Lebanon announced
Higgins' execution on Monday, State Department spokeswoman Margaret
Tutwiler said she was unable to think of a single country that
hasn't spoken out against the action.
   Still, other officials cautioned the situation remains grim,
pointing out the captors of Joseph Cicippio, who was taken hostage
in 1986, have not backed off their pledge to execute him on
Thursday.
   Ms. Tutwiler seemed to attach importance to a joint statement
issued Tuesday in Tehran by Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze and Iran's president-elect Ali Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani in which they expressed regret over Higgin's reported
death.
   They also condemned ``all acts of a terrorist nature.''
   Ms. Tutwiler called on Rafsanjani to act ``in accordance with
the spirit'' of his statement.
   She said the United States ``remains convinced that Iran is in a
position to bring significant influence to bear'' on the
pro-Iranian groups who hold the American hostages and she called on
the Iranians to use the influence.
   If Higgins' death is confirmed, that would leave eight American
hostages in Lebanon. The State Department was still unable to
confirm absolutely that the body in the videotape released Monday
in Beirut was that of Higgins.
   Ms. Tutwiler also welcomed a statement by a top aide to
Palestine Liberation Organization leader Yasser Arafat criticizing
the execution of Higgins.
   The sense among American officials was that the outrage
expressed by Western as well as Islamic countries about the
developments in Beirut may be having an impact on Iran and its
Shiite allies in Lebanon.
   The officials, asking not to be identified, left open the
possibility that the Iranians may have convinced the captors of
Cicippio, 58, to delay his execution by 48 hours.
   A crisis atmosphere had prevailed here when the group claiming
to hold Cicippio, the Revolutionary Justice Organization, said it
would kill him Tuesday at 11 a.m. EDT unless Israel freed a Shiite
Moslem cleric kidnapped by Israeli commandos July 28.
   With the delay in administering the death sentence, officials
expressed hope that intensified diplomatic efforts by U.S. envoys
may be bearing fruit. The U.S. diplomats have been in touch with a
number of countries with access to or influence with Iran.
   In Beirut, Shiite Moslem sources said Iranian pressure may have
been behind the decision to delay the execution and added the
chance his life may be spared has increased.
</TEXT>
