<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Martinez     08-02 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Martinez,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Governor Gives Bush Anti-Drug Recommendations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida Gov. Bob Martinez brought President
Bush a thick packet of recommendations Wednesday from the National
Governors' Association on how to wage the war on drugs.
   Bush promised to forward the proposals swiftly to drug policy
chief William J. Bennett, who is due to unveil a new national
drug-fighting strategy next month.
   The governors' 10-point plan, approved at their summer meeting
in Chicago on Tuesday, endorsed Bush's call for a hemispheric drug
summit and urged that foreign aid be tied to countries' cooperating
with U.S. efforts to eradicate drugs.
   ``The loss of a generation of young people because of the abuse
of drugs ... is the most serious issue facing the nation,''
Martinez said after emerging from the Oval Office.
   Providing ``a larger carrot ... in foreign aid and perhaps a
better deal on the reduction of the world debt, I believe, is a
good way to go,'' said Martinez.
   He added that a new extradition treaty with Colombia with ``some
teeth'' is also needed.
   The governors also urged the Bush administration to convert idle
military bases into federal drug prisons.
   ``The land is there. The facilities are there. It's a question
many times of perimeter fences, so we're not talking big money on
most of these items that we are submitting to the White House,''
Martinez said.
   Bush ``did not indicate to me how close they were in developing
the policy,'' said Martinez.
   He said they also discussed the congressional primary results in
Miami, where state Sen. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen captured the GOP
nomination for the seat of the late Claude Pepper. The Democratic
race is headed for a Aug. 15 runoff, two weeks before the special
election.
   Martinez said he also informed Bush of the National Governors
Association vote Tuesday calling for a two-year moratorium on
expanding Medicaid.
   Martinez, who has called a special session of the Florida
legislature Oct. 10 to seek stricter limits on abortion, said he
and Bush did not discuss abortion.
   Florida lawmakers will be the first to tackle the issue since
the recent Supreme Court ruling giving states more authority to
restrict abortions.
   The governor said he was trying ``to balance the rights of women
and the unborn child.''
   Martinez said he favors changing state law to declare the fetus
viable at the 20th week instead of the 24th, to impose higher
medical standards for abortion clinics, and to require attending
physicians to counsel women about ``the health of the unborn baby''
before performing abortions.
   ``I cannot imagine anyone who would like to see an unborn baby
that's viable aborted,'' said Martinez, who said he supports state
funding of abortion for poor women only in cases of rape or incest
or if the woman's life is threatened.
   Asked about polls that indicated most Floridians were
pro-choice, Martinez said, ``It depends which polls you look at.
... I've seen enough polls to know that people do not want abortion
to be a system of birth control. I'm also confident that the
Floridians do not want to see a viable baby aborted.''
</TEXT>
