<FIRST>r i AM-GarciaMarquez     08-02 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Garcia Marquez,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Garcia Marquez Awarded Prize For Contributing To Latin Unity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The unity and freedom of Latin America is a
``dream within a dream'' that must soon become reality, author
Gabriel Garcia Marquez said Wednesday as he accepted an award for
his contributions to the fulfillment of that dream.
   ``In his prose, Gabriel Garcia Marquez presents the various
facets of the vision of a single Latin America,'' Jose Juan de
Olloqui, chairman of Banca Serfin, told 300 people at the Mexican
presidential residence.
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari presented the Serfin Prize
to the Nobel prize-winning author but made no remarks. The prize
carries no monetary award, a bank official said.
   Garcia Marquez grappled with the problem of Latin unity in his
latest book, ``The General in his Labyrinth,'' a controversial
novel cast as a deathbed narrative by Simon Bolivar, a hero of
South America's independence from Spain.
   Bolivar's goal was not just independence but the creation of a
united Latin American federation to compete with the United States
in North America. That vision dissolved into the separate nations,
including Bolivar's Greater Colombia, now Colombia, Venezuela,
Ecuador, Bolivia and Peru.
   The book has created a literary controversy because it deals
with a sensitive subject and because of its demythologizing
portrayal of the man known as ``the Liberator'' as a foul-mouthed
libertine.
   In his brief remarks, Garcia Marquez began by recounting a story
by Italian author Italo Calvino in which an emperor of China asks a
painter to portray a crab.
   The painter replies that it will take five years and he'll need
a house with 12 servants. When the five years are up, he asks for
another five years.
   When the emperor comes back again, the painter rises, snatches
up his brush and in an instant paints the most beautiful crab ever
seen.
   ``In this story from ancient China you can see a crude
representation of artistic creation, the most incomprehensible and
enslaving of human passions,'' Garcia Marquez said.
   The 20th century, which has ``unleashed the furies of the atom
as a servant of death, and seen a flag planted on the windless
wastes of the moon,'' might be just another of man's many lost
centuries if if were not for a dream.
   ``Let us dream aloud, then. Let us dream that a fundamental
change has started in the world, that the craziest concentration of
power in the history of mankind is ending because the dogmas that
sustained the two sides are breaking down, and we are headed for a
new millenium dominated by the freedom of creative thought.''
   Inside those dreams, Garcia Marquz said, lies Bolivar's dream,
the dream of a united Latin America, ``finally part of the torrent
of history, made up of our invincible culture, our inspired
nightmares, our crazy magic, of the disasters that revive us, and
the irresistible power of the imagination.
   ``Mr. President, ladies and gentlemen, Latin Americans all, I
think it is time for us to draw the crab.''
</TEXT>
