<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     08-02 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Governing Party Poised to Pick Ex-minister to Lead Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Cabinet minister with reform credentials
emerged Wednesday as the clear front-runner for prime minister
after maneuvering within the governing party, which is beset by
scandal and plummeting popularity.
   Former education minister Toshiki Kaifu was the only declared
candidate after a day of meetings by Liberal Democratic Party
leaders. The party is expected to elect a new party president on
Tuesday and then vote him in as prime minister on Aug. 10.
   With its large majority in the lower house of Parliament, the
party can be assured of victory in the vote for prime minister.
   Kaifu, 58, gained support, though lukewarm, from enough party
factions to make him the leading contender. No other strong
candidate was put forward, but other people could still be
championed until Saturday morning.
   The former minister would succeed Prime Minister Sousuke Uno. He
resigned last month after only eight weeks in office in the wake of
a sex scandal and a severe loss in the July 23 election for the
upper house of Parliament. Uno was accused of keeping paid
mistresses.
   Kaifu belongs to one of the smallest factions in the
conservative governing party, a position that normally would have
made him an unlikely choice for high office. In addition, he has
not held the key Cabinet posts or top party jobs that are normally
part of a prime minister's background.
   But leaders of all the bigger party factions are tainted by
responsibility for the election defeat or by a bribery scandal that
toppled Uno's predecessor, Noboru Takeshita.
   ``I hope I can get as much support from the party as possible,''
Kaifu told reporters after his faction united behind him. ``I'm
overwhelmed by the honor and will do my best.''
   He said it was too early to answer questions about details of
his policy ideas. ``But political reform is the biggest issue that
has been raised by the people,'' he said.
   Party members have called for political reform to help restore
public trust eroded by the bribery scandal.
   Kaifu acknowledged he had accepted political donations from the
company at the hub of the scandal, the Recruit Co. information
conglomerate.
   He said Recruit had contributed about $110,000 to his political
coffers over five years, but the money had been properly reported.
Kaifu said he stopped receiving Recruit money after the scandal
emerged last year.
   Kaifu, a longtime member of the lower house of Parliament,
belongs to the political reform committee set up by the party to
deal with the scandal.
   From 1974 to 1976, he was deputy chief Cabinet secretary under
the late Prime Minister Takeo Miki, who sought to clean up Japan's
money politics when he succeeded scandal-plagued Prime Minister
Kakuei Tanaka.
   Kaifu later served as education minister for two periods of
about a year each.
   His candidacy had been rumored since the weekend, when party
Secretary-General Ryutaro Hashimoto's bid began to falter.
   Kaifu became the clear front-runner Wednesday after his mentor
and faction leader, 78-year-old Toshio Komoto, said he had decided
not to run.
   The next prime minister must deal not only with the party's
scandals but also with widespread opposition to a new 3 percent
sales tax.
</TEXT>
