<FIRST>r w AM-FishWars     08-02 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fish Wars,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Finds Holds Of Taiwanese Vessel Filled With Salmon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Coast Guard personnel who boarded a
Taiwanese drift net vessel suspected of involvement in a scheme to
sell $1.3 million worth illegally caught fish reported Wednesday
that its holds were filled with salmon.
   Taiwanese enforcement officers and observers from the Coast
Guard cutter Morganthau boarded the Sung Ching No. 1 early
Wednesday about 75 miles off Taiwan.
   The Morganthau had been shadowing the Sung Ching No. 1 for more
than two weeks in the North Pacific as the State Department sought
permission from the government of Taiwan for U.S. personnel to
board. The Taiwanese initially refused, then decided to dispatch
their own law enforcement officials to the ship and allow a
joint-boarding party.
   ``All the holds were filled with salmon,'' said Carolyn Feldman,
a spokeswoman at the Coast Guard's Pacific Command in Alameda,
Calif.
   After the boarding, the vessel was turned over to Taiwanese
officials.
   The State Department demanded that the vessel's crew be
prosecuted under Taiwanese law, which restricts the export of
salmon and limits where Taiwanese drift net vessels are allowed to
fish.
   The Sung Ching No. 1 was one of at least two Taiwanese drift net
vessels implicated in the illegal sale of salmon to U.S. undercover
agents posing as fish buyers in a six-month sting operation.
   Last month, federal agents arrested two Taiwanese men as they
emerged from a Seattle bank vault carrying more than $1 million in
cash allegedly received as payment for 500 metric tons of illegally
caught fish.
   At the same time the arrests were made, the Sung Ching No. 1 and
another Taiwanese ship were rendezvousing with the U.S. government
chartered fishing tender Redfin north of Midway Island to deliver
the fish.
   When the captains of the two vessels boarded the Redfin to
arrange details of the fish transfer they were detained, but their
vessels fled as the Morganthau approached.
   While the Morganthau tracked the Sung Ching No. 1, the Redfin
followed the other boat for several days before running short of
supplies and heading for Alaska.
   Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, said the discovery of a ``huge
quantity'' of salmon aboard the Sung Ching No. 1 gives Taiwanese
authorities ``plenty of evidence to go along with what we have
already provided, and it is up to them to throw the book at these
outlaws.''
   U.S. fishing groups claim that illegal drift netting by vessels
from Taiwan, Japan and South Korea has already had a serious impact
on salmon runs in Alaska, Washington state and Oregon.
</TEXT>
