<FIRST>r w AM-FSLICDeparture 1stLd-Writethru a0658 08-02 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FSLIC Departure, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>California S&amp;L Gets OK to Leave FSLIC and Become Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 5-6 pvs, bgng: The bank, with 3 new grafs to include
congressional comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal savings and loan regulators have
authorized the nation's eighth largest thrift institution to become
a commercial bank, potentially reducing revenue to the beleaguered
fund insuring S&amp;L deposits by millions of dollars.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, in a decision late Tuesday,
said Home Federal Savings and Loan Association of San Diego could
leave the insolvent Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp.
   Home Federal is only one of several big S&amp;Ls trying to escape
FSLIC and join the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., the commercial
bank fund which charges its members less for the same federal
insurance of $100,000 per account.
   But, before the S&amp;L can become HomeFed Bank, it must secure
permission from California S&amp;L and bank regulators and from the
FDIC, a process expected to take at least several months.
   The bank board's decision is generating criticism in Congress,
which hopes to pass legislation this week committing taxpayers to
spending billions of dollars to bail out the S&amp;L industry.
   As part of the price for the bailout, S&amp;Ls will continue to pay
higher insurance premiums than banks for the next five years, even
if they convert to a bank.
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., a member of the House Banking
Committee, said regulators may have had no choice but to rule in
favor of Home Federal. But, he added, ``I think it's awful. It
sends a terrible signal. ... If there was a legal way to avoid the
decision, it should have been done.''
   Home Federal is hoping to get out of FSLIC under a provision of
1987 banking legislation that permits institutions to leave
provided they applied before March 31, 1987. Home Federal filed its
applications to the FDIC and state regulators a day before the
deadline.
   It is unclear, however, if that loophole will still be good if
Home Federal, as expected, is unable to complete its conversion
before Congress enacts new S&amp;L legislation, which has provisions
that would supersede the law passed two years ago.
   John Buchman, a bank board staff attorney, said the Home Federal
decision will not set a precedent favorable to several other large
S&amp;Ls trying to bolt the FSLIC.
   Two Los Angeles-based S&amp;Ls _ Home Savings of America and Great
Western, the largest and second-largest thrifts in the nation _ are
also trying to leave FSLIC.
   The bank board denied Great Western's application and, in June,
the thrift lost an attempt to overturn the decision in U.S.
District Court in Los Angeles. It is appealing the ruling.
   The bank board has until October to rule on the application from
Home Savings of America.
   The bank board has allowed 13 other S&amp;Ls to secede from the
FSLIC under the 1987 law, all considerably smaller than Home
Federal.
   Home Federal, ranked eighth in the nation with $17.2 billion in
assets at the end of May, has about 200 branches throughout
California. Last year, it paid $13.7 million more in insurance
premiums than it would have as a bank.
   Both bank and S&amp;L premiums would be raised under the S&amp;L bill,
but Home Federal would still pay about $9 million less in premiums
as a bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 2104EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-US     08-02 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-US,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senior State Department Official To Visit Sudan on Aid Cutoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior U.S. official will visit Sudan on
Sunday to decide whether Washington should freeze $108 million in
aid because of a military coup a month ago, a Western official said.
   Herman Cohen, assistant secretary of state for African affairs,
is to determine whether U.S. law requires the funding cutoff, which
would not affect about $100 million in annual humanitarian aid, the
official told foreign reporters.
   Section 513 to the U.S. 1987 Foreign Assistance Act stipulates
that economic aid must cease to a country where a democratically
elected government is removed in violation of the country's
constitution, said the official on condition of anonymity.
   Fiji in 1986 became the first country to have its U.S. aid
halted under provisions of Section 513, he said.
   However, the law, known as Section 513, ``includes a waiver
provision related to national security interests of the United
States,'' he said.
   ``Cohen will explore the possibility of using the waiver,
depending on how the new Sudanese government will deal with certain
issues,'' the official said.
   He said said Cohen will study the position of Lt. Gen. Omar
Hassan el-Bashir, who with other middle-level field-grade officers
overthrew Sudanese Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi's government on
June 30.
   The official said Cohen will gauge el-Bashir's stands on two key
sore points between the United States and el-Mahdi. One is ending
the southern Sudan civil war and the other is allowing delivery of
relief supplies to southerners suffering from a famine the
6-year-old war has caused.
   The law puts at stake $108 million committed to Sudan, the
official said.
   Already, $22 million in development and economic aid has been
frozen since January under rules requiring it after a country faces
back debt payments on U.S. government loans for more than a year.
   But the official stressed that neither Section 513 nor that
rule, called the Brooke Amendment, affect U.S. humanitarian aid to
Sudan, one of the world's poorest countries. That amounted to $100
million dollars in the past year.
   He said Washington believes el-Bashir is ready to take the steps
necessary to end the war.
   President Hosni Mubarak, who last month took over as chairman of
the Organization of African Unity, already began mediating between
el-Bashir and the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army, which is
supported by Ethiopia.
   Exploratory peace talks are to start in the Ethiopian capital
Addis Ababa this week.
   The Western official said he believes the talks may succeed
because both Sudan and Ethiopia are economically exhausted by the
long struggle.
   Cohen's African tour started in Cairo to see how the United
States can help Mubarak, as OAU chairman, end several regional
African conflicts. Among them are those between Somalia and
Mauritania and Chad and Libya.
   Africa's foreign debt, estimated at $250 billion, is another
item on Cohen's agenda during his tour, which also will take him to
Ethiopia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 2109EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ChildCPR     08-02 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child CPR,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Cross Launches Campaign To Prevent Child Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Red Cross launched a national
campaign Wednesday aimed at preventing child deaths from choking,
suffocation and drowning.
   The Infant and Child CPR Campaign encourages parents,
grandparents, baby sitters and other care-givers to learn how to
handle breathing emergencies in infants and children.
   Actress Lynda Carter, who has an 18-month-old boy, lent her name
to the campaign.
   ``There's a lot a parent can do before the ambulance arrives,''
said Robert Burnside, director of health services for the American
Red Cross.
   The Heimlich maneuver, however, is not among them.
   That method of using abdominal thrusts to dislodge obstructions
in the breathing passages works on choking adults but does more
harm than good when used on a baby, Burnside said.
   A choking baby needs to be held in a certain way and be given a
series of blows to the back and thrusts to the chest to restore
breathing, he said.
   The technique taught in the American Red Cross Infant and Child
CPR course was highlighted in a segment of the CBS daytime drama
``The Young and the Restless'' Wednesday when a choking emergency
occurred to a young child.
   Besides choking emergencies, the seven-hour Red Cross course
teaches mouth-to-mouth rescue breathing, cardiopulmonary
resuscitation and injury prevention.
   Thousands of children who die from choking, suffocation and
drowning could be saved if more adults knew how to respond to the
emergencies, Burnside said.
   Choking and suffocation are leading causes of accidental deaths
in children under 1 year old, according to the Johns Hopkins
University Injury Prevention Center.
   Among children ages 1-4, drowning is the second leading cause of
accidental deaths after motor vehicle accidents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
