<DOCNO> AP890802-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1804EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-RiceMarket     08-02 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rice Market,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coals to Newcastle? Try Rice to China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China is forecast to become a net importer of
rice for the first time in recent history, helping create a record
worldwide trade in rice in 1989, the Agriculture Department said
Wednesday.
   The report, ``Rice: Situation and Outlook Yearbook,'' says
China, Indonesia and India are fueling this year's record demand,
with trade forecast at 13.4 million metric tons.
   The previous record was 13.1 million metric tons set in 1981,
the report said.
   Although the United States will increase its exports 10 percent
this year to 2.5 million metric tons, Thailand will be the big
winner, exporting a record 5.5 million metric tons.
   The U.S. share of the export, 19 percent, and the Thai share, 41
percent, will be the same as last year, the USDA said.
   China has already bought 950,000 tons from Thailand, which has
been exporting rice at ``an extraordinary pace'' since August 1988,
the report said. China is expected to buy 1.2 million tons of rice
this year from all sources, the report said. That is triple the
amount bought the previous year.
   The report said ``it is unclear how or if the current turmoil in
China will affect its short-term rice trade.''
   ``There have been few reports of exports in the first half of
1989, and China is forecast to export only 300,000 tons by the end
of the year, less than half the amount it exported in 1988,'' the
report said.
   China, India and Indonesia will also account for about a 5
percent drop in the 1990 market when their crops improve and stocks
are replenished. India and China account for over 50 percent of the
world's rice production.
   China imports rice to feed its urban populations. In the
forecast for 1990 contained in the report, the department cites
reports that farmers will keep more rice on the farm because of the
government system of paying farmers with IOUs that cannot be
redeemed immediately.
   Indonesia is forecast to import 400,000 tons and India will
likely take in 500,000 tons, the report says.
   China and India are expecting record crops in the crop year
1989-1990.
   Arkansas, California, Louisiana, Mississippi, Missouri and Texas
are the main rice-growing states. The main U.S. customers are
Europe, the Middle East, South America and Africa.
   Low stocks and strong import demand caused world prices to soar
starting in January. They reached $8.91 per hundredweight in July,
after having fallen to $5.90 in December 1988. Recent prices were
at their lowest in 1986-1987, when abundant world prices kept them
down as far as $3.78 a hundredweight.
   U.S. farmers are planting 2.8 million acres in rice this year, 5
percent less than a year ago, the department estimates. Yields are
unlikely to show improvement, meaning a drop in production, the
department says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
