<FIRST>r a AM-GeorgiaCrash     08-02 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Georgia Crash,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Plane Crashes On Takeoff, Six Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plane Emergency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine plane crashed on takeoff
Wednesday at Albany's airport, getting barely aloft before tumbling
to the ground and exploding in flames. Six people were killed,
authorities said.
   The Beechcraft Queen Air BE-80 was bound for Akron, Ohio,
according to William Hoefer, an air traffic controller at Southwest
Georgia Regional Airport.
   The plane had climbed only about 10 feet off the ground when its
right engine caught fire, witnesses said.
   The plane's right wing then slammed into the ground, spewing
fuel as the aircraft cartwheeled several times, the witnesses
reported.
   The plane, engulfed in flames, came to rest upside down and
broken apart near the control tower.
   The fire prevented any rescue, witnesses said. ``There's not
much you can do when that gas ignited,'' said off-duty Eastern
Airlines pilot Doug Powell, who saw the crash.
   Rescue crews left the victims' bodies in the wreckage until
investigators from the Federal Aviation Administration and the
National Transportation Safety Board could examine it, said Fire
Chief J.D. Jansen.
   ``As far as we can determine now we have six fatalities,'' said
Jansen.
   Six people, including the pilot, were driven by van from the
terminal and boarded the plane minutes before takeoff, said Linda
Bradshaw of Gray Air Service, the van's driver.
   The victims were not immediately identified.
   The plane was registered to Rainbow Properties of Sarasota,
Fla., according to Vedder Steed of the FAA in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
