<FIRST>u i AM-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0648 08-02 0991</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,1024</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hopes Rise for Sparing Cicippio; U.N. Official Arrives</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs, RAISES reference to Shiite Moslems, UPDATES
with Bush's efforts. Picks up 12th graf, `There are...' with minor editing
to TRIM. ^LaserPhotos NY31,32</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. official went to southern Lebanon
Wednesday to press the search for the body of a slain American
hostage as a glimmer of hope came from the Shiite Moslem camp that
a second hostage would be spared.
   The victim, U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, was on U.N.
duty when he was abducted.
   Shiite sources said they expected kidnappers threatening the
life of Joseph Cicippio, 58, of Norristown, Pa., to spare him at
Iran's behest to avert a confrontation with the United States.
   Pro-Iranian kidnappers said they hanged Higgins on Monday in
retaliation for Israel's abduction Friday of a Lebanese Shiite
cleric. The colonel was seized Feb. 17, 1988, near Tyre in south
Lebanon.
   The Vatican said Pope John Paul II, at President Bush's request,
would assist in efforts to have Higgins' body returned to the
United States.
   Bush said Wednesday he is ``leaving no stone unturned'' in
trying to free American hostages but lacks hard information as he
tries to deal with the crisis ``in a prudent way.''
   He said he contacted many world leaders and ``We have had
assurance after assurance ... they want to help.''
   British officials in London said Bush and Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher talked for 20 minutes about the crisis.
   A videotape the kidnappers provided shows a man, apparently
Higgins, hanging from a gallows. No body has been found and there
is no way of knowing when the tape was made. Some reports have said
Higgins was killed months ago.
   Pentagon officials said the USS Belknap, flagship of the U.S.
6th Fleet, and the fleet commander canceled a visit to Sevastopol
in the Soviet Union in case Bush needs them, but said a military
strike was unlikely. The aircraft carrier America cut short a visit
to Singapore, they said.
   Marrack Goulding, U.N. undersecretary-general for peacekeeping
operations, flew to U.N. headquarters in the Lebanese border town
of Naqoura by helicopter from Israel.
   He met with Maj. Gen. Lars-Eric Wahlgren, Swedish commander of
the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon, and battalion commanders of the
nine-nation force known as UNIFIL to investigate Higgins' death and
try to find his body.
   UNIFIL spokesman Timor Goksel said Goulding put off going to
Beirut because of the fighting but would try to make the trip
Thursday. Christian forces and a Syrian-led Moslem alliance have
fought an artillery war in Beirut for five months.
   The undersecretary-general is scheduled to meet with Lebanese
leaders in Beirut, but Goksel would not identify them.
   ``There are no negotiations involved, although he has a
secondary mission of trying to find out about other hostages in
Lebanon,'' the spokesman said.
   Sixteen Westerners are captives in Lebanon, including eight
Americans. Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Higgins, 44, commanded a 75-man observer team attached to the
5,800-member UNIFIL force.
   Cicippio's captors, who call themselves the Revolutionary
Justice Organization, said Monday he would be killed unless Israel
freed Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid by 6 p.m. the next day.
   Two hours after the Tuesday deadline, the kidnappers announced a
``non-extendable postponement'' of 48 hours. No specific hour on
Thursday was mentioned as a new deadline.
   The statement cited a plea for mercy from Cicippio's Lebanese
wife, Elham, and other ``friendly appeals and sincere behests.''
   Mrs. Cicippio said Wednesday: ``Even if it was a postponement
for only one minute, it's better than nothing.''
   Shiite sources said Iran might have stepped in to save Cicippio
because of the international uproar created by Higgins' death.
   An organization caling itself the Organization of the Oppressed
on Earth claimed to hold Higgins.
   Nearly all the groups holding hostages are believed to be fronts
for Hezbollah, or Party of God, a Shiite movement in which Obeid is
a spiritual leader.
   Israel has offered to exchange Obeid and other Shiite prisoners
for the foreign hostages and three of its soldiers held prisoner in
Lebanon, but Hezbollah rejected the deal.
   Moshe Arens, the Israeli foreign minister, said Wednesday there
was a ``good possibility'' hostages would be freed, but other
officials said negotiations could be lengthy.
   Iran sponsors Hezbollah, which also holds two of the three
Israeli soldiers.
   Israeli commandos abducted Obeid, 33, and two aides from his
home in Jibchit, a south Lebanon village.
   Hezbollah denies any connection with the hostages, but publicly
endorsed the Oppressed on Earth group when it claimed
responsibility for Higgins' abduction.
   One Lebanese Shiite source said: ``The Iranians probably are
bringing immense pressure on their Lebanese surrogates, seeking to
defuse the crisis generated by Higgins' murder. They can do without
a showdown with the United States.''
   Hashemi Rafsanjani, just elected president of Iran, has sought
improved relations with the West in the past in hopes of aid in
rebuilding from eight years of war with Iraq.
   Other Shiite sources said the emergence of Rafsanjani as Iran's
most powerful politician had meant a decline in the influence over
Hezbollah of a hard-line rival, Interior Minister Ali Akbar
Mohtashemi.
   Analysts say the hostages' fate may be dictated by the struggle
between those known as pragmatists, led by Rafsanjani, and
hard-liners over the direction of Iran's 10-year-old Islamic
revolution.
   The first Shiite source noted that Revolutionary Justice is not
known to have killed a hostage, but has issued death threats in the
past.
   The Revolutionary Justice statement announcing the 48-hour
postponement for Cicippio was accompanied by a picture of another
American hostage it holds, writer Edward Austin Tracy, 58.
   Statements from the group threatened both men's lives twice in
1988.
   Cicippio was acting comptroller of the American University of
Beirut when he was abducted from its campus on Sept. 12, 1986.
</TEXT>
