<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 2128EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CleanAir     08-02 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Air,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Discuss Clean Air Plan with Environmental Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top administration officials met Wednesday
with environmental leaders to discuss criticisms of President
Bush's clean air plan, won praise for keeping an open White House
door but received no blanket commitment of support.
   Bush and his environmental advisory team invited the
environmentalists to discuss the acid rain provision of the clean
air package and promised later meetings on the airborne toxics and
urban smog sections which have prompted the most criticism from
environmental activists and members of Congress.
   The Environmental Defense Fund, which has praised Bush's
proposal to curb acid rain, will lobby for that aspect of the
president's package on Capitol Hill, spokesman Fred Krupp said
after the White House session.
   He said the acid rain portion ``is stronger than anything being
offered'' in competing legislation in Congress. He praised Bush for
``taking leadership'' on the environment that represented a ``sea
change'' from the Reagan administration.
   But Richard Ayres, of the National Resources Defense Council,
said his organization still has reservations about the provisions,
in part focusing on the way the White House calculated gaseous
emissions that cause acid rain.
   The administration claims its plan will result in a 10
million-ton reduction in sulfur dioxide emissions from 1980 levels,
but the NRDC's calculations are it will be only 9 million tons
since 1 million ton reduction has already been achieved.
   The meeting was the latest effort by the administration to take
the offensive on its clean air bill after weeks of criticism from
environmental groups and their congressional backers.
   Bush dropped by the meeting only briefly, participants said.
   Environmental Protection Agency Assistant Administrator William
Rosenberg said the meeting was called to ``continue the dialogue''
with environmental groups.
   However, he insisted the administration was not positioning to
make changes in the bill it sent to Congress last month.
   ``We're talking about clarifying our position, their position.
Sometimes there are interpretation questions that need to be raised
where we say one thing and different people read it for different
results. At this point it's an information discussion and not a
negotiating session. The administration's bill stands as it is,''
he said.
   Last week, Rosenberg accused Democrats in Congress of making
``unfair and totally biased attacks'' on the legislation and of
falsely calling the proposal a sellout to industry.
   Ayres said the administration officials at the meeting were
``very upset by the criticism the bill has got from the
environmental community and members of Congress. We responded with
equal vehemence that we don't think you've been unfairly attacked.
We believe what we're saying is based on the facts.''
   Administration officials have complained that the environmental
critics are nitpicking the bill after the administration solicited
their views and addressed many of their concerns in the package.
   ``They certainly would like us to be more positive than we have
been. I would like to be more positive than we've been able to
be,'' Ayres said.
   Paul Pritchard, president of the National Parks and Conservation
Foundation, praised the administration for continued consultation
with the environmentalists.
   ``Clearly they were stating that they were opening the door and
it's up to us to work with them,'' he said.
   But a number of organizations in the main environmental lobbying
group, the National Clean Air Coalition, were not invited _
including the Natural Resources Defense Council, Environmental
Action, the American Lung Association and the AFL-CIO.
   Ayres, director of the coalition, said he was invited only 15
minutes before the session, after he complained to administration
officials.
   But White House spokesman Steve Hart said it had been thought
that Ayres might be more appropriately invited to the later
sessions on urban smog and toxics than to Wednesday's meeting on
acid rain.
   An EPA source, speaking only on condition he not be named, said
the White House issued the invitations, and both EPA Administrator
William Reilly and Rosenberg ``were shocked that Ayres was not
invited.'' The source said the two EPA officials demanded that the
White House invite Ayres.
   ``The point they may have misjudged somewhat is that the
coalition works together,'' Ayres said. ``I speak for the
coalition.''
   The director of Environmental Action, Casey Padgett, accused the
White House of trying to ``fracture the coalition.''
   Others invited included representatives of the Wilderness
Society, Conservation Foundation, National Wildlife Foundation,
Sierra Club, and National Audubon Society.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
