<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 2132EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     08-02 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Guerrillas Attack Towns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas fought
overnight battles with government soldiers on San Salvador's
northern outskirts, and others attacked at least four towns
Wednesday.
   Six people were reported killed and more than 10 wounded in the
towns. At least one soldier and a civilian were killed and three
people were wounded in the battles Tuesday night in San Ramon and
Mejicanos, working-class areas on the city's northern edge.
   Venceremos, the guerrilla radio station, said the attacks on
towns were part of a rebel campaign against ``the fascist
government'' of President Alfredo Cristiani and ``increases in
transportation costs and repression in general.''
   Cristiani's conservative administration lifted price controls on
about 200 consumer items and services earlier this week, including
transportation and electricity, in an effort to revive the
war-battered economy.
   Bus fares increased Wednesday, in some cases to almost double
their former levels. New electricity rates will be announced next
week.
   Guerrillas of the rebel Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front has fought U.S.-supported governments for a decade. Human
rights groups say more than 70,000 people have been killed, most of
them civilians.
   Several rebel columns attacked military positions at San Pedro
Nonualco, 38 miles east of the capital, early Wednesday and one
civilian was killed in the fighting, the army press office said.
   A Venceremos broadcast told people to stay off the road in the
area because rebel forces had mined it.
   One rebel was killed and five were wounded in a guerrilla attack
on military positions in northern Chalatenango province, near the
Honduran border, and other rebel forces attacked San Jorge and
Carolina in San Miguel, an eastern province, the army said. There
were no reports on casualties in San Jorge and Carolina.
   Sgt. Ventura Lopez, who commands a squad of 10 soldiers in the
San Ramon district, one of the areas of overnight fighting, said
his post was attacked by about 60 rebels from the San Salvador
volcano northeast of the city.
   He said the guerrilas, armed with dynamite, assault rifles and
rocket-propelled grenades, were driven off by about 100 soldiers
from the Belloso infantry battalion.
   It was the fifth rebel attack in eight months on the San Ramon
army post. About 200 guerrillas are believed to be camped on the
volcano.
</TEXT>
