<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 2135EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TimberCompromise     08-02 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Timber Compromise,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Committee Puts Off Action On Ancient Forest Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate negotiators will meet in
September on legislation that would impose a 14-month ceasefire in
the battle over the ancient forests of Oregon and Washington state,
lawmakers said Wednesday.
   The lawmakers said the delay until after Congress' August recess
would give them more time to try to negotiate a compromise
acceptable to both the timber industry and environmentalists.
   ``If we can come up with a way to get the job done and soften
some of the criticism, we will certainly be looking for that,''
said Rep. Norman Dicks, D-Wash.
   The conference committee had originally been scheduled to meet
this week to discuss the spending bills for the Interior Department
and related agencies passed by the House and Senate.
   Congress is scheduled to recess at the end of the week until
after Labor Day.
   Environmentalists oppose the legislation, which would limit
their access to the courts to appeal timber sales during the
14-month grace period, and plan to use the month before the
conference committee meets to lobby against it.
   They say logging in the old-growth forests of the Northwest
destroys prime nesting areas for the rare northern spotted owl.
   Illinois Democratic Rep. Sidney Yates, chairman of the House
Appropriations interior subcommittee, put of the meeting of the
House-Senate conference committee because of major differences in
the versions of the spending bills adopted by the two chambers.
   The timber legislation is included as an amendment to the
Senate-passed version of the Interior spending bill, but not the
one approved by the House.
   Lawmakers said the legislation should ensure a short-term supply
of timber for the region's mills while protecting the old-growth
forests from logging. A permanent fix would still have to be
negotiated.
   The legislation would bar federal courts from suspending or
overturning any timber sales planned in federal forests of the
Northwest known to contain spotted owls through the end of fiscal
1990.
   In addition, the legislation requires that environmentalists
release more than half of the roughly two billion board feet of
timber currently enjoined from sale.
   If environmentalists do not agree to release the timber by Oct.
1, the legislation would allow the Forest Service and the Bureau of
Land Management to proceed with sales regardless of the injunctions.
</TEXT>
