<HEAD>Policeman, Two Children Injured In Grenade Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior policeman in Soweto
township and his two sons were injured Wednesday when attackers
tossed two grenades into his house, police said.
   Lt. Col. Fanyana Zwane and his 10-year-old son were slightly
hurt, while his 12-year-old son was seriously injured, said police
spokesman Joseph Mobeni.
   No group claimed responsibility, but militant anti-apartheid
activists regularly target black policemen.
   Zwane is one of the highest-ranking blacks in the South African
police and has worked in Soweto, the huge township outside
Johannesburg, for more than 15 years.
   Police have said that the outlawed African National Congress
guerrilla movement is planning to increase attacks during the weeks
leading up to the segregated parliamentary elections on Sept. 6.
   There are separate polls for whites, Asians and people of
mixed-race, but the 28-million black majority is excluded.
   There have been several nighttime bombings during the past two
weeks in the Johannesburg and Cape Town areas.
