<FIRST>r a AM-BishopCollege     08-02 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bishop College,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lankan Woman Forfeits $75,000 In Jewels After Missing Deadline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sri Lankan woman has forfeited $75,000 worth of
sapphires she put up as a deposit and still owes $100,000 after
failing to meet the deadline to buy a bankrupt college for $10
million, officials said Wednesday.
   ``We're kind of back to square one. ... It's for sale again,''
said bankruptcy court trustee Duke Salisbury.
   Predominantly black Bishop College was closed by U.S. Bankruptcy
Judge Robert C. McGuire last year when officials of the
108-year-old school couldn't raise $1.85 million needed to cover
this school year's deficit.
   The school, which sits on a 200-acre plot in south Dallas, was
saddled with $18 million in debt; faculty and staff had worked
without pay for about two years and are owed about $900,000. A
portion of the land has been appraised at about $12.6 million.
   In April, a contract to purchase the school was awarded to
Aryadesh Inc., a group represented by Panditha Sujatha Nadarajah, a
Sri Lankan woman whose attorney said she had lived in Lubbock since
1985.
   Ms. Nadarajah is an internationally known Buddhist scholar and
planned to open an international university at the school, her
attorney, A.W. Clem, said in March.
   Ms. Nadarajah put up five sapphires worth $75,000 to seal the
deal, and agreed to pay an additional $100,000 to get a four-week
extension of the original July 4 deadline.
   After missing Tuesday's deadline to come up with the $10 million
to buy the college, Salisbury said Ms. Nadarajah has forfeited the
jewels, but has yet to pay the $100,000.
   ``We will have to make demands upon her for the $100,000 cash,''
said Salisbury.
   Proceeds from the sale of the jewels will go to creditors of the
college, Salisbury said.
   Ms. Nadarajah returned to Sri Lanka in July to raise the money
and Raoul Smyth, an attorney for Salisbury, said she apparently has
had trouble getting out of the island nation off the coast of India.
   Sri Lanka has been wracked by two years of fighting between
Sinhalese extremists, angered by peace overtures made to the
country's Tamil minority and by the continuing presence of Indian
peacekeeping troops, and the Sinhalese-dominated government.
   When Salisbury recommended awarding the contract to Ms.
Nadarajah, he said: ``We have investigated her as best we can. It
seems that she does indeed have the money.''
   Ms. Nadarajah's attorney did not return phone calls Wednesday.
   Salisbury said he already had at least 10 inquiries about buying
the college Wednesday morning and hopes media attention will die
down.
   ``I've never had to conduct a business negotiation ... in front
of the likes of the media,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
