<FIRST>u w AM-S&amp;Ls     08-02 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Prepares for Action on S&amp;L Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House moved Wednesday to speed easy
passage of a taxpayer bailout of savings and loan losses as Senate
Republicans mounted a final attempt to prevent the costs from
swelling the federal deficit.
   The House Rules Committee set aside one hour of debate for
Thursday before a floor vote, anticipated to occur by noon, puts
the legislation's fate in the hands of senators deeply divided on
how to raise the $50 billion needed to close 500 insolvent S&amp;Ls and
pay off their depositors.
   Senate and House negotiators from both parties agreed last week
to President Bush's recommended massive overhaul of the way the
government regulates the nation's nearly 3,000 thrift institutions.
   And House Republicans generally have folded their opposition to
Democratic demands that the rescue money be borrowed through the
Treasury _ a move that would swell the deficit by some $9 billion
this year and $24 billion in fiscal 1990.
   However, the parties are deadlocked in the Senate, where 41
Republicans _ one more than needed to thwart the bill's approval _
have said in a letter they would hold out for Bush's elaborate
financing scheme.
   That effort was being led by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, co-author
of the 1985 Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law mandating a federal
deficit no greater than $110 billion for the next fiscal year
beginning Oct. 1.
   Bush's bailout plan would raise the deficit at most only $5
billion a year by borrowing the money through higher-interest bonds
on the private market. Critics contend the higher interest rates
would cost taxpayers a total of $4.5 billion more than necessary
over the next 30 years.
   Senate GOP Leader Bob Dole of Kansas on Tuesday threatened to
tie the S&amp;L measure to a bill raising the government's debt ceiling
above $2.8 trillion as a parliamentary tactic if the House tried to
recess for the rest of the month before the Senate votes.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., however, said Wednesday
he has no intention of recessing until after both the House and the
Senate have acted on the S&amp;L bill as well as the debt ceiling.
   Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., another co-author of the
deficit-reduction law, said he remains solidly with Gramm but added
he did not know about the other 39 GOP senators who had signed the
Texas Republican's letter.
   ``I don't know what the vote count is, I don't think anybody
does,'' Rudman said.
   However, support for Gramm and the administration's efforts was
clearly waning among House Republicans.
   ``I understand the administration's concern, but it's a hard
thing to sell when you get everything else in place and have it
hung up on that one issue,'' said House GOP Leader Bob Michel of
Illinois. ``We've got some problems with our counterparts in the
Senate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
