<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Scattered Across The South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of Hurricane Chantal produced heavy rain Wednesday
across north-central Texas, and rain also was scattered over other
sections of the South and the Northeast.
   More than 4 inches of rain fell during the morning at Ivan,
Texas, producing lowland flooding over eastern sections of Stephens
County, the National Weather Service said.
   Out to sea, Hurricane Dean had maximum sustained wind speed of
75 mph and was moving toward the west-northwest at 20 mph.
Hurricane warnings were issued for the islands of the Lesser
Antilles and Puerto Rico.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed in warm, humid,
unstable air from the Gulf Coast region to the southern Atlantic
Coast and Florida.
   An upper air disturbance produced thunderstorms that moved from
southeastern Ontario into western New York state. Showers and
thunderstorms were also scattered over northern New England.
   A cold front moved through the central Rockies and western
sections of the northern Plains. Behind the front were cooler air
and widely scattered showers, and showers and thunderstorms were
scattered ahead of the front over southeastern Wyoming and western
Nebraska.
   During the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT no rain amounts of an inch
or more were reported.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Mullan, Idaho, to 101 at Needles, Calif. Wednesday's low
in the Lower 48 states was 27 at Truckee, Calif.
   For Thursday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from south-central and eastern Texas across the Gulf Coast into
Florida. Showers and thunderstorms also were forecast from
north-central Texas across Oklahoma, eastern Kansas, the middle and
upper Mississippi Valley to the upper Great Lakes. Scattered
showers and thunderstorms were forecast over eastern New England.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted from northwestern Montana across
the Pacific Northwest to along the California coast; in the 80s
from northern New England to the northern and central Appalachians,
from the northern half of the upper Great Lakes across much of the
middle Mississippi Valley into eastern Kansas, and from Montana
into the Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah; above 100 over the
desert Southwest, inland valleys of southern California, and near
the Big Bend of the Rio Grande in Texas; and in the 90s over much
of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
