<FIRST>r w AM-Post-Contract     08-02 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Post-Contract,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Post Guild Members Approve Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Newspaper Guild at The
Washington Post on Wednesday overwhelmingly ratified a new contract
that will raise salaries at the newspaper by about $165 per week
over the next five years.
   In addition to the salary hike, the new contract includes
improvements in guild representation for the paper's 1,420 union
members, according to Lewis Diuguid, a member of the bargaining
committee. The contract was tentatively approved last Friday after
all-night negotiations.
   In addition to newsroom workers, employees in the paper's
accounting, advertising, circulation and data-processing
departments are covered by the agreement.
   The contract is the first between the paper and the guild in
nearly three years. The previous pact expired in 1986, and
newspaper officials declared that negotiations had reached an
impasse a year later.
   To protest the slow pace in the contract talks, many Post
reporters removed their bylines from stories on the two
anniversaries of the breakdown in discussions.
   The new contract raises salaries between 4 percent and 6 percent
a year, with lower-paid workers receiving a higher percentage
increase along with improvements in minimum salary scales.
   The average salary for Post reporters is more than $52,000 per
year.
</TEXT>
