<SECOND>AM-Capsized Rig, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0679,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Currents Drive Divers Off Capsized Rig</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with bodies found on rig, DELETE
outdated material; picks up 7th graf, `There were ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers on Wednesday found the bodies of three
men aboard a drilling rig that capsized while fleeing Hurricane
Chantal, and the search continued for seven missing crewmen,
officials said.
   The search of the floating rig, which overturned Monday, was
delayed earlier in the day by strong currents and high seas.
   The bodies were recovered from the vessel's crew quarters, said
Chevron spokesman Jonathan Lifa.
   Coast Guard officials earlier speculated that crewmen may have
survived the accident if they were trapped in the watertight crew
quarters, but did not estimate how long the men could live on a
limited amount of air.
   Lifa said he didn't know what condition the crew quarters were
in.
   The names of the dead were being withheld pending notification
of their families, Lifa said.
   The search had to be abandoned Monday because of high seas and
strong wind stirred up by Chantal. Chevron, which had leased the
rig and hired the rescue divers, and the Coast Guard sent vessels
to resume the search Tuesday after Chantal blew ashore in Texas and
weakened to a tropical depression.
   There were conflicting reports about where the missing men were
last seen _ in the water or in the watertight crew's quarters
submerged in about 30 feet of water _ said Coast Guard Petty
Officer Glenn LaMont in New Orleans.
   The technical name for the rig is a lift boat. It has
retractable legs that anchor it to the sea bottom when in use, and
raise out of the way to allow the rig to be floated to a new
location.
   The legs were retracted and it was headed to shore early Monday,
trying to avoid Chantal, when it capsized.
   Three survivors were taken aboard a fishing vessel Monday and a
fourth was rescued by helicopter.
</TEXT>
