<HEAD>Relatives of Pan Am Victims Push for Congressional Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several angry relatives of victims lost in the
downing of Pan Am Flight 103 renewed their demand for a
wide-ranging congressional investigation Wednesday, saying their
pleas for more information have been virtually ignored.
   ``It is now four months since we met with President Bush and all
100 senators to request an investigation of the weak security and
the failure to act on high-level warnings issued to the FAA, the
State Department and the airline'' before the Dec. 21 incident,
said Paul Hudson, father of Melina Hudson, one of the victims.
   ``We are surprised and disappointed that the Bush administration
has adamantly opposed a congressional investigation or the
appointment of a special commission at every turn,'' Hudson told a
news conference.
   ``We also cannot understand why Congress has delayed taking any
action on their commitment to conduct a full-scale investigation of
this, the worst act of terrorism against civilians in our
history,'' he said.
   Investigators believe a mid-flight explosion downed the jet over
Lockerbie, Scotland, killing 270 people, including 189 Americans.
   Bush told the relatives earlier this year he had asked
Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner to work with them on a
review of airline security procedures.
   But in his statement Wednesday Hudson asked, ``Is it fear of
what might be disclosed as to the culpability of our allies, or is
this another example of non-action in the war against terrorism by
the U.S. government?''
   Rosemary Wolfe, stepmother of Pan Am victim Miriam Wolfe, said,
``We need an investigation now and urge the 60 to 70 senators and
many members of the House, who have told us they support an
investigation, to pass legislation now.''
