<FIRST>u i AM-Havel 2ndLd-Writethru a0668 08-02 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Havel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0668,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Playwright, Voted on Board of PEN Group, Arrested in Prague</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to include info on PEN chapter. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Writers in Czechoslovakia said Wednesday
the PEN branch was being allowed to reopen and Vaclav Havel would
be on the board, but reports from Prague said police had detained
the prominent, banned playwright.
   Ivan Klima, a dissident writer, said in Prague about 20
colleagues gathered on Tuesday and elected a new PEN governing
board. Klima said both he and Havel were on the panel, which also
included authors sanctioned by Czechoslovia's strict communist
regime.
   Klima was banned after a Soviet-led invasion crushed the 1968
``Prague spring'' of reforms. The Czech branch of the international
writers' club became dormant around 1971 after purges of Communist
Party members, including many writers.
   Dissident sources and a West German Embassy spokesman in Prague
said Havel was detained Wednesday while on his way to the embassy
for lunch with Ambassador Hermann Huber.
   It was the second day in a row Havel was picked up. Police
detained him for about three hours Tuesday.
   Sources in Prague said by telephone they did not know whether
Havel was released later Wednesday.
   In Bonn, West German Foreign Ministry spokesman Otto Lampe said
his government considered the detention an ``extremely serious''
incident and had lodged a formal protest.
   Havel was sentenced to eight months in jail earlier this year,
but released on parole about midway through the term after domestic
and foreign protests.
   On Tuesday, Klima said, police freed Havel in time for him to
appear at the end of the meeting.
   He said police summoned two members of the human rights group
Charter 77, Eva Kanturkova and Milan Simecka, for questioning at
the same time as the meeting, so they were unable to attend.
   CTK, the official Czechoslovak news agency, reported the PEN
reorganization briefly.
   Klima said the 10 members of the new board included six
dissident or nonconformist writers and four who were officially
sanctioned. CTK did not mentioned the board's makeup.
   Jiri Mucha, an official writers, was elected board chairman in
what Klima described as a compromise.
   Reviving the PEN chapter is the first joint official-dissident
literary venture in almost 20 years. Klima said he hoped the club
could negotiate with authorities on publishing forbidden books and
lifting bans on writers.
   Authorities have made small moves in the past year toward
artistic liberalization. Books by Franz Kafka have appeared for
only the second time since the ``Prague spring'' and bans were
removed from several movies, plays and rock bands.
   Officials say Havel and some other writers have remained under
prohibition because of their refusal to renounce political
activities.
   In May, the 60-chapter international PEN association voted
unanmously to admit a Soviet chapter, ending a long quarrel with
Moscow.
   Soviet participation in the 10,000-member group has been an
issue since PEN turned down an application in 1924.
   PEN champions freedom of expression for writers and had stayed
out of the Soviet Union because of its persecution of writers and
other intellectuals. The change of heart came after Mikhail S.
Gorbachev introduced more liberal policies.
</TEXT>
