<FIRST>u i AM-Europe-Fires     08-02 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europe-Fires,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fires Along the Riviera Force Tourists to Flee; 2 Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CAN2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARSEILLE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of firefighters struggled
Wednesday to contain forest fires that killed two tourists in
Corsica, forced the evacuation of thousands of people and destroyed
dozens of homes on the French Riviera.
   The fires threatened some of the most popular vacation areas in
southern France.
   Flames shot up near the village of Bormes-Les-Mimosas, west of
Toulon, forcing evacuation of a camping site. Firefighters used
planes to dump water on that blaze.
   The Interior Ministry said the fires, fanned by the region's
usually strong winds, have devastated about 50,000 acres of forest
and brush land.
   It said the winds had combined with drought to make the work of
firefighters ``very difficult.'' The firefighters had been trying
to stop advancing flames for three days, but the ministry said new
fires were breaking out in many places.
   Two Italian tourists were killed Monday when they drove their
car into a wall of fire in northern Corsica, an island off the
French coast, officials said.
   Nearly 25,000 acres have burned there, the ministry said. Other
fires were spreading along the coast of southern France, especially
around Marseille and Toulon.
   More than 4,000 people were evacuated northwest of Marseille and
about 50 homes and cottages were destroyed.
   Fires also destroyed 62 miles of telephone cable and 1,000
poles, and up to 4,000 homes were without service, the telephone
company said.
   Electricity of France said thousands of electric lines were cut
Tuesday and Wednesday at an estimated damage of up to $795,000.
   Several people were detained for questioning in the
Bouches-du-Rhone region around Marseille as authorities tried to
determine if arson played a role in the more than 100 separate
fires.
   In Corsica, shepherds are widely suspected of setting fires to
open land and improve next year's grazing.
   In Sardinia, hundreds of firefighters aided by helicopters and
aircraft battled wind-whipped brush fires that have killed four
people. The fires have burned more than 2,500 acres of land in the
island's Sassari Province.
   An Italian woman airlifted to a Rome hospital died Wednesday.
Another woman evacuated to the hospital Tuesday was reported in
critical condition.
   Three others have died since the fires began Tuesday.
</TEXT>
