<FIRST>r w AM-Lucas 1stLd-Writethru a0691 08-02 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0691,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Says Lucas Lost Because He Failed ``Litmus Test''</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS one graf after 17th graf pvs, But presidential, to show
Lucas considered for other jobs also</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said
Wednesday that William Lucas didn't win Senate Judiciary Committee
approval to be civil rights chief because he failed a ``litmus
test'' on discrimination issues.
   The attorney general said he discounted the significance of
criticism by several Democrats that Lucas lacked expertise for the
job, saying the Detroit Republican lost Tuesday's vote because he
refused to criticize recent Supreme Court decisions on civil rights.
   ``That was the reason expressed by one of the members of the
Judiciary Committe on the Democratic side,'' Thornburgh said.
   ``His reason for not supporting Mr. Lucas was that Mr. Lucas
supported the recent Supreme Court decisions on civil rights,'' the
attorney general said in an apparent reference to Sen. Paul Simon,
D-Ill.
   Civil rights lawyers have bemoaned the court decisions they say
will make it harder for discrimination victims to win bias suits in
court.
   Thornburgh said ``Mr. Lucas supported the views of the president
and the attorney general in this regard'' when he testified that no
legislation was needed at this time to overturn the rulings.
   ``I find it somewhat bizarre to expect an appointee of the
president to begin his career in opposition to the president in an
important area of the law,'' Thornburgh said.
   ``The fact that they have laid down as a litmus test that the
prospective nominee must refuse to support Supreme Court decisions
will make it difficult for us to walk the fine line that that view
implies,'' the attorney general said.
   Before Tuesday's vote, Simon cited Lucas' support of the high
court rulings during confirmation hearings as his reason for voting
against the nomination.
   But other Democrats said Lucas' lack of legal experience and
knowledge of civil rights laws was the basis for their votes
against the nomination.
   Simon said Lucas' views on the Supreme Court rulings ``are not
the test. But his answers were a symptom.''
   ``Bill Lucas is a fine person,'' Simon said, ``but the chief
civil rights enforcement officer of the land must have a firm grasp
of the laws he oversees and a firm commitment to vigorously enforce
those laws.''
   Lucas, 61, a former sheriff and chief executive of Wayne County,
Mich., has never tried a court case. The panel refused Tuesday on a
pair of 7-7 votes to recommend Lucas' nomination or send it to the
Senate floor for further consideration.
   The votes virtually killed Lucas' chances for Senate
confirmation but Thornburgh said the Justice Department was
considering the option of giving Lucas a so-called recess
appointment after Congress goes out of session Friday.
   ``I think we are going to look at every option and consult with
the White House,'' the attorney general told reporters after
testifying before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
   Congressional and White House sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity, say it is unlikely that President Bush would antagonize
the Senate by appointing Lucas to the job while Congress takes its
summer recess. Such an interim appointment would be in effect until
Congress' adjournment in 1990.
   But presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said ``we are still
assessing our options.''
   An official said the administration is also considering whether
to name Lucas to another post that does not require Senate approval.
   Thornburgh said the Justice Department still has a pool of
applicants for the job of assistant attorney general for civil
rights from which Lucas' name was selected.
   ``Those will be re-evaluated in the light of his failure to get
a vote on the Senate floor,'' Thornburgh said.
   The threat of a recess appointment could backfire. Under Senate
rules, all nominations awaiting confirmation are sent back to the
White House when Congress goes into recess.
   The Senate, however, traditionally waives this rule by unanimous
consent of its members when the White House pledges not to make
recess appointments.
   Without such a promise, the Senate could send all 123 of Bush's
nominations now pending on Capitol Hill back to the White House and
begin confirmation proceedings anew in September.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
