<FIRST>u a AM-PlaneEmergency 2ndLd-Writethru a0751 08-02 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Emergency, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0751,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Piedmont Jet Lands Safely After Landing Gear Jams</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 2nd to UPDATE with NTSB investigator saying
he doesn't know when chock was left in landing gear, other details. Picks
up 3rd graf pvs, `Passengers praised...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos GBO2, XASB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM FOREMAN Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Piedmont Airlines jet dragged its left
wing and engine down a runway during an emergency landing Wednesday
after part of its landing gear jammed, but none of the 100 people
aboard was injured.
   ``I've had worse landings on regular flights,'' said passenger
Tammy Rudd, 26, of Washington, D.C.
   The left landing gear could not be lowered because of a wheel
chock that had lodged in the landing gear bay, said National
Transportation Safety Board investigator Phillip Powell.
   He said he did not know how or when the rubber chock, which is
used to hold planes in place on the ground, might have been wedged
there. A Piedmont spokesman said wheel chocks are supposed to be
left on the ground.
   ABC News reported that investigators believe mechanics at
Washington National Airport might have accidentally left the chock
in the plane's landing gear well.
   Passengers praised the crew and the pilot, whom Piedmont refused
to identify.
   ``It was kind of like a roller-coaster, kind of fun,'' said Army
Sgt. Debbie McDorman of Washington, D.C. She said the passengers
were calm and the landing ``was just as smooth as if he was on
wheels.''
   The Boeing 737-400 carried 94 passengers and six crew, including
the pilot, said Piedmont spokesman David Shipley. Piedmont took
delivery of the jetliner in December 1988 and has had no problems
with it or with the 737-400 fleet in general, Shipley said.
   The plane was bound for Charlotte from Washington National
Airport, but was diverted to Greensboro, where Piedmont has a
maintenance hangar, after a cockpit light showed the landing gear
wasn't locked, Shipley said.
   The pilot ``circled for better than an hour in an attempt to get
all the gear down,'' said Federal Aviation Administration spokesman
Roger Myers. The pilot got the nose wheel and right landing gear
down, but not the left gear, Myers said.
   During maneuvers to shake loose the landing gear and use up
fuel, the jetliner did a touch-and-go on one wheel _ contacting the
runway before immediately taking off again.
   Finally, the plane was eased down to the ground near the
beginning of the 10,000-foot runway. After the right main landing
gear touched down, the left wing tilted slowly toward the ground,
tapping it twice before the wing and its engine assembly dragged
the runway.
   Emergency vehicles lined the runway after the airport was closed
to other traffic.
   There was a brief flash of flame and smoke, apparently from a
tire, and the plane slid in a straight line, coming to rest about a
third of the way down the runway.
   Passengers slid down emergency chutes. Emergency crews sprayed
foam on the wing and engine.
   Carolyn Long said she was moved from her seat, which was located
on an emergency exit so that someone stronger could handle the door
once the plane landed.
   ``They had prepared us with this brace procedure,'' Mrs. Long
said, crossing her arms over her head to demonstrate the
instructions. ``I braced and braced.''
   Some passengers were still shaking and soaked in sweat after
they were bused to the terminal from the runway.
   Alfred Roscoe, also of Washington, D.C., had but one comment
when he emerged from the plane: ``Thank God.''
   He said the pilot ``did a very beautiful job.''
   ``I went to the pilot when we got off'' and flashed him a
thumbs-up sign, said passenger Richard Kochan.
   Kochan said the pilot looked at him, then pointed to the sky.
   ``I think the crew deserves a tremendous amount of praise,''
said Piedmont spokeswoman Susan Young. ``It shows a tremendous
amount of professionalism.'' She said the pilot had flown 20 years
for Piedmont.
   Boeing, which delivered the plane to Piedmont on Nov. 14, 1988,
will not send a crash investigation team, said spokesman Tom Cole
in Seattle.
   On Saturday, the Piedmont name will disappear and all planes
will bear USAir markings. Piedmont and USAir have been subsidiaries
of USAir Group for two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
