<FIRST>u w AM-Abortion-DC 2ndLd-Writethru a0760 08-02 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-DC, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0760,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Defeats Abortion Restrictions in Capital</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS new 5th graf, The House, with vote on final passage expected
Thursday; ADDS three grafs after 13th graf pvs ``This is, with Dornan comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An emotionally divided House on Wednesday
rejected an effort to tighten abortion restrictions in the District
of Columbia, the first congressional test on the subject since a
Supreme Court ruling last month permitting states to impose new
limits.
   On a surprising 219-206 vote that evoked hugs and hoots of cheer
on the House floor by supporters of the right to abortion, the
lawmakers rejected a proposal that would have banned all government
spending on abortions in the capital.
   The vote was a reversal of House sentiment last year, when the
legislators voted 222-186 to ban public spending on the procedures.
Abortion activists said it was the first time since 1980 the House
had refused to restrict government spending for abortion.
   The defeated provision, an amendment to a spending bill for the
fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 that forms Washington's municipal
budget, was proposed by Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif. The
prohibition would have included cases in which the mother's life is
in danger or pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
   The House recessed for the day and left the vote on final
passage of the overall bill for Thursday. That left anti-abortion
lawmakers one more chance to find votes and try to salvage their
proposal, perhaps by defeating the entire spending measure.
   Defeat of the amendment left intact abortion provisions in the
bill which are more liberal than current law. The bill would allow
the district to spend its own funds for abortions and to use
federal funds if the pregnancy was the result of rape or incest or
if the mother's life was in danger. Current law, which expires
Sept. 30, contains a ban on spending either federal or district
funds unless the mother's life is threatened.
   Quoting the hospitalized Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., one of the
House's foremost abortion opponents, Dornan said, ``This is not
government intervention. The government's first duty is to protect
the weak from the strong.''
   Dornan and his supporters said they preferred to include an
exception for mothers whose lives are threatened, but did not
because it would have left their amendment vulnerable to being
struck down for procedural reasons.
   Opponents to Dornan's language warned that the roll call would
supply a hit list of lawmakers for voters who support the freedom
to choose abortions.
   ``All across the country, a newly energized pro-choice movement
is going to say to supporters of amendments like this, `If you are
anti-choice, when we the voters go to the ballot box, we won't
choose you,''' Rep. Les AuCoin, D-Ore., said before the vote.
   Jubilant pro-choice lawmakers readily conceded that they had not
expected to win, but attributed the surprise victory to a new alarm
among voters triggered by the Supreme Court's recent decision
restricting women's constitutional right to abortion.
   After the vote, AuCoin said: ``It was clear to members that this
is an issue on which they're going to be held accountable. This
vote was a dramatic turn, and it clearly reflects what's happening
in the country. It's a sea change.''
   The court's decision ``was really a wake-up call'' to abortion
defenders, said Rep. Pat Schroeder, D-Colo. House members ``must be
starting to hear from people back home.''
   ``This is a barometer,'' said Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif. ``The
winds are blowing, and they're blowing in our direction.''
   Dornan blamed his defeat on the new attention the Supreme Court
ruling has brought to abortion, the election of several freshmen
who favor liberalized abortion laws, and a reluctance by some
lawmakers to vote for a measure containing no exception for
endangered mothers.
   He noted that earlier Thursday the House had overwhelmingly
approved a separate spending bill that barred the Department of
Health and Human Services from providing any funds for abortions,
except for instances when the woman's life is at stake.
   ``I'm not worried about losing anything else,'' he said.
   Eleanor Smeal, president of the Fund for the Feminist Majority
and a former president of the National Organization for Women, was
elated.
   ``We're on a roll. Thirty-three votes switched since 1980. ...
We've marched in the streets, surged in the polls and challenged
both parties,'' Ms. Smeal said.
   On July 3, the Supreme Court gave states greater powers to
restrict abortions, allowing them to ban public employees or
facilities from participating in abortions, even when patients are
willing to pay for them.
</TEXT>
