<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 2020EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DefenseBill 4thLd-Writethru a0776-a0777-052015:3508-02riAM-AfghanistseBill
08-02 1121</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Bill, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0776-a0777-a0752,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Defense Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs; INSERTS graf 15: ``Voting against,'' with the
four opponents. This graf serves in lieu of a roll call</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Wednesday approved a $295
billion defense bill that leaves President Bush's strategic
programs such as Star Wars and the B-2 bomber relatively intact,
but backs an aircraft Bush sought to kill.
   ``The basic goals of the president was met,'' said Sen. John
Warner of Virginia, ranking Republican on the Senate Armed Services
Committee, prior to final passage of the legislation.
   By a vote of 95-4, the Senate approved its version of the
defense authorization bill for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 _ a
blueprint that bears no resemblance to House legislation that
gutted or severely cut the president's big-ticket weapons systems.
   The Senate bill endorses the president's two mobile-missile
plan, including the request of $1.1 billion for the MX
rail-garrison and $100 million for the Midgetman.
   The legislation also makes a modest cut of $400 million in the
$4.9 billion request for Star Wars and trims $300 million from the
$4.7 billion proposal for the B-2 stealth bomber.
   The Senate backed the costly bomber, priced at $530 million a
copy, if it meets flight test and radar-evasion standards, and
accepted Bush's decision to cancel the F-14D Tomcat jet fighter.
   But the chamber diverged from the president on the Marine Corps'
V-22 Osprey, the tilt-rotor assault transport that takes off like a
helicopter but can fly like a plane. The Senate approved $255
million in research and development for the Bell-Boeing aircraft.
   The House and Senate meet in conference in early September to
complete a final version of the two defense blueprints the chambers
have crafted. The final product will include $295 billion for the
Defense Department, plus $10 billion for the Department of Energy.
   ``We have more profound differences this year than we've had in
a long, long time,'' said Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the
Senate Armed Services Committee. ``We face a difficult conference
with the House on this bill.''
   The money still has to be dispersed through appropriations bills.
   Last week, the House slashed $1.8 billion from the Star Wars
request, limited production of the B-2 bomber to two planes next
year and two the year after that _ half what the administration
sought, required the Pentagon to come up with a program cheaper
than $70 billion for the planned 132 planes and cut $502 million
from the MX missile.
   The House also eliminated all $100 million for the Midgetman and
restored the V-22 Osprey and the F-14D jet fighter, the two planes
Bush proposed canceling.
   Overwhelming Senate approval of the bill was not without some
dissent.
   ``Our motto ought to be: In Bombs We Trust. That's our national
ethic _ that is the example we are setting _ here on this floor,''
said Sen. Mark Hatfield, the Oregon Republican who entered Congress
during the Vietnam War and was one of the first serviceman on the
scene after the atom bomb was dropped on Hiroshima.
   Voting against were Sens. Kent Conrad, D-N.D.; Tom Harkin,
D-Iowa; Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, and Hatfield. Sen. Donald
Riegle, D-Mich., did not vote.
   In other developments on the bill, which kept lawmakers will
past midnight on Wednesday and then throughout the day, senators:
   _Approved by voice vote a non-binding resolution urging Bush to
continue development of the Marine Corps' V-22 Osprey, the
tilt-rotor aircraft the administration sought to cancel. The
defense bill includes $255 million for research and development of
the Bell-Boeing V-22, which takes off like a helicopter but can fly
like a plane.
   _By voice vote, the Senate approved an amendment by Sen. Trent
Lott, R-Miss., requiring graduates of the nation's military
academies to serve six years of service after graduation rather
than the eight years the bill would have required. The current
requirement is five years. Lott argued that the eight-year
requirement would drive applicants away from the academies.
   The effort to table the amendment failed 55-45 prior to the
voice vote. There is no comparable provision in the House version
of the bill.
   _Accepted by voice vote a non-binding resolution instructing the
CIA and Defense Department to report by Sept. 1 on how best to
locate and rescue American hostages in Lebanon. The report must
detail how additional money and agents can be used to find the
hostages and win their release.
   _Voted 53-44 against a plan to spend $100 million for the
effective deployment of 100 ground-based interceptor missiles in
Grand Forks, N.D., by 1995. The interceptors, part of the
Accidental Launch Protection System, would have been used against
sudden terrorist missile attacks.
   _Approved a series of ``burden-sharing'' amendments aimed at
increasing the contributions to defense by U.S. allies in Europe
and Asia.
   _Declined to vote on a proposal to restore former Marine Lt.
Col. Oliver L. North's $23,000 pension. North has been convicted on
three felony counts in the Iran-Contra affair, and the Senate
ordered its Judiciary Committee to hold hearings on the subject of
his pension.
   The defense bill legislation contains $200 million for
anti-satellite weapons in addition to unspecified amounts in the
Star Wars budget.
   Sens. John Kerry, D-Mass., and James Jeffords, R-Vt., had
proposed restrictions to bar such tests unless the administration
could certify that the Soviets had engaged in tests of their own,
had refused to bargain in good faith in limitations and had blocked
international verification efforts.
   The efforts to block attempts to chip away at Bush's defense
package were evident earlier this morning when the Senate avoided a
vote on an amendment transferring $450 million from the
administration's $4.9 billion request for the Star Wars
anti-missile shield to the war on drugs.
   Instead, the Senate approved a compromise drafted by Sen. Sam
Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Armed Services Committee, that would
shift unspent balances in federal programs left over at the end of
the fiscal year ending Sept. 30 to the anti-drug effort.
   The measure exempts entitlement programs, including Social
Security, Medicare, and subsidized housing. But all other
government programs and agencies, including the Defense Department,
would be compelled to contribute.
   The Senate has sought to avoid following the House lead in
gutting or severely cutting back Bush's strategic programs. Last
week the House voted to cut $1.8 billion from Star Wars, impose
strict limitations on the B-2 stealth bomber, slash $502 million
from the $1.1 billion request for the MX nuclear missile and
eliminate all $100 million for the Midgetman missile.
   The House and Senate meet in conference in early September to
complete a final version of the two defense blueprints the chambers
have crafted.
</TEXT>
