<FIRST>u i AM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru   08-02 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0674,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Detained For Questioning on Lawmaker's Trip North</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 graf to UPDATE with Kim released, says he's not
involved; picks up 4th pvs, `Government officials...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security agents detained opposition
leader Kim Dae-jung on Wednesday and released him 22 hours later
after questioning on whether he was involved in a lawmaker's secret
trip to North Korea.
   Following his release Thursday, Kim told a news conference that
he was cleared of any suspicion.
   Clashes occurred Wednesday near the police station where he was
held when about 100 Kim supporters were stopped by hundreds of riot
police. Two of the protesters were injured.
   Investigators from the Agency for National Security Planning had
questioned Kim, head of the Party for Peace and Democracy, and
lawmaker Moon Dong-hwan after taking him from his party
headquarters to the downtown police station.
   Moon was also released, but there were no reports he spoke about
his investigation.
   Government officials said Kim was investigated to determine
whether he was involved in an unauthorized trip to North Korea by
Suh Kyung-won, a former party lawmaker jailed on charges of
espionage and security violations.
   The government prohibits any unofficial contacts with North
Korea.
   Kim, who ran twice for the presidency, has denied any
involvement in Suh's trip and charged the government with political
harassment.
   Suh was expelled from the party after his June 28 arrest on
charges of espionage for allegedly accepting $120,000 from
communist agents.
   Moon, the other lawmaker questioned, is a senior party member
and younger brother of Presbyterian minister Moon Ik-hwan, a
dissident clergyman who also defied the travel ban and visited
North Korea. The elder Moon is in jail.
   Hundreds of party members and supporters chanted Kim's name and
anti-government slogans when intelligence agents took Kim and Moon
away Wednesday.
   Shouting ``Disband the NSP!'' in reference to the national
security agency, they marched around their party headquarters and
briefly stopped the agents. The opposition leader smiled and waved
as he left in his car.
   Party spokesman Lee Sang-soo said that with Kim's detention, the
national security agency's ``scheme to suppress and destroy the
party has reached the extreme.''
   The intelligence agency earlier said it wanted to question Kim
about how Suh, a dissident farmer, joined the opposition party and
gained access to the opposition leader.
   At least 10 people have been jailed since Suh's arrest.
   In another development, North Korean news reports said a
visiting South Korean student has ended a five-day hunger strike
she staged after the U.N. Command guarding the border said they
would not let her return through the border village of Panmunjom.
   Im Su-kyong vowed to cross the border Aug. 15 in a demonstration
for unification and asked the South Korean government and the
U.S.-led U.N. Command to allow her safe passage.
   South Korean officials have said she will be arrested on her
return.
   ``I consider that the hunger strike ended in a great victory,''
the official Korean Central News Agency quoted Miss Im as saying.
``I will wage a struggle ... for my return home.''
   The U.N. Command has not blocked the student's return home, but
said they would consider an unauthorized crossing of the border a
violation of the armistice agreement that ended the 1950-53 Korean
War.
   Miss Im visited North Korea to attend the July 1-8 World
Festival of Youth and Students. She then joined a march from Mount
Paekdu, at the northern end of North Korea, to the border village.
   Korea was divided in 1945 after World War II. The 16-nation U.N.
Command fought on South Korea's side in the Korean War.
</TEXT>
