<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     08-02 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Rented Houses Can Be Destroyed, 13 Wounded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Israeli Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that
the army can destroy the homes of Palestinians suspected of
anti-Israeli activities even if they are rented.
   The decision followed by just four days a Supreme Court ruling
that said the army must give Palestinians an opportunity to appeal
before destroying their homes.
   In the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, 13 Palestinians were
shot and wounded in stone-throwing clashes with troops, hospitals
reported.
   A Palestinian prisoner, Jihad Abdel Imadi, was seriously beaten
by fellow inmates at Israeli's Ketziot detention center in the
southern Negev desert, the army said. It said it was investigating
the circumstances of the incident.
   The Supreme Court ruling came in response to a case brought by
an Arab landlord in the West Bank town of Tulkarem, the independent
Itim news agency reported.
   The landlord, Ahmed Khalil Jumail, said he rented an apartment
to Mustafa Omar, who has been charged with throwing Molotov
cocktails at an army vehicle and at the house of a Palestinian
suspected of collaborating with Israel.
   Jumail said that even though he had no connection with Omar's
alleged activities, the Defense Ministry had ordered his property
destroyed.
   Meir Shamgar, the court president, ruled that if sanctions could
not be taken against rental property, it would ``negate all the
deterrent power that comes from the usage of the emergency defense
regulations,'' Itim said.
   He said, however, that Jumail's property should be sealed and
not destroyed.
   Israeli forces have blown up or torn down at least 225 houses in
the occupied territories since the start of the Palestinian
uprising against Israeli rule 19 months ago. At least 527
Palestinians and 38 Israelis have died in the uprising.
   The United States and international human rights groups have
called for an end to the practice, saying that it is carried out
without due process of the law. In many cases, property is
destroyed before the suspect is either charged or tried.
</TEXT>
