<FIRST>r a AM-LakeDerail     08-02 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lake Derail,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fuel Spill Hits Beaches; Governor Demands Railroad Pay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB ANEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITEFISH, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diesel fuel spilled into Whitefish Lake
by a train derailment began washing up on beaches and shores near
this resort community Wednesday and residents complained that the
cleanup effort was halfhearted.
   Gov. Stan Stephens toured the site by helicopter and said
Burlington Northern Railroad would be held accountable for
``anything that's been adversely impacted that has a cost to it,''
as well as all cleanup costs.
   BN Vice President Bill Francis said the railroad would pay all
costs ``legally that we need to.''
   BN continued to pump diesel oil remaining in tanker cars that
landed in the lake, but said all leaks had been plugged by divers
and no more oil was spilling. The railroad estimated 10,000 gallons
had spilled since Monday's derailment.
   Twenty-nine cars of a 100-car train derailed Monday four miles
north of Whitefish in northwestern Montana, and several cars,
including the fuel-carrying tankers, went down a 100-foot
embankment into Whitefish Lake. No injuries were reported.
   Francis estimated the cost of the derailment alone at $557,000,
but said he has no estimate on cleanup costs.
   A helicopter survey Wednesday revealed that about half the
3,350-acre lake was covered with the telltale rainbow sheen of a
thin oil slick, and oil began washing ashore on the populated
southern and eastern banks.
   ``It's awful,'' said Dean Olafson, who lives on the eastern
shore. ``We've been mopping all morning and the winds changed and
now it's just come back in again.''
   Olafson complained that there had been too little response to
the spill.
   ``The way they react is just wrong,'' Olafson said. ``They're
always looking for the cheap way out, and it ends up being more
expensive.''
   The governor said he was ``deeply saddened'' by the sight,
noting he and his family have vacationed at the lake for years.
   The tank cars should be pulled out of the water sometime
Thursday, said Gus Melonas, BN's Montana spokesman.
   The derailment closed BN's main line from Minneapolis to
Seattle, forcing freight trains to be rerouted south, and Amtrak
had to bus passengers from its Empire Builder train around the
derailment area.
</TEXT>
