<FIRST>r w AM-TravelAdvisories     08-02 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Travel Advisories,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Questions U.S. Travel Advisories In Wake Of Kenya Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman Wednesday questioned how the
State Department issues travel advisories, saying a warning should
have been posted for Kenya before a Connecticut woman became the
latest tourist killed in a recent string of ambushes.
   ``While the State Department did respond the following day by
placing Kenya on the travel advisory list, I must seriously
question why this action was not taken earlier,'' Rep. John G.
Rowland, R-Conn., said in a letter to Secretary of State James A.
Baker III.
   Three German tourists were wounded in an ambush in April, two
French tourists were killed by ivory poachers in early July and two
Americans were beaten while riding horseback last week, Rowland
said.
   ``It is my understanding that incidents such as the above weigh
heaviest in any decision to place a nation on the travel advisory
list,'' the congressman said. ``American citizens deserve to be
informed of any dangers they face as international travelers.''
   An advisory for Kenya was not issued until after Marie Ferraro,
50, of Bethany, Conn., was shot to death last Thursday by two
bandits armed with assault rifles who fired at a van carrying a
Connecticut Audubon Society wildlife tour group.
   ``My saddness and concern stem from this tragic loss of life and
the possibility that proper risk notification was not given,''
Rowland said.
   The congressman requested a detailed explanation of the
decision-making process for travel advisories and urged an
``in-depth review'' by the department of its procedures.
   A spokeswoman for the State Department's Bureau of Consular
Affairs referred to a March press release that read in part,
``Travel advisories which describe a potential for violence and
physical danger usually reflect a trend or pattern of violence over
a period of time in which the government of the country involved is
unwilling or unable to afford normal protection.''
</TEXT>
