<DOCNO> AP890802-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 2123EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Students     08-02 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Students,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Expelled for Leading University Demonstration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese student who helped stage a
demonstration at Beijing University last month has been expelled
and refused his diploma, university officials said.
   A public announcement, posted on bulletin boards once festooned
with the posters of the student-led pro-democracy movement, said
Xiong Dayong, 22, had broken martial law regulations banning
unauthorized gatherings.
   The notice, dated July 25, said Xiong, a fourth-year student of
Chinese and a member of the Communist Party's Youth League, had
``incited other students to cause trouble by breaking martial law
restrictions.''
   It also accused Xiong of being a ``known criminal'' who had
stolen three bicycles this summer and caused a drunken brawl last
year.
   With no diploma and an expulsion on his record, Xiong will have
difficulty finding work.
   On July 23, from 300 to 400 students sang and beat pots and pans
to mourn classmates killed June 3-4 when troops opened fire on
student protesters and supporters.
   China has said 200-300 people died in the military assault, but
Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence sources said the death
toll may have been as high as 3,000.
   The students said they held the July 23 demonstration because
they felt oppressed by the ideological study classes they were
forced to attend following the military crackdown. They were also
protesting because some of them were refused permission to join the
work units to which they were earlier assigned.
   Most college graduates in China are assigned jobs by the
government. Most of the 32,000 graduates from 80 universities and
colleges in Beijing this year have been accepted by their assigned
units, the official Xinhua news agency reported Wednesday.
   The report said more than 1,000 graduates, however, had not
found appropriate jobs, in part because some foreign companies,
party schools, judicial departments, travel agencies and the
military had dropped plans to accept more than 300 students.
   The report did not say whether the refusals were due to
political considerations arising from participation in the
pro-democracy demonstrations this spring, which were initiated and
led by students from Beijing universities.
   It quoted Han Xueping, head of the student department of the
Beijing Higher Education Bureau, as saying that all graduates in
Beijing had undergone three weeks of political study to review
their thought and actions during the student protests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
