<FIRST>r w AM-Guard-Citizenship     08-02 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guard-Citizenship,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Files Complaint To Strip Man Of Citizenship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department started proceedings
Wednesday to strip a former Akron, Ohio of his citizenship because
he failed to disclose that he was a Nazi concentration camp guard.
   A complaint was filed in U.S. District Court in Washington
against Jakob F. Denzinger, who became a naturalized citizen in
Akron in 1972.
   Denzinger, 65, is believed to have left the country, the Justice
Department said in a prepared statement.
   The government alleged that Denzinger guarded prisoners at slave
labor sites, manned watchtowers and ``assisted in the persecution
of those interned.''
   According to the complaint, Denzinger was born in Yugoslavia,
entered the Waffen SS in 1941 and was an armed guard at several
concentration camps, including the Auschwitz death camp.
   To date, U.S. citizenship has been revoked from 30 World War
II-era criminals, including 27 who have been deported, said the
Office of Special Investigations, which builds the cases against
suspected Nazi persecutors.
