<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Moldavia     08-02 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Moldavia,0274</SECOND>
<UNK>Moldavians Protest Stalin-Hitler Pact</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people gathered in Kishinev, the
capital of Soviet Moldavia, Wednesday to condemn the Soviet
annexation of their homeland in a secret pact between Josef Stalin
and Adolf Hitler, an activist said.
   Yuri Rozhgo said from Kishinev that demonstrators demanded that
the Soviet government declare the August 1939 pact to be null.
   A Moscow legislative commission is thought to be within days of
declaring void the agreement that divided Eastern Europe before
World War II into Soviet and German spheres of influence. The
Kremlin had denied for years that any such pact existed.
   Activists in the Baltic republics of Lithuania, Latvia and
Estonia have pushed for such a decision for more than two years.
Rozhgo said Moldavia also came under Soviet control because of the
pact.
   Rozhgo, a member of the Moldavian People's Front, said that
between 2,000 and 3,000 people gathered in central Kishinev to mark
Wednesday's 49th anniversary of the Moldavian Soviet republic.
Soviet soldiers occupied the small republic bordering Romania on
June 28, 1940.
   Rozhgo said the People's Front was told that members of Vatra, a
group promoting Moldavian culture, were beaten by police when they
tried to gather in Bendery, southeast of Kishinev.
   Demonstrations have swept the republic this year as ethnic
Moldavians, who are closely related to Romanians, demand
restoration of the Latin alphabet and their native language. The
language was converted to Russian letters after the Soviet takeover.
   The republic's Supreme Soviet, or legislature, is to meet Aug.
28 to consider a law that would make Moldavian the official
language.
