<FIRST>r a AM-ObsessedFan     08-02 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obsessed Fan,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Studio Visit Foretold Suspect's `Obsession,' Guard Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man accused of killing ``My Sister
Sam'' star Rebecca Schaeffer was once thrown out of the TV studio
where she was working after a guard noticed ``something haywire''
about him, the guard said.
   Robert John Bardo, 19, came to the studio lot two years ago with
a teddy bear and a bouquet, and begged to see the actress, said
John Egger, chief of security for The Burbank Studios.
   Egger said he took Bardo off the lot and drove him to the
run-down motel in Hollywood where the youth was staying. He said
Bardo promised to return home to Tucson, Ariz., and that Bardo
called him the next day to say he was about to board a bus going
there.
   ``I thought he was just lovesick, which I think he was,'' Egger,
62, said this week. ``He was terribly insistent on being let in.
`Rebecca Schaeffer' was every other word. `I gotta see her. I love
her. If I could just see her for a minute.'
   ``He seemed to be an intelligent kid, no raving lunatic, no
dumbbell, but something was definitely wrong, mentally,'' Egger
said. ``There was something haywire going on, but I didn't perceive
it as potentially violent.''
   Egger said Bardo initially made numerous phone calls to the
production office asking to speak to Miss Schaeffer.
   The incident provided another glimpse into what authorities call
Bardo's fatal obsession with the 21-year-old actress, who was shot
July 18 as she opened the door to her apartment building. Bardo was
arrested in Tucson the next day and charged in the slaying.
   Egger, a former Beverly Hills police captain, said he followed
standard procedure in informing Miss Schaeffer's production unit
about Bardo's attempt to see her in June 1987. But whether anyone
told Miss Schaeffer remained unclear Wednesday.
   ``So a fan tried to get on the lot. So what? Who's going to
think he's a potential murderer?'' asked Mimi Weber, vice president
of the production company for ``My Sister Sam.''
   ``It would have seemed harmless: another young kid who's
star-struck,'' she said. ``We have tons of those. Lots are lovable;
some are crazy. But who's to know?''
   People who were present remember hearing about a persistent fan
trying to gain access to the set but were unsure whether Miss
Schaeffer was told.
   The young actress already had received seemingly innocuous fan
letters from Bardo.
  
</TEXT>
