<SECOND>AM-Korea-Libya Crash,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bodies of Plane Crash Victims Brought Home From Libya</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Korean Air plane on Thursday flew
home the bodies of the 68 South Korean victims of last week's
airline crash in Libya.
   The coffins, flown from the Libyan capital of Tripoli, were
draped in South Korean flags and were taken to a government
hospital in Seoul.
   Officials said the bodies would not be returned to family
members until the completion of autopsys and identification.
   Airline officials said 73 of the 199 passengers and crew aboard
the Korean Air DC-10 that crashed July 27 were killed, including
one Japanese and four Libyan passengers. At least six people died
on the ground.
   Survivors returned to Seoul on Sunday.
   Passengers on the plane were mostly construction workers in
Libya and nearby countries.
   At Seoul's Kimpo airport, hundreds of friends and family members
of victims have refused to budge during negotiations with airline
officials on compensation.
   On Wednesday, about 20 angry relatives overturned desks and
shattered windows at an airport building after rejecting an
unspecified offer of compensation by the airline.
   Investigators were still trying to determine the cause of the
accident in which the plane crashed just short of fogbound Tripoli
airport.
