<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     08-02 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Killed in Battle near San Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas based on San
Salvador Volcano attacked an army post on the edge of the capital
Tuesday night and at least one soldier and a civilian were killed
in the fighting.
   Another soldier and two civilians were wounded in the battle
that lasted two hours and kept many of the residents of the city's
northwestern sector inside buildings or huddled behind walls or
vehicles. Gunsmoke settled over the San Ramon neighborhood where
the fighting was heaviest.
   It was the fifth time in eight months that the army post in San
Ramon has been attacked. An estimated 200 rebels are based on the
volcano and its foothills nearly reach San Salvador's city limits.
   Sgt. Ventura Lopez, who was in command of the detachment of 10
soldiers at the post, estimated the number of attackers at 60. He
said the guerrillas threw packets of TNT at the post. One explosion
ripped a hole in the roof of the single-story cinderblock building
that serves as post headquarters.
   Nearly 100 soldiers from the Belloso army brigade reinforced the
post's unit about 20 minutes after the fighting began at dusk.
Thousands of rounds from assault rifles and machine guns and
sporadic detonations of rocket-propelled grenades and TNT bombs
kept residents pinned down.
   ``All I want to do is get home,'' sobbed Leticia Ramirez, laying
face down in a trench next to a reporter while bullets whizzed
overhead.
   A helicopter circled at about 3,000 feet above the battle. Its
gunner fired bursts of tracer rounds from time to time, though the
action was beyond effective range of his M-60 machine gun.
   Leftist rebels of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front
have fought the U.S.-backed government for nearly 10 years.
   Attacks on military posts in and near the capital have increased
during the past 10 months after three years in which San Salvador
was almost free of combat.
   During the 10 months the rebels acquired hundreds of
Soviet-designed Dragunov sniper rifles and an estimated 2,000 AK-47
assault rifles to augment their arsenal.
   The Dragunovs have an effective range of about 2,650 feet and
have been used to damage several helicopters. The rifles have
forced air force pilots to fly higher nd abandon more missions than
at any time during the war.
</TEXT>
