<FIRST>r a AM-ChineseOpera 1stLd-Writethru a0751 08-02 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chinese Opera, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0751,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fate of Possible Chinese Defectors Unknown</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `The opera ...' to CORRECT date opera company
flew back to Thursday, sted Sunday. </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight Chinese performers have been missing
for a week since they left a group returning to China, but
immigration officials said Tuesday no one had contacted them on
behalf of the entertainers.
   ``All I can tell you is they haven't walked into this office and
applied for any relief,'' said David Ilchert, a spokesman for the
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   Four other Chinese citizens have chosen to defect in San
Francisco since the June 4 crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators
in Beijing.
   If the eight entertainers who fled the Kun Opera company last
week seek political asylum in the United States, it would be the
largest single defection of Chinese citizens since the 1950s.
   ``Everybody in China wants to leave, so whoever has a chance to
go out of China, they will try to stay there,'' said Jeffrey Shia,
president of the Kiangsu Chekiang Association, a non-profit
association that helps Chinese immigrants.
   The performers left the 28-member opera over a two-day period
last week while the company was in San Francisco en route to
Shanghai following a series of performances in the United States.
   ``We have had zero contact with them or with the consulate,''
said FBI spokesman Chuck Latting. ``We would like to talk to them.
We always want any defector to know that we are a wonderful
umbrella for them. We can help them get to us or any other agency.''
   The opera company flew back to Shanghai on Thursday, according
to Officer Larry Higgins, coordinator of VIP travel at San
Francisco International Airport.
   A spokesman for the Chinese consulate confirmed the eight
performers did not leave with the company.
   ``They were influenced by people with ulterior motives,'' said
spokesman Wang Shaohua.
   Officals of the Chinese consulate in San Francisco have blamed
the disappearance on ``people with motives to bring damage to
China.''
   The missing entertainers include Hua Wen-Yi, a famous opera
singer in Shanghai. Two other singers in the group, Chen Tong-Shen
and Zhan Ping-Ping, also are well known in Shanghai. Zhan is a
famous television and film star as well as an opera performer. The
others were identified as Qui Huan, Chen Chi-Ping, Ma Xin-Bao,
Peter Chong and Lou Sei-Long.
   ``I think at this moment they fear making a wrong move _ whether
they should seek political asylum or use other reasons to remain
here,'' said Shia.
   ``I think they are going to wait until this incident is cooled
off and then decide what options they should take,'' he said.
   Although accounts of the disappearances differ, Shia, who spoke
with several opera members last Wednesday, gave this description:
Two members left during a farewell dinner on July 25, two others
left that evening, three group leaders early the next day,
Wednesday, and one performer left Wednesday morning.
   Jon Wu, an attorney who specializes in immigration and who has
represented defectors, said the performers have numerous legal
options.
   Because they arrived in San Francisco June 5, they are eligible
for the emergency ``deferred departure status'' announced by the
Bush administration in June. The policy offers a one-year blanket
visa extension to all Chinese citizens who were in the country on
or before June 5.
   Alternatively, political asylum is ``tough for people to get who
haven't really expressed any opinions'' against the Chinese
government, Wu said.
   Shia said if the performers were involved in the pro-democracy
movement in China, they would not have been allowed to leave.
   Other options to remain in the United States include permanent
labor certification, temporary work authorization or permanent
residency if a relative successfully petitions on behalf of a
Chinese citizen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
