<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1210EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-SovietTourists Adv11   08-02 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Tourists, Adv 11,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs Aug. 11 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Tourists in Israel Trade Caviar for Computers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet tourists, starved for consumer
goods back home, are trading caviar for computers and using
borrowed rubles to buy video cassette recorders.
   ``This video will pay for the trip,'' said Natalya, a Moscow
housewife in her 40s, clutching a VCR at Ben-Gurion International
Airport.
   ``Everybody is buying videos. I wanted to bring another one for
my son, but I did not have the money.''
   As a result of a thaw in Soviet relations with Israel, thousands
of Soviet Jews have been visiting relatives and friends in Israel.
   En route many stop in Larnaca, Cyprus, to purchase electronic
goods that can be resold in the Soviet Union where a VCR can fetch
the equivalent of 10 months' salary _ about 2,000 rubles, $3,140 at
the official rate of exchange.
   Natalya and other travelers demanded anonymity because they
feared reprisals for engaging in black market transactions.
   One recent flight from Cyprus carried 60 Soviet tourists with 26
VCRs and two double-deck radio-cassette players. One Georgian
family was seen pushing a cart with three VCRs.
   The tourists are required to leave the VCRs and other goods at
the airport to be picked up when they leave Israel.
   Some Soviet visitors, who include musicians and artists of
Soviet touring groups, bring luxury items like caviar that are
scarce in Israel to trade for personal computers and other
electronic equipment.
   ``My refrigerator was packed with caviar tins,'' said Shmuel
Weismel, an Israeli computer programmer in Jerusalem who recently
hosted a Soviet theater troupe.
   He said the Soviets brought French perfume and caviar purchased
on the black market back home and sold them here for several times
the price.
   They then bought personal computers, which cost $2,000 to $4,000
in Israel. An additional $7,850 must be paid in customs taxes when
they arrive back home. But once in the Soviet Union, a computer can
be sold to a factory or a state-owned business for the equivalent
of $78,500 to $110,000.
   Other Soviet visitors select one of a half-dozen Israeli firms
offering a different way to buy electronics.
   ``We offer a transit deal,'' said Boris Sterenhal of Tal-Hen &amp;
Khanan Electronics in the Israeli coastal town of Netanya. ``Soviet
tourists order tax-free products, which are delivered by our
European branch directly to the Soviet Union.''
   The firm, which advertizes in some of the seven Russian-language
newspapers published in Israel, offers Soviet Jews radios, tape
cassette players, VCRs, televisiion sets and personal computers.
   Attendants said not a day passes without a Soviet coming into
the store ``to buy something, at least a radio.''
   But the Soviet tourists also buy other things in short supply at
home.
   Sonia, a retired biochemist from Moscow, bought a $7.50 baroque
freshwater-pearl necklace as a present for her daughter.
   ``In Moscow, its costs 200 rubles ($314),'' or about an average
month's salary, she said.
   While the Soviet Union does not allow the use of hard currency
to import luxury items, it tolerates private imports.
   ``There is a tremendous demand for all kinds of goods that the
government can't supply,'' said Galia Golan, a Soviet specialist at
Hebrew University in Jerusalem. ``So they have always permitted the
black market and the second economy to continue.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Aug. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
