<FIRST>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv03   08-02 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 03,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday August 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rate Declines Challenge Money-Fund Investors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve's easing of its credit
policy and the accompanying drop in interest rates have posed a
$325 billion question for investors in money market mutual funds.
   Should they sit tight with their money in the face of declining
yields, or look elsewhere for better returns?
   If the past record is any guide, the vast majority of money fund
assets will stay put.
   From 1975, when the earliest money funds had attracted less than
$4 billion, to this year, when their assets have swollen by more
than $50 billion from $272 billion at the end of 1988, the
long-term industry trend has shown almost uninterrupted growth.
   Periods of low or falling interest rates halted the funds'
expansion only briefly.
   In 1983, for example, when interest rates were falling and
stocks were soaring in the early stages of a spectacular bull
market, money fund assets shrank by about 20 percent. A year later,
they rebounded once again to new highs.
   Today's savers and investors have a wider range of competitive
alternatives to choose among than ever before.
   And thanks to rallies in the stock and bond markets, funds that
invest in those long-term securities have been producing
substantially higher returns than money funds have offered.
   Late last month, Donoghue's Moneyletter, a newsletter that
tracks developments affecting fund investors, issued a ``buy''
signal recommending a move from money funds to growth stock funds
for venturesome investors.
   But with all that, many investors _ especially those who view
their money fund holdings as a kind of modern-day savings account _
may find few other choices that appeal more to them on the basis of
both risk and potential reward.
   The risks of stock market investing, of course, are well
advertised. At a recent yield of 8.85 percent, analysts point out,
money funds still offer rewards close to the historical average
annual return of 9 percent to 10 percent posted by the stock market.
   What about the other alternatives? Tax-free money funds,
investing in state and local government securities whose interest
is not subject to federal taxation, recently were yielding about
5.6 percent to 5.7 percent.
   That put them at an unattractive level, by Donoghue's reckoning,
even for an investor in the 33 percent bracket.
   Bank money-market deposit accounts have the allure of federal
deposit insurance, but their typical yields of about 6.5 percent
languish far below their money fund competitors.
   People wanting to lock in yields as protection against further
declines in interest rates traditionally turn to long-term bond
investments. These days, however, they aren't very well compensated
for making that commitment.
   In late July the yield available on the longest-term Treasury
bonds slipped below 8 percent.
   Double-digit yields can still be found in abundance in so-called
``junk bonds'' and the mutual funds that specialize in these
lower-rated securities. But some advisers say this is an especially
dangerous time to be increasing credit risk.
   ``Much of the newly issued `junk' securities have not been
tested in a period of prolonged adversity,'' says the Boston-based
United &amp; Babson Investment Report. ``A sacrifice in yield is well
worth the price of safety, and a good night's sleep.''
   Indeed, while investors are casting a wary eye on the other
options, analysts say they may want to give their money funds a
fresh appraisal as well.
   Sponsors of two funds, the Value Line Cash Fund and the Liquid
Green Trust, reached into their own pockets in June to cover losses
that resulted from a default on short-term securities issued by
Integrated Resources Inc.
   As a result of their response, fund shareholders lost no money.
But the experience was ``a humbling lesson,'' as Donoghue's
described it, for an industry that prides itself on its safety
record.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday August 3.</NOTE>
