<FIRST>a i AM-Colombia-Flowers Adv11   08-02 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Flowers, Adv 11,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Aug. 11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Colombians Pushing Their Flowers To Counter Drug Image</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAROLD OLMOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This land of drug cartels and violence
is also the land of beautiful flowers, and those who grow them are
about to launch an advertising campaign to get Americans and
Canadians to buy more of them.
   ``We counter the violence of drugs with the beauty of our
flowers as a real image representing Colombia more than anything
else,'' said Jorge Enrique Uribe, president of the Colombian
Flowers Exporters Association.
   Years of sustained efforts to produce popular flower types _
particularly carnations and chrysanthemums, in addition to the
exotic specimens native to Colombia _ have earned Colombia a
respectable second place after the Netherlands among
flower-exporting nations.
   Flowers represented $205 million last year in export revenues,
more than double the amount of 1980. Next year could be another
all-time record for Colombian growers and dealers if their goal of
$260 million in exports is met.
   Colombia's 8 percent to 10 percent share of the international
market over recent years, surpassing Israel and Italy, reflects the
drive of its flourishing non-traditional export industry.
   All this despite all sorts of difficulties, including
embarassing actions by drug traffickers who often smuggle cocaine
with shipments of flowers. Last year a cargo plane of Avianca, the
Colombian national airline, was seized in Miami after the police
found cocaine concealed in the soil of a flower shipment.
   Fined $3 million, Avianca halted its overseas cargo operations
and Colombian florists had to look for other airlines to ship their
flowers _ at much higher rates.
   Flower shipments now are subject to stricter controls at the
Bogota airport in an effort to detect hidden drugs.
   Flowers, Uribe said, are ``innocent victims of drug
traffickers.''
   Flower cultivators, like any other businessmen, are constantly
adapting to the mood of customers.
   ``Flowers are like clothes: colors and taste for them change,''
Uribe said. ``And we have to follow the customers' whims.''
   Flowers began as a tiny portion of Colombian exports in the
mid-1960s, when they accounted for less than $100,000 annually.
   Colombian florists feel confident that their business will be
rosier if the $8 million advertising campaign to persuade Americans
and Canadians to buy more flowers is successful.
   Studies by Colombia florists associations indicate Americans and
Canadians buy flowers mostly to give to others and rarely for
themselves.
   ``Europeans take flowers to their homes as much as they send
them as gifts,'' Uribe said. ``Our studies demonstrate that West
Germans, famous for their lavish preference for flowers, buy as
much as eight times more flowers than Canadians and Americans.''
   Colombian floriculturists joined the 28,000-member U.S. Florists
Transworld Delivery Association to launch the advertising campaign,
which begins in September.
   ``The future lies in convincing Americans and Canadians to
change habits and persuade them to buy flowers for themselves,
too,'' Uribe said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Aug. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1403EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-God'sLove Adv07   08-02 1156</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-God's Love, Adv 07,1187</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Aug. 7, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>God's Love We Deliver Nourishes Spirit and Body</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY MacVEAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On this Wednesday one of the people they'd
nourished day after day, hopefully and compassionately, died. It
was all too usual.
   Word of the death was passed around the office and at a
storefront church in Harlem, the man's neighborhood. But God's Love
We Deliver Inc. kept up its work _ feeding people who are confined
to their homes by AIDS.
   ``We deal with it all the time,'' said program director Joan
Block. ``It may be harder in some ways, but it is also much richer.
The issue of life and death is the great magnifying glass.
   ``I don't get it when people ask how we can do this. It's not as
if if you worked in a bank you never had to handle the death issue.
This is a really great training program for what is inevitable for
all of us.''
   ``I don't think any of us is qualified to find a cure for
AIDS,'' said Carl Johnes, one of 450 volunteers who make sure
nearly 200 homebound AIDS patients get gourmet, high-calorie food
five days a week. ``But we are qualified to keep people alive until
such time as a cure is found, so it's a life-saving job.''
   There is eloquence in the preparation and delivery of
nourishment that provides a bounty beyond calories.
   On Valentine's Day, the delivery to Gary Gruber, a Manhattan
landscaper, included heart-shaped cookies and roses. ``I opened it
up, expecting a meal and it was a party. I started crying from
happiness.''
   There were flowers and cake on his 39th birthday. ``I didn't
know they knew,'' he said. ``But they said it was all in the
computer.''
   Early one morning, eight people chat in the small, well-equipped
kitchen in the basement at West Park Presbyterian Church in
Manhattan. They fill plastic containers of cream of mushroom soup
and containers of pasta, hamburger, and carrots and peas. There
also are a salad and homemade cookies this day.
   Soup and vegetables cook in stock pots on two stoves. The air is
stifling, and two fans do far less than volunteers' attitudes to
ease the discomfort.
   A visitor pitches in as she looks over the program with an eye
to starting something similar in Los Angeles. Later in the day, the
power goes out, and hurried plans are made to protect the food. The
clients still need meals.
   In the kitchen, there is gentle banter, about a book someone
will write, or their own efficiency. No one complains and no hands
are allowed to remain idle. Newcomers are warmly welcomed, often
with a hug, but then an apron is given over and a chore assigned.
These are people with a mission.
   ``We all do it because it makes us feel good. It isn't about
being a saint,'' said Johnes, a writer from Manhattan.
   God's Love produces made-from-scratch meals from a rotating
30-day menu that includes carrot bisque, artichoke salad, smoked
turkey, shish kebab, four-cheese lasagna, veal stroganoff, pears in
puff pastry and fruit Bavarian.
   ``We have a big food budget and we buy top quality. But we're
pretty frugal,'' said chef Luli Gray, who saves the drippings from
one day's beef for another day's soup or sauce. Leftovers are
packed, marked and frozen for use.
   A walk-in refrigerator was donated by the Gay Men's Chorus.
God's Love needs a bigger kitchen; it always needs money and
volunteers. As AIDS spreads from homosexual men to intravenous drug
users, their lovers and their children, the work will only increase.
   The goal is that no homebound person with acquired immune
deficiency syndrome ever goes hungry. ``We are dedicated to not
putting anybody on a waiting list,'' said Gary Bressler, the
organization's executive chef.
   Clients had lost an average of 18 pounds from the onset of AIDS
to the time they began receiving meals, but gained an average of 10
pounds after meals were delivered, Bressler said.
   One symptom of AIDS is loss of appetite, so he works to make
sure the food is ``not only nutritious and fattening but appetizing.
   ``We try to keep their weight up, and that's adding to their
strength ... and that's what we're here for.''
   Cooking begins daily at 7:30 a.m., and meals go into four vans
by 10 a.m., when work starts on tomorrow's meals. By 2:30 p.m.,
everyone has been fed. The kitchen closes at 9.
   ``When the kitchen opened in August 1987, we were serving six
meals. Now, we're serving 160 to 180,'' said Bressler.
   Meals go to all five New York City boroughs and Jersey City,
N.J. Some are delivered directly to homes; others are left at
churches, homes, a Red Cross office or bars, where neighborhood
volunteers take them to people with AIDS. Twenty-five or 30 meals a
day are made to suit special medical needs.
   Johnes came to God's Love as a volunteer after donating money
for a year and deciding that wasn't enough. ``I came the Friday
night before Christmas and made orange zest, crushed garlic and
peeled 25 pounds of cucumbers. I went to bed smelling like a
salad.'' On Christmas Day, he delivered meals.
   ``Nourishment is important,'' he said. ``It's not controversial.
How can you argue with people who feed other people?''
   God's Love We Deliver was conceived in 1985 when Ganga Stone,
now executive director, took groceries to a man suffering from AIDS
and was horrified to find him too weak to get up and cook the food.
She decided to do something.
   First, she cooked at home and delivered meals on her bicycle.
Then meals were solicited from restaurants. Finally, in August
1987, God's Love moved to West Park Presbyterian. From a woman on
her bike, God's Love grew to a staff of 22 and a budget for 1989 of
more than $1 million. It is financed by the New York State
Nutrition Assistance Program and other donations and grants.
   Originally, clients were mostly white, homosexual men. Now,
maybe half are intravenous drug users and their children. Many are
women.
   When Gruber was released from a hospital 1{ years ago, he called
God's Love at a friend's suggestion and talked with Stone. ``She
said how about a meal today or tomorrow, then we'll do the
paperwork.''
   When he called God's Love, ``I wasn't eating very much. I'd go
into the kitchen, open the refrigerator and think, `Oh, that's all
I can deal with,' and close it. It was too exhausting to do more.''
   When he did summon the energy to cook, Gruber said, he'd make a
big pot of spaghetti and eat the same food four days straight.
``God's Love saved my life, because I didn't want to eat. It's
really the high point of my day.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Aug. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
