<DOCNO> AP890802-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1358EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRdp Adv04   08-02 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 04,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Aug. 4, and thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Black Catholic Clergy Caucus has
called for study of developing an African-American rite within the
Roman Catholic Church.
   Such a rite has been urged by a suspended Washington, D.C.,
priest, the Rev. George A. Stallings Jr.
   Brother Roy Smith, caucus president, said Stallings brought the
issue of racism within the church to the forefront and ``heightened
the discussion of the intensity of those issues.''
   Stallings several weeks ago founded the Imani Temple, a church
that combines elements of Roman Catholicism with African and
Southern black traditions. He was suspended by Cardinal James
Hickey of Washington.
   The Rev. Victor Cohea, a caucus board member, said the issue of
an African-American Catholic rite is almost a century old, but this
is the first time in the 20th century that a group of black
Catholics has proposed study of such a rite.
   The caucus met in Milwaukee recently with the National Black
Catholic Seminarians and the National Black Sisters' Conference.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of Concordia Theological
Seminary voted to retire the seminary's president, the Rev. Robert
Preus, charging ``turmoil'' in the institution made him ineffective.
   Preus called that a ``complete fabrication.''
   Head of the Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod institution for 15
years, Preus said he had not wanted to retire and contended the
board's action would have a ``damaging effect on seminary income, a
demoralizing effect on the student body'' and a polarizing effect
the faculty.
   He said charges by the board that ``turmoil within the faculty''
made it impossible for him to serve effectively were false.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern Baptist gifts to the
denomination's worldwide hunger ministries dropped in the first six
months of 1989 to the lowest point i five years. The total of $3.1
million was about $1 million less than for the same period last
year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only a tiny fraction of young women counseled
at pro-life centers give their babies up for adoption and that's
``a scandal,'' says Michael J. McManus, who writes the syndicated
``Ethics and Religion'' column.
   He says 300,000 babies are born annually to unmarried teen-agers
with scant prospects as mothers, but only 1 percent of those
counseled by Birthright centers and 4 percent of those counseled by
the Christian Action Council centers offer the newborns for
adoption and a more secure future.
   ``It is as if the pro-life forces are only `pro-life' up until
the birth of the baby _ with little pro-life concern after birth,''
he writes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1989 American Jewish Year Book estimates the
Jewish population of the United States in 1988 at 5.935 million,
down slightly from 5.944 the year before.
   Both figures represent 2.5 percent of the overall U.S.
population.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WHEATON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet Baptist says atheism is in a state
of confusion in his homeland and it no longer will be a required
course in universities.
   Instead, an elective introduction to religion class will include
lessons both on atheism and Christianity, says the Rev.Yakov K.
Dukhochenko of the All-Union Council of Evangelical
Christians-Baptists of the Ukraine.
   ``This is God's timing for our country,'' he said at the Slavic
Gospel Association's international conference.
</TEXT>
