<FIRST>a w AM-MarketingtheMail Adv07   08-02 1131</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marketing the Mail, Adv 07,1166</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Aug. 7, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Postal Service Edges Into World of Marketing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Move over Topps _ you have new competition.
But the baseball cards being marketed by the U.S. Postal Service to
promote stamp sales won't have the trademark piece of bubble gum
inside.
   The post office is easing into the card business with just four
of the popular collectibles as part of a push to shift from the
image of a neighborhood store into a modern marketing machine.
   Probably the most visible effort in this change will come in
September, in a joint campaign promoting postage stamps featuring
dinosaurs in conjunction with MCA Inc.'s home video release of the
movie ``The Land Before Time.''
   But this isn't the first tie-in between stamps and other
businesses, and it won't be the last, said Gordon C. Morison,
assistant postmaster general for philatelic and retail services.
   The baseball cards, for example, take advantage of previously
issued stamps honoring popular ballplayers. The stamps featuring
Lou Gherig, Jackie Robinson, Babe Ruth and Roberto Clemente have
been combined in a new albumn, with four matching baseball cards
included.
   Last year a set of stamps featuring carousel animals got special
promotions at several amusement parks around the country, Morison
said. And the agency is interested in future arrangements, perhaps
for planned stamps featuring lighthouses and marine mammals.
   And new stamps often receive special promotions when issued,
often organized by local post offices.
   For example the Key West, Fla., office prepared a special 12- by
16-inch print of the recent Hemingway stamp in the Literary Arts
series.
   Mounted on a backing with a copy of the stamp canceled on July
17, its first day of issue, the print is being offered for $25, by
mail order, to collectors and Hemingway fans.
   But the arrangement with Steven Spielberg's film about dinosaurs
is the most ambitious effort so far in the effort to boost sales of
stamps to collectors.
   Buyers of the home video will receive a little brochure
advertising the dinosaur stamps, offering for sale a T-shirt
featuring one of the stamps, and also promoting holiday seals sold
by the movie company and a special deal from Pizza Hut.
   The dinosaur stamps should appeal to youngsters, the T-shirts
and posters to both youngsters and slightly older people, Morison
said.
   With the movie going on sale in September, the promotion arrives
just in time for Stamp Collecting Month, which the post office
celebrates in October.
   The purpose of the effort is simple: getting people interested
in collecting stamps, a hobby that means big bucks for an agency
struggling to cover its ever increasing costs while avoiding
raising postage rates.
   Those little piles of stamps ``collected'' in envelopes and desk
drawers across the nation may seem like a small investment to their
owners.
   But to the U.S. Postal Service, collectors represent $150
million to $170 million in sales annually, Morison said.
   And the best part is, it's virtually all profit.
   A postage stamp is, after all, nothing more than a receipt for
advance payment for a service _ the delivery of a letter or parcel.
   When people collect new stamps and save them, the post office
gets its quarter but doesn't have to perform any service for the
money.
   That's the kind of business most companies would love to have,
and one the post office is happy to encourage.
   It should please non-collectors, too, since the profits from
stamps sold to collectors _ philatelists is the formal term _ helps
subsidize the postal service and thus lowers the costs to people
who use stamps to get letters delivered somewhere.
   Since stamps were first issued in the mid-1800s, the postal
service has enjoyed the fact that people collect stamps,
occasionally seeing a boost when some collector became famous, such
as President Franklin D. Roosevelt.
   But only in recent years has it studied them and sought to
increase the market.
   Who collects stamps?
   Well, 75 percent of youngsters have a collection of some type,
said Mary Margaret Grant, manager of philatelic services at the
postal service.
   As youngsters enter their teens they find other interests, Ms.
Grant said, and the stamp collection usually gets put aside until
later in life when they marry, have families, and often get
interested in stamps again.
   It was the nostalgic folks returning to collecting that made
last year's carousel stamps big sellers, Morison said.
   This returning group is about half ``casual'' collectors, who
buy stamps they like from time to time, but don't make a big deal
out of it. One-fourth are ``accumulators'' who have some stamps,
often ripping used ones off envelopes. And the rest are serious
collectors, buying whole sheets of stamps, subscribing to stamp
publications and following the hobby closely.
   The serious collectors lobby the agency for stamps, but Ms.
Grant said officials seek to please all types of collectors.
   One thing they have in common is that everybody likes pretty
stamps, Morison said, although serious collectors lean toward more
formal engravings while casual collectors seem to prefer more
colorful productions.
   Much of the recent marketing efforts is aimed at converting
casual collectors to serious ones _ explaining how to mount stamps
in albums, organize them by theme and so forth.
   To do this Morison has instituted a quarterly series of ``stamp
packs'' including a brochure and all of the colorful commemorative
stamps issued over three months.
   Previously, sets of stamps were issued just once a year, but the
stamp packs four times annually help spread out the interest,
Morison said.
   In addition, the agency has subscription services for stamp
collectors to make sure they get all the new stamps that come out.
   There are 38,000 Benjamin Franklin Stamp Clubs for youngsters
around the country, encouraged by the postal service as a means of
getting youngsters interested in stamp collecting.
   Meanwhile, Morison has branched out postal marketing in other
areas, too, promoting the sale of stamps in shopping malls and
supermarkets, for example. Those sales have grown to $500 million,
and ``the public just loves it,'' he said.
   People find it more convenient to buy stamps in supermarkets, he
explained, and this also shortens the lines at post offices,
improving service for people who need help from clerks.
   Shopping mall operations are being planned where people can
``shop and ship,'' Morison added.
   Similar to the postal substations run by many small town stores,
these operations would allow shoppers to buy something at a store,
have it wrapped, and then take it to a counter in the mall for
mailing to a friend or relative without having to make a special
trip to a post office.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Aug. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
