<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-Kodak     08-02 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Kodak,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Blames Restructuring for Second Quarter, Half-Year Earnings
Loss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. says its second-quarter
profits fell 85 percent, mainly the result of a $225 million
restructuring charge that was announced last week.
   Without the special charges, profits still would have dropped 26
percent in the second quarter. The company blames higher costs,
including interest expenses and the impact of the strong dollar.
   Chairman Colby Chandler vowed last week and again Tuesday that
strong steps would be taken to deal with the slump in operating
profits.
   Nevertheless, the stock fell Tuesday. It was off 62{ cents at
$47.50 in late trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Net earnings were $60 million, or 18 cents a share, down from a
record $390 million, or $1.20 a share, a year earlier. Sales rose
to a record $4.5 billion from $4.13 billion for the second quarter
last year.
   For the first half, profit fell 60 percent to $260 million, or
80 cents a share, from $650 million, or $2 a share, a year earlier.
Sales rose to a record $8.4 billion from $7.46 billion in last
year's first half.
   The one-time charges cover changes that ``have happened, are
happening and will be happening,'' said company spokesman Paul
Allen. He said the changes could involve layoffs, sale of
businesses and discontinuation of products.
   But the company has not released details about its specific
plans.
   ``That's what we're waiting for. There's been nothing concrete
so far,'' said Eugene Glazer, stock analyst for Dean Witter
Reynolds in New York.
   He said the company has already made it clear that the current
restructuring is not going to be major by Wall Street proportions.
   ``It's going to be significant, but not gigantic,'' Glazer said.
``But that leaves the question of whether the company is going to
tighten its belt by one notch, two notches or three.''
   ``While volume gains so far this year have been gratifying,
especially in the United States, our earnings have not kept pace,''
Chandler said.
   Some cost-cutting steps may be taken in the company's
Information Systems business segment, which includes copiers, and
microfilm and graphics equipment.
   For the second quarter that segment posted a $144 million loss,
as compared to a $92 million second-quarter profit last year. Even
without restructuring charges, the segment would only have posted a
profit of $6 million.
   ``There seems to be tremendous pressure there for something to
happen,'' said Glazer.
</TEXT>
