<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0240EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AT&amp;T-Card     08-02 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AT&amp;T-Card,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T To Sell Smart Card in Europe Through Olivetti</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AT&amp;T says its ``smart card'' will be used to
allow European motorists to pay tolls without stopping at toll
booths under a marketing agreement with Italy's Ing. C. Olivetti &amp;
Co. SpA.
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. said Tuesday its contract
marked the first time smart card technology developed in the United
States will be marketed in Europe.
   Smart cards, which are popular in Europe and Japan, are the size
of credit cards but contain tiny computer chips. They can be used
as charge cards, dog tags or electronic keys, among other things.
   Drivers approaching a highway toll plaza will slow to about 40
mph and insert their smart cards into transmitters mounted in the
cars, AT&amp;T said. Information stored on the cards will be sent to
the toll station and the cost of each toll will be subtracted from
an account programmed into the card.
   AT&amp;T said it has had discussions with highway and municipal
authorities about selling systems in the United States but has
nothing to announce yet.
   Other companies, including Dallas-based Amtech Corp., offer
devices that allow cars to pay tolls without stopping. But AT&amp;T
said it has the only card whose software allows it to be used for
multiple purposes. For example, the same card could also store car
maintenance records.
   Amtech's system, which uses a plastic TollTag, is in operation
on the North Dallas Tollway. The company is also trying to sell a
system in Oslo, Norway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
