<FIRST>r f PM-MCIRates     08-02 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-MCI Rates,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>MCI Cutting Long-Distance Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCI Communications Corp. says it will cut
long-distance rates by about $12 million annually to keep pace with
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.'s lower rates under new federal
pricing regulations.
   MCI said Tuesday it was lowering its interstate long-distance
rates by an average of 1.5 percent, effective immediately.
   The Federal Communications Commission in April imposed a new
``price cap'' regulatory scheme on AT&amp;T that put limits on what
AT&amp;T can charge for its long-distance services instead of limiting
how much it can earn above its costs.
   The plan went into effect July 1, and AT&amp;T said its customers
would save $140 million immediately.
   MCI, the nation's No. 2 long-distance provider behind AT&amp;T, said
its own rate reductions ``will ensure that MCI remains competitive
in the wake of the newly implemented price cap regulations.''
   MCI's residential rates will go down by an average of 1.9
percent, business-commercial rates by an average of 0.4 percent and
MCI card usage fees by 1 percent, the company said.
   The No. 3 long-distance company, US Sprint, cut its evening
long-distance rates 25.6 percent effective Tuesday for its new
Sprint Plus calling plan.
</TEXT>
