<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0243EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-DebtLimit     08-02 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Debt Limit,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Votes to Increase National Debt Ceiling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has voted to increase the national
debt limit temporarily by $70 billion so the Treasury won't go into
default while Congress is on its summer recess.
   The bill, approved 231-185 Tuesday and sent to the Senate, adds
to the debt ceiling of $2.8 trillion only through Oct. 31. By then,
Congress hopes to complete work on bill boosting the Treasury's
permanent borrowing authority to more than $3.1 trillion.
   The Treasury is already bumping up against the $2.8 trillion
limit and would be unable to meet its obligations by mid-August
without additional power to issue debt. A U.S. government default
would be unprecedented.
   The House passed the short-term debt extension after blocking,
228-193, an attempt by Rep. William Dannemeyer, R-Calif., to make
the increase contingent upon House consideration of an amendment to
the Constitution requiring a balanced budget.
   The House actually approved the permanent debt increase when it
passed the fiscal 1990 budget last spring, but the legislation has
been held up in the Senate.
   Several senators plan to use the must-pass legislation to carry
amendments addressing pet priorities, and it could also become the
vehicle for a new deficit-reduction effort by congressional leaders
and the White House.
   The national debt has tripled since the beginning of the decade
due to the huge budget deficits of the Reagan administration. The
Treasury has been forced to borrow more and more money to finance
government spending that exceeds tax receipts.
   The annual deficits have gone down from their peak of over $200
billion a year, but nearly $150 billion in red ink will be added to
the pool this fiscal year.
   The Gramm-Rudman budget law, itself passed as part of a 1985
debt bill that first put the limit above $2 trillion, mandates that
Congress and the president reduce the deficit in fiscal 1990 to
$100 billion.
   Fiscal 1990 begins Oct. 1. Congress commences its four-week
summer recess this Saturday.
   The short-term debt limit bill approved by the House on Tuesday
also included a provision, requested by the Treasury, to change the
way the government accounts for its zero-coupon bonds when
calculating the debt. The change will lessen the immediate impact
the bonds have on the debt.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
