<DOCNO> AP890802-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0246EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ToyotaChanges     08-02 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Toyota Changes,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toyota to Modernize Way of Making Decisions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Corp., the conservative giant of
Japanese industry, says it plans to drop special courtesy titles
for employees and cut in half the number of approvals required for
most decisions.
   The steps are part of a broad plan to make Toyota more flexible
and ``provide every employee the opportunity to work creatively and
to the fullest of his or her ability,'' the company announced
Tuesday.
   Toyota also said it will spend $730 million on bettering
employees' work lives, through new recreational facilities, dining
rooms and company housing for both married and single employees.
   Aspects of Toyota's plan such as more company housing are
strictly Japanese, but the emphasis on employee creativity is
Western.
   While American companies are trying to be more Japanese in
management, the Japanese are trying in some respects to become more
American.
   ``This is in order to have quick decisions and get more ideas,
more energetic work from the staff,'' said Akikazu Kida, a Toyota
spokesman in New York. The changes were also announced in Tokyo.
   To promote workplace democracy, old titles such as kacho
(manager) will be discarded and all employees will be referred to
simply as san, the Japanese equivalent of Mr., Mrs. or Ms.
   Personnel evaluations that have been dominated by seniority will
now take performance more into account, Toyota said. About 1,000
supervisors will be reassigned to creative, hands-on work.
   Toyota is the largest industrial company in Japan and has a
reputation for a slow, conservative management style, in contrast
to more Western-style companies such as Honda Motor Co. Ltd.
   Japanese companies have long succeeded by adapting American
technology and perfecting manufacturing techniques, but corporate
leaders have decided that success in the future will demand
innovation. And innovation requires giving employees freer rein.
American consultants have traveled to Japan to lecture the
industrial giants on such themes as how one person can make a
difference.
   ``Employees will be encouraged to realize their own potential
and pursue their own professional interests,'' Toyota said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0251EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Princeton-Newport-RICO Bjt   08-02 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Princeton-Newport-RICO, Bjt,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convictions Could Strengthen Use of Racketeering Statute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<UNK>AP Business Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The conviction of six Wall Street professionals
on racketeering charges has intensified debate over whether the
laws passed in 1970 to fight organized crime should be used to
prosecute white-collar crime.
   Legal experts said Tuesday the guilty verdict on 63 of 64 counts
in the Princeton-Newport tax fraud trial strengthens the
government's decision to use the controversial Racketeer Influenced
and Corrupt Organizations law.
   ``I think the verdict shows the statute can be used successfully
in this area,'' said Gerard Lynch, a criminal law professor at
Columbia University. ``I would have expected it would be used more
anyway and this verdict encourages it.''
   The U.S. District Court trial of five executives of the defunct
investment firm Princeton-Newport Partners LP and a former Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. trader was the first time the statute was used
in a securities case.
   Opponents of the law say applies far too stiff penalties for
white-collar criminals _ including a 20-year jail term per count.
They also say its provision for pretrial asset seizures can force
companies out of business before a trial.
   ``I think RICO as originally promulgated by Congress was
excellent. I think it has become grossly overused and abused,''
said securities lawyer Aubrey B. Harwell Jr., who represented a
former Drexel trader in another case stemming from the government's
three-year crackdown on Wall Street crime.
   Former Manhattan U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani, now running for
New York City mayor, pioneered the new use of RICO _ and, critics
say, threats to use it.
   Giuliani was accused of trying to pressure the Princeton-Newport
defendants to testify against others by charging them with
racketeering. Princeton-Newport has said the charges last August
forced its liquidation shortly thereafter.
   Drexel Chief Executive Frederick H. Joseph has said his firm
agreed in a separate case to pay $650 million and plead guilty to
six securities felonies rather than face a possible RICO indictment.
   Michael Milken, the former head of Drexel's junk bond
operations, was indicted on 98 counts of racketeering and fraud
earlier this year for transactions that included one also cited in
the Princeton-Newport complaint after refusing to enter a plea
agreement.
   A person familiar with his legal preparations said Tuesday the
Princeton-Newport verdict would not affect Milken's plans to fight
the charges.
   But legal experts said Monday's guilty verdict would give
prosecutors a psychological boost as they ready for Milken's
scheduled March 1990 trial. It also could spur more RICO securities
cases.
   ``It certainly would indicate the Department of Justice the
viability of RICO at least before a jury and in a case where tax
seemed to be the overriding concern,'' said Columbia securities law
professor Harvey Goldschmid.
   Justice Department guidelines on RICO state the law should not
be used as a substitute for tax fraud prosecutions. But the
guidelines are flexible, and in the Princeton-Newport case tax
claims were brought instead as mail fraud charges.
   New York attorney Martin Klein, a close friend of Milken's,
argues that the statute should not be used simply to fit the needs
of prosecutors.
   ``It's not a substitute for the securities laws or the tax laws
and it's not to be used as a catchall for every other federal
statute,'' he said.
   Nevertheless, proponents of the law say its broad nature and the
changing nature of crime, in which such frauds as insider trading
have become more common, have made RICO a logical tool to fight any
pattern of criminal activity.
   ``If the RICO statute can be used for three bookmakers standing
on the corner it certainly ought to be used for individuals sitting
in corporate boardrooms stealing massive amounts of money from the
public,'' said Ronald Goldstock, director of the New York State
Organized Crime Task Force.
   Congress is considering two bills that would revamp RICO's use
in civil cases, eliminating its award of triple damages. Supreme
Court Chief Justice William Rehnquist in May called for imposing
limitations on civil use of RICO.
   Others said RICO's severe potential penalties were inappropriate
for cases such as Princeton-Newport. The jury, lawyers said, may
have convicted the defendants of arranging illegal tax schemes with
or without the RICO charge.
   ``My own view is that it's got to be an extremely aggravated
white-collar case to use the RICO statute,'' said criminal defense
lawyer Robert Morvillo. ``I don't think it was originally designed
for this use. I think it's very heavy-handed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0305EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Route128Slowdown Bjt   08-02 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Route 128 Slowdown, Bjt,0814</SECOND>
<HEAD>Route 128's Woes: A Matter of Style As Well As Substance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every morning, traffic moves at a crawl along
Route 128, the high technology highway ringing Boston. Some
insiders say the pace of business inside the sleek corporate
headquarters along 128 isn't any faster.
   ``Tactical decisions that take six weeks in Boston can take
anywhere from six days to six nanoseconds in California,'' said
Sterling Hager, founder of a public relations firm that represents
computer firms on both coasts.
   After a year of falling profits and employment, many companies
along Route 128 are going through a period of painful retrenchment
and self-examination, and a common conclusion is that they need to
become more agile, less hierarchical and more willing to take risks.
   In the last week, three of the four largest computer makers in
Massachusetts _ Wang Laboratories Inc., Data General Corp. and
Prime Computer Inc. _ announced quarterly losses.
   Prime's troubles have made it a takeover target, and two other
Massachusetts high-tech companies _ Cullinet Software Inc. and
Apollo Computer Inc. _ already have been sold this year. Another
former high flyer, Leading Edge Products Inc., is in bankruptcy.
   All told, high technology manufacturing companies in
Massachusetts have eliminated 7,300 jobs in the past year and
36,100 since their peak in December 1984, the state Department of
Employment and Training says.
   Underlying Route 128's woes are the maturing of the computer
industry, the slowdown in the national economy and the stiff
competition that minicomputer makers face from workstations and
ever more powerful personal computers.
   But those trends do not entirely explain why some Massachusetts
computer firms are still prospering, or why Route 128's West Coast
counterpart, California's Silicon Valley, is generally healthy.
   The substance of Route 128's problem, critics charge, is style:
Boston-area executives in their button-down shirts and brown shoes
are more cautious and slow-moving than their California rivals in
polo shirts and Reeboks.
   ``In Northern California companies, the hierarchy seems
compressed,'' said Hager. ``An account executive in Sunnyvale might
be reporting directly to the president, the CEO or the founder. In
Cambridge, that person will speak to the communications manager,
who works for the VP of you-name-it, who reports to the executive
VP, who whispers to the Main Force.''
   In part, Hager said, the different management styles reflect
cultural or lifestyle differences. In part, they are a matter of
age.
   ``The high-tech superstructure on the West Coast is run and
managed by people in their 30s, and the people who run the
high-tech companies on the East Coast are mainly in their 50s and
60s,'' he said. ``People in their 20s and 30s have no fear _ of
anything.''
   Stephen L. Josselyn, a computer market analyst with
International Data Corp. in Framingham, agrees that decision-making
is slower and product cycles longer along Route 128. ``It's just
harder to get people to move on the East Coast,'' he said.
   Examples abound:
   _Wang, which pioneered the market for word processors, lost
ground when it failed to move quickly into personal computers. It
is now making a big push into document imaging products, but it
announced a $375 million quarterly loss Monday. Some analysts say
the family-controlled company may have to find a substantial
outside investor.
   _Digital Equipment Corp., the state's largest computer maker,
also stuck with proprietary operating systems and failed to
capitalize on the PC explosion. Now it is moving into ``open,'' or
non-proprietary, software. But Digital's earnings have slipped this
year, and it has frozen salaries.
   _Data General also is moving away from proprietary systems
toward open software and reduced instruction set computing _ or
``risc'' _ technology, which simplifies the circuitry of a computer
and allows cost savings. In a two-year restructuring, it has cut
its work force from 16,000 to 14,000, and posted a $23.1 million
loss for the quarter ended June 24.
   Data General spokesman Michael F. Klatman calls the critic's
charges ``baloney.''
   ``From the time management made the decision to commit to open
systems, it took us just nine months to get our first products out
the door,'' he said. ``That's something you never would have seen
in this industry 10 years ago.''
   Klatman and others point out that aside from sales of PCs and
workstations, the entire U.S. computer market is slow.
   Minicomputer makers have been hit particularly hard, squeezed
between mini-supercomputers on the high end and technical
workstations on the low end, said Douglas J. Crook, an analyst with
Dataquest Inc. in San Jose, Calif.
   ``It just so happens, it's an accident of nature, that there are
more minicomputer makers based in Massachusetts, and the
traditional minicomputer is not growing at the rate of other
areas,'' said Klatman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0313EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Princeton-Newport     08-02 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Princeton-Newport,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Begins Deliberations On Forfeiture</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Princeton-Newport-RICO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury that convicted five former officials of
Princeton-Newport Partners LP and a former Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. trader of racketeering charges now must decide how much money
they will have to forfeit to the government.
   The jurors began deliberations on the forfeiture issue Tuesday
after hearing arguments from both sides.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Hansen said the defendants should
relinquish salaries and other claims that could total more than $21
million.
   Defense attorneys, who have said they will appeal the
conviction, argued that the forfeiture sought by the government was
excessive and violated the constitutional ban on cruel and unusual
punishment.
   On Monday, the Manhattan federal court jury convicted the
defendants of racketeering, racketeering conspiracy, conspiracy and
numerous counts of mail and wire fraud.
   The case marked the first time securities professionals were
accused of racketeering under a controversial federal law aimed at
combating mobsters and drug pushers. The Racketeer Influenced and
Corrupt Organizations law provides for heavy fines and lengthy
prison terms, in addition to forfeiture.
   The trial received widespread attention because it grew
indirectly out of the Ivan Boesky insider trading scandal that
rocked Wall Street three years ago.
   The largest forfeiture was sought from former Princeton-Newport
partner James Sutton Regan. His partnership interest was placed at
$13.3 million and his salary at $1.75 million.
   From former Drexel trader Bruce Lee Newberg, the government
sought $2.5 million in salary.
   The prosecution asked the jury to require forfeiture for the
other Princeton-Newport defendants as follows: former partner
Charles M. Zarzecki, $1.1 million partnership interest and $267,483
in salary; former partner Jack Z. Rabinowitz, $791,191 partnership
interest and $454,507 in salary; former partner Paul A. Berkman,
$762,613 partnership interest and $558,328 in salary; and former
controller Steven B. Smotrich, $124,583 in salary.
   ``Here's a man who has no money and the government wants him to
forfeit millions and millions of dollars,'' said Regan's attorney,
Theodore Wells. ``I submit to you that is cruel and unusual
punishment.''
   But Hansen told the jury that the racketeering statute permitted
the forfeiture of all interest from an illegal enterprise.
   ``As they chased the almighty dollar, they crossed far past the
line of law,'' Hansen said. ``You must decide whether the
defendants should be stripped of some of their tainted wealth.''
   The case involved a series of pre-arranged stock transactions
from 1984 to 1986. The government alleged during the five-week
trial that the defendants illegally bought and sold stocks to
generate phony tax losses.
   Princeton-Newport went out of business after the indictment was
brought last August. Defense lawyers said at the time that the
charges alone, though unproven, destroyed the securities firm's
ability to do business.
   Besides forfeiture, the defendants face up to 20 years in prison
on each of the two racketeering counts, jail terms ranging from
five to three years for the other charges and fines. A sentencing
date has not been scheduled.
   Before the lawyers presented their arguments to the jury, U.S.
District Judge Robert Carter ruled that the prosecution could not
tell the jury about a $650 million fine Drexel paid to settle
securities law charges in another case, which also stemmed from the
Boesky scandal.
   Defense attorneys had argued that telling jurors about the fine
would prejudice them on the forfeiture question.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
