<DOCNO> AP890802-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0751EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FamilyLeave     08-02 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Leave,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Pushes for Passage of Unpaid Leave</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Release at 10 a.m. EDT; time set by source. A version moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. families are losing at least $607 million
a year because the government hasn't passed legislation
guaranteeing workers unpaid leave to care for young children or
sick parents, a group backing such a law said today.
   ``Year after year, American families are the big losers because
Congress has failed to pass minimum family and medical leave
policies,'' Donna Lenhoff of the Women's Legal Defense Fund said in
prepared remarks. ``Working parents should not have to choose
between having a job and having a family.''
   Legislation is awaiting debate on both the House and Senate
floors that would require employers to provide up to 10 weeks of
unpaid leave over a two-year period to meet family needs during the
birth or adoption of a child and for family medical emergencies.
   ``Unnecessary Losses,'' the report for the Family and Medical
Leave Act Coalition, was based on a 1988 survey of 7,000 families
conducted by the Institute for Social Research at the University of
Michigan.
   The institute compiles data on a broad range of topics annually
and it is then used by researchers who break out and interpret
areas of particular interest to them.
   The analysis said the $607 million in family losses ``represents
the additional earnings lost by new mothers who return to work, but
are unable to return to their former jobs because their employers
don't have parental leave policies in place.''
   ``When these new mothers without job-protected leaves return to
work but are unable to return to their former jobs, they experience
more unemployment and lower wages than those mothers who return
after a period of protected leave,'' the report said.
   Moreover, the report said, taxpayers spend $108 million a year
on government assistance programs that wouldn't be necessary if
there was a nationwide family and medical leave program.
   ``Working mothers without job-protected leave receive $108
million more in assistance from such programs as unemployment
insurance, supplemental security income and welfare than do mothers
working for employers with parental leave policies,'' the report
said.
   ``As Congress prepares to leave for their summer break, we
wanted to remind our nation's lawmakers that American families are
suffering unnecessary losses due to their inaction on family
policies,'' Lenhoff said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
