<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 0823EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern Bjt   08-02 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Airlines Boosts Schedule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines has boosted its daily flights to
350 as part of a plan to emerge from a crippling strike as a leaner
carrier, but unionized pilots say the only thing that has increased
is the danger level.
   The expansion, which began on Tuesday, represents an increase of
nearly 60 percent over last month's schedule. Eastern is now back
to about a third of its pre-strike size.
   ``It's another major step back from the impact of the strike and
the bankruptcy and a very significant phase in the rebuilding of
the airline,'' said Eastern spokesman Robin Matell.
   But union officials called the schedule expansion an unsafe rush
to return with inexperienced flight crews.
   The Air Line Pilots Association issued a statement saying, ``If
you get past all of the hype and all of the slogans, there is a
level of risk to the flying public never before experienced in the
history of American commercial aviation.''
   ALPA said 75 percent of Eastern's flight crews are unfamiliar
with the type of aircraft they are flying and that Eastern is
violating federal standards by pairing inexperienced pilots.
   ``We are in complete and total compliance with all Federal
Aviation Administration rules,'' Eastern's Matell countered. ``Our
training and procedures are guided by conservatism is all
respects.''
   Matell added the unions have repeatedly used ``safety scares and
smear tactics'' in an effort to hurt Eastern.
   FAA spokesman Jack Barker said Eastern ``is meeting the
recommendation. If there is anything to the contrary, we would like
to know about it.''
   Eastern said the inreased flights went off smoothly, except for
one New York-to-Montreal flight canceled because a catering truck
damaged a plane.
   Also, some passengers in the Atlanta hub, where many of the new
flights were added, complained about long delays.
   ``This is my first time on Eastern in two years _ first and
last,'' said passenger David Parker, who complained that his flight
from Charlotte, N.C. arrived about an hour late. ``My travel agent
talked me into this for the $39 fare.''
   To entice more passengers Eastern offered temporary one-way
fares as low as $39. It also was required to lease several planes
from its sister carrier, Continental Airlines.
   Unable to maintain its pre-strike schedule of nearly 1,100 daily
flights when the strike began March 4, Eastern filed for Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection five days later.
   Last month, the company filed a reorganization plan calling for
Eastern to emerge from bankruptcy by year's end at two-thirds its
previous size. The airline's unions back an alternative buyout
proposal by Chicago commodities trader Joseph Ritchie.
   Eastern said it plans to increase its daily flights to 390 by
Aug. 15. Its goal is 800 daily flights from 77 cities, down from
102 cities before the strike.
   Eastern and Continental are owned by Texas Air Corp. The unions
contend Texas Air wants either to liquidate Eastern or merge it
with predominantly non-union Continental.
</TEXT>
