<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Plessey     08-02 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Plessey,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>GEC and Siemens Reach Agreement With Government Over Plessey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. PLC and Siemens AG reached an
agreement with the British government on conditions for resuming
their joint bid for Plessey Co. PLC, the government said Wednesday.
   The British and German electronics giants have pledged to remedy
public interest questions identified by the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission, the Department of Trade and Industry said in a brief
statement.
   The department in April said GEC and Siemens could renew their
bid for Plessey, also a British electronics company, on the
recommendation of the monopolies commission.
   But the clearance was conditioned upon the companies negotiating
with the department and the Ministry of Defense to ensure there is
no reduction in competition in the British defense electronics
industry.
   Details of the agreement weren't immediately available. But a
department spokesman said there were ``no differences of
substance'' between the measures agreed to by GEC and Siemens and
the recommendations made in the commission's April report.
   Among the commission's chief objections to the original
structure of the Plessey takeover was an accompanying plan for GEC
to acquire a 35 percent stake in Siemens' defense interests. The
commission said it opposed such a stake on the ground it would give
GEC an interest in the Plessey radar and military communications
interests to be acquired by Siemens.
   The original GEC-Siemens offer made earlier this year, valuing
Plessey at $2.8 billion, automatically lapsed when the monopolies
commission launched its inquiry in January.
   A spokesman for GEC refused to say whether the two companies
would renew their bid. ``We are considering with our partners'' on
the next step, said the spokesman, who wasn't identified, in
accordance with British custom.
   Under British takeover regulations, GEC and Siemens have 21 days
in which to re-introduce their bid.
   A Plessey spokesman couldn't be reached for comment.
   GEC is not related to the similarly named American company.
</TEXT>
