<FIRST>d f BC-Japan-CommunistTrade     08-02 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Communist Trade,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company President Formally Charged in Sales to East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of a machinery company has been
formally charged with selling East Germany restricted semiconductor
equipment and rare materials that could be used in nuclear reactor
rods, officials said Wednesday.
   Hirokuni Matsuda, president of Prometron Technics Corp., was
charged with violating Japan's trade and foreign exchange control
and custom laws by allegedly selling the items without government
approval, said an official of the Tokyo Metropolitan police, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The official declined to discuss further details and prosecutors
were not immediately available for comment.
   Police arrested Matsuda last month for allegedly supplying East
Germany in 1986 and 1987 with more than 20 pounds of hafnium, a
rare material that can be used in nuclear reactor rods.
   Hafnium is on a list of items restricted by the Coordinating
Committee on Multilateral Export Control, or COCOM, a Paris-based
organization that regulates Western trade in strategic items with
the Communist bloc.
   Matsuda also was accused of exporting to East Germany restricted
semiconductor manufacturing equipment valued at $875,000 via South
Korea and China in 1987. That equipment is also on the COCOM list.
</TEXT>
