<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Narrowly Mixed Amid Indictment Jitters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid
jitters over the expected announcement of commodity fraud
indictments.
   ``Everybody's feeling depressed waiting for this afternoon to
see if their name is going to be on the list,'' said John Frazier,
an executive vice president of the futures brokerage Balfour
Maclaine Corp.
   Attorney General Richard Thornburgh, FBI Director William
Sessions and Commodity Futures Trading Commmission Chairman Wendy
Gramm were scheduled to join U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas at a
late-afternoon news conference in Chicago to announce indictments
stemming from a 2{-year undercover investigation of suspected
trading fraud at the Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Frazier said traders feared the government would label some of
the Chicago trading pits as ``criminal enterprises'' in order to
seek racketeering convictions against traders.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent lower to { cent higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.88 a bushel; corn was
\ cent lower to } cent higher with September at $2.22\ a bushel;
oats were 1 cent to 1{ cents higher with Septmber at $1.34 a
bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 1{ cents higher with August
at $6.15 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mixed
in early trading on the Chicago Merc.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .30 cent higher with August at
72.72 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent lower to .15 cent
higher with August at 83.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .25 cent
lower to .25 cent higher with August at 45.75 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .25 cent lower to .40 cent higher with August at
25.22 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Tuesday with pork
bellies down sharply.
