<DOCNO> AP890802-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1222EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Avon-Jacobs     08-02 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Avon-Jacobs,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avon Receives Takeover Proposal From Investor Jacobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc. today said investor Irwin L.
Jacobs, who holds a stake in Avon stock, has proposed a possible
acquisition of the cosmetics company for $41 a share, or nearly $3
billion.
   Avon said it received a letter from Jacobs late Tuesday
requesting a meeting to negotiate the deal.
   James E. Preston, Avon's chairman and chief executive officer,
said Jacobs' letter would be discussed at the board's regular
meeting on Thursday. In a brief statement, Preston said he has sent
a letter to Jacobs informing him that the Avon board repeatedly has
said the company is not for sale.
   Earlier this year, the Avon board rejected a $39-a-share
takeover offer from rival direct selling company Amway Corp. and
indicated at the time that it would resist future acquisition
attempts. Amway withdrew its bid of about $2.1 billion but
continues to hold roughly 10.3 percent of Avon's common stock
outstanding in a partnership with Jacobs.
   The A-J Partnership, as the alliance of Amway and Jacobs is
called, did not act jointly in making the initial bid for Avon nor
are they acting together now.
   Jacobs said in a telephone interview today that Amway was not
participating in his offer for Avon in any way.
   If Jacobs prevails in his takeover attempt, he said, he plans to
sell Avon's retail division, which consists of some the country's
best-selling perfumes sold at department store counters, including
Giorgio Beverly Hills and Red.
   The direct selling operations of New York-based Avon in the
United States and abroad would be retained, Jacobs said.
   He said he has no intention of selling any piece of Avon to
Amway or to Mary Kay Corp., the parent of direct seller Mary Kay
Cosmetics Inc., which also has previously expressed interest in
Avon.
   Jacobs, who runs his investment operations from Minneapolis,
also said he has submitted a filing to the Securities and Exchange
Commission in which he said he has hired an investment banking
division of Citicorp to arrange financing for the all-cash bid.
   He said he has not had any contact with Avon executives except a
telephone call to acknowledge receipt of his letter.
   Jacobs' $41-a-share offer for Avon is worth about $2.25 billion
based on 54.91 million shares of common stock outstanding. Jacobs
also said in the SEC filing that he contemplates redeeming Avon's
preferred shares, which would cost $33.50 per share, or a total of
about $603 million.
   Avon also has about $1 billion in debt that would be part of any
acquisition.
</TEXT>
