<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BoeingTalks 1stLd-Writethru f0017 08-02 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0017,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing and Largest Union Begin Contract Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with three grafs to UPDATE with talks beginning. Picks
up 4th graf pvs, Aerospace industry ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co., halfway through another record year,
today opened contract talks with union leaders who say they want a
wage hike this time instead of the productivity bonuses of the past
six years.
   Negotiations began in Wichita, Kan., between Boeing and three
districts of the Machinists union, which represent 57,800 workers
in Seattle, Portland, Ore., and Wichita.
   Representing the union are District 751 president Tom Baker of
Seattle, Ron Eldridge of Wichita's District 70 and George Miller of
Portland's District 24.
   Aerospace industry analysts say the union is in a strong
position to exact a favorable settlement because of a $67 billion
backlog of commercial airplane orders, $346 million in profits in
the first half of 1989 and a shortage of skilled workers that
forced Boeing to borrow Lockheed Corp. workers earlier this year.
   Union officials say they want an hourly wage increase, likely to
be in the double-digits, to replace once-a-year productivity
bonuses Boeing has given the past six years.
   Boeing customers have been irritated by deliver delays for
747-400 model jets. With 44 due for delivery in the last quarter, a
work stoppage would jeopardize Boeing's reputation for reliability.
   The company borrowed about 600 Lockheed workers earlier this
year as it rescheduled delivery dates for the 747-400, and union
officials say those workers should be leaving Boeing this month.
   ``I think they will get a wage increase ... I don't think push
is going to come to shove here,'' said Gary Reich, aerospace
analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   The chance of a strike is small, say analysts, who believe
Boeing workers know they are better off riding the crest of record
airplane orders than sitting out the good times on a picket line.
   ``I would not anticipate a prolonged labor disruption or
strike,'' said William Deatherage, aerospace analyst at Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. in New York.
   ``Not many people at Boeing are not aware of the cyclical nature
of the business. This is the opportunity of a lifetime (for
workers) to get all the overtime they can,'' he said.
   Other union contract requests will cover overtime rules, an
improved cost-of-living index, better pension payments, on-site
education programs and child care, union officers said. Wages will
be the last item discussed.
   Boeing, led by chief negotiator Larry McKean, vice president of
human resources, has until Aug. 9 to make its first
counterproposal, with further negotiations scheduled as needed.
   The union's current three-year contract expires Oct. 3.
   Before departing for Wichita on Monday, Baker said the union
would ask for a ``significant'' wage increase, adding he did not
consider a single-digit increase significant.
   Except for welders, the people who make Boeing planes currently
earn $8.88 to $18.42 per hour depending on pay level and seniority.
The average wage is $13.50 to $14 an hour.
   ``All the signals are that it looks good for us. Boeing can well
afford to pay an increase in wages and increase benefits,'' Baker
said.
   ``Our relations have in general been very good with the union,''
said Boeing spokesman Paul Binder. He declined to comment on the
negotiations.
   Union officials want a wage increase to replace, either
completely or partially, the bonuses that have ranged from 3
percent to 12 percent a year since 1983.
   Analysts said a reasonable increase would not affect Boeing's
profitability, especially if it can pass part of the increase on to
customers. Boeing also adjusts its prices as labor and commodity
indexes rise.
   ``Customers may have to take a bite in the next three years'' if
a wage hike is granted, said Steve Binder, senior aerospace analyst
with Bear Stearns &amp; Co. Inc. in New York. He is not related to
Boeing's Paul Binder.
   Frank Shrontz, chairman and chief executive officer, has said
that Boeing's goal is to hold down costs to improve profit margins
and increase shareholders' return on equity.
   The union's bargaining position represents a complete turnaround
from its position during the 1983 and 1986 negotiations. In 1983,
about 12,000 Boeing workers had been laid off because of the
industry slump, weakening the union's hand at the bargaining table.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-HomeShopping-GTE     08-02 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Home Shopping-GTE,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>GTW Wins $100 Million Libel Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury awarded $100 million in libel
damages today to GTE Corp. after rejecting Home Shopping Network's
claim that the communications company was to blame for lost sales.
   HSN contended GTE didn't give it adequate equipment to handle a
large volume of calls in 1986 and 1987 as the network expanded into
11 new markets. GTE won the case on its counterclaim.
   The six-member jury reached its verdict after about five hours
of deliberations in the complicated case following a six-week trial
before Pinellas Circuit Judge Howard Rives.
   The award was to be split evenly by GTE Florida and GTE
Communciations. In a breakdown of each award, the jury said $10
million should by paid by HSN, $20 million by board Chairman Roy
Speer and $20 million by President Lowell Paxon.
   In final arguments Monday, HSN attorneys said GTE told ``little
white lies'' to the network to cover up the communications
company's failure to provide for the volume of calls.
   On Tuesday, GTE lawyer Roy Reardon responded that a Dec. 2,
1986, letter placed in evidence documented that HSN thought the
telephone firm had been ``responsive to all our previous needs''
and was looking forward ``to continuing this highly successful
relationship.''
   Ten months after that, HSN sued, claiming it lost millions of
calls and about $500 million in potential sales because its GTE
telephone network equipment was insufficient for the volume of
calls. The parent company, based in Stamford, Conn., the Florida
subsidiary and GTE Communications were named as defendants.
   In response, GTE filed a slander and libel counterclaim placing
blame for HSN's decline in the electronics market and stock market
on its own mismanagement there.
   HSN's 1986 purchase of 11 UHF stations in new markets, combined
with its entrance into the cable television market, caused
subscribers to soar from 9 million to 46.5 million in one year,
GTE's Reardon said.
   GTE knew about the cable arrangements, he added. Cable companies
were offered a $1 million stock option which enhanced their
interest in HSN, he said, and 70 cable outlets were obtained.
   But, even when HSN made its initial public offering of stock on
May 13, 1986, the company didn't mention its plans to purchase the
broadcast stations as a second operational network, Reardon argued.
   He recalled that HSN operations vice president William DeLany
warned in September 1986 the company didn't have enough personnel
to handle the growing number of calls, but Speer ``didn't want to
hear they needed more operators.''
   Competition from similar retailers also has hurt HSN, Reardon
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890802-0272 </DOCNO>
