<HEAD>London Shares End Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shares ended sharply higher Wednesday following a
strong rally on Wall Street during the London afternoon.
   A lack of selling pressure and strong rallies in the retaili and
pharmaceutical sectors also combined to push the market higher.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share ended up 15.5
points, or 0.7 percent, at 2,307.8, the session high. At its
lowest, the index touched 2,285.8, a fall of 6.5 points.
   Share prices opened lower but rallied on news of an agreement by
General Electric Co. PLC and Siemens AG with the British government
under which the British and West German electronics giants may
resume their joint bid for Plessey Co. PLC., a British electronics
company.
   Dealers said trading volume wilted during the afternoon, as the
market tracked movements on Wall Street.
   ``It was a pretty volatile day but it seemed the market wanted
to rally after its declines earlier in the week,'' one trader said.
   Volume was 424.8 million shares, compared with 413.5 million
shares Tuesday.
