<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-02 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices were mostly higher but corn
and soybeans lower Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, where
the expected commodity fraud indictments may have sent some traders
to the sidelines early.
   While wheat thrived in the wake of a 100,000-ton buy late
Tuesday by China and rumors of a second buy, equally large
purchases of soybeans established a contract low for the seventh
time in eight days.
   Volume was lighter than usual at the exchange's soybean pit,
rumored to be one of four pits at the BOT and the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange where undercover federal agents concentrated
their investigative efforts during the 2{-year probe.
   ``It probably kept people away,'' one trader who asked not to be
identified said of indictments, which were announced after the
markets closed. ``But how much effect it actually had is debatable.
A lot of this is already in the market.
   ``And besides,'' the trader added, ``bearish weather is killing
the beans _ not indictments.''
   On the close, wheat was 1 cent lower to 1{ cents higher, with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.89 a bushel; corn was
1{ cents lower to 1} cents higher, with September at $2.21\ a
bushel; oats were unchanged to { cent higher, with September at
$1.33 a bushel; and soybeans were 7 cents lower to 1 cent higher,
with August at $6.13 a bushel.
</TEXT>
