<FIRST>r f AM-HelmsleyAds     08-02 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helmsley Ads,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ad Agency Drops Helmsley Hotel Account</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Version on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advertising agency said Wednesday it had
dropped the Helmsley Hotels' $5 million-a-year account, saying
proprietor Leona Helmsley intruded too much and recently cut agency
fees by 60 percent.
   Mrs. Helmsley, who has been on trial in a tax evasion case in
U.S. District Court, has been depicted in the advertising as the
``queen'' standing on guard making sure everything is perfect at
the hotels.
   The ad agency Taylor-Gordon, Aarons &amp; Co. Inc. had handled the
Helmsley account for the past three years. Agency president Elaine
Taylor-Gordon said her company stands to lose $500,000 a year from
its decision.
   ``All of us knew she was queen and we were there to serve her,''
Taylor-Gordon said. ``It was evident in her body language, her
imperiousness and her arrogance.''
   She described a typical business meeting with Mrs. Helmsley:
``She was drinking martinis, and I was drinking Brioschi. There was
a lot of tension ... She told me, `Don't get comfortable. You're
not here for a social event.'''
   Agency officials said she sealed her fate with Taylor-Gordon,
Aarons when she imposed an arbitrary 60 percent cut in agency fees
for May and June.
   They said Mrs. Helmsley was informed of the decision in a letter
sent to her home. Mrs. Helmsley was approached by reporters at the
courthouse about the agency's decision, but she said nothing.
   Taylor-Gordon, Aarons was not the first agency to use Mrs.
Helmsley in ads for the hotel chain, or to dub her the ``queen.''
   The approach was apparently effective: occupancy jumped from 24
percent before the ads to 87 percent afterwards, agency officials
said.
</TEXT>
