<FIRST>u f AM-AutoPrices     08-02 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Prices,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Air Bags Increase Ford Prices for 1990</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co.'s 1990 models will cost about 4.8
percent more than 1989 models, partly because of new federal
requirements on air-bag protection for passengers, a preliminary
price list indicates.
   The increase showed up in a Ford advisory recently sent to
dealers for use in taking early orders for fall, company spokesman
Dave Krupp said Wednesday.
   ``About half of that is for air bags,'' Krupp said of the price
boost.
   Ford will announce final prices for the 1990 models in
mid-September, two to three weeks in advance of the Oct. 5 debut of
new vehicles, he said.
   General Motors Corp. and Chrysler Corp. officials remained
silent Wednesday on their pricing plans for the new model year.
   GM will announce prices later this month in preparation for a
late September introduction of the new models, spokesman Terry
Sullivan said.
   Chrysler will announce prices in late September or early October
and introduce its 1990 models in early October, spokeswoman Karen
Stewart said.
   Neither GM nor Chrysler has sent preliminary prices to dealers,
the two said. Analysts have predicted automakers would trim
production in anticipation of slow 1989 sales continuing into next
year, consequently raising prices.
   GM and Chrysler have estimated air bags will add $500 to the
price of a new car, and Ford has estimated that cost at between
$350 and $700.
</TEXT>
