<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-02 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Heads Mostly Higher in U.S.; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained against most major foreign
currencies in subdued U.S. dealings Wednesday after weakening on
markets abroad.
   Gold prices posted minor changes. On the Commodity Exchange in
New York, gold for August delivery closed at $370.10 a troy ounce,
down 70 cents from Tuesday's settlement. The Republic National Bank
quoted bullion at $369.70 an ounce as of 4 p.m. in New York, 80
cents lower than Tuesday's late bid.
   Despite closing near its highest levels of the day in New York,
currency dealers said the dollar lacked direction and a bearish
undercurrent lingered in the market due to the likelihood of
additional U.S. interest rate declines.
   The value of a country's currency typically is eroded by
reductions in the country's interest rates.
   Simon Fischer, of Bear, Stearns &amp; Co., attributed part of the
buying to reactions to Tuesday's selloff and maneuvers in
anticipation of reports expected to shed more light on the
condition of the U.S. economy.
   The Commerce Department's June report on the Index of Leading
Economic Indicators is scheduled for Thursday release and on Friday
the Labor Department is due to issue June unemployment figures.
   The market was preoccupied with developments in the Middle East
regarding Western hostages. Reports of American warships moving
positions raised speculation about possible military action in the
Middle East following the reported execution of Marine Lt. Col.
William Higgins.
   Earlier, in currency trading in foreign financial centers, the
dollar ended generally lower.
   Dealers in Europe reported trading seemed trendless, with the
number of participants operating in the market down due to summer
holidays. They said the dollar was unlikely to make any major moves
ahead of the U.S. economic reports.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.45 yen to close at 136.20 yen. Later
in London, the dollar traded at 136.05 yen. But, in New York the
dollar closed at 136.60 yen, up from 135.80 yen on Tuesday.
   The British pound traded at $1.6635 late in London, up from
Tuesday's $1.6550. Later, in New York, sterling stood at $1.6560
compared to $1.6648 on Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday's rates, included: 1.8575 West German marks, up from
1.8505; 1.5970 Swiss francs, up from 1.5895; 1.17515 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1747; 6.29 French francs, up from 6.266; and
1,334.50 Italian lire, up from 1,330.05.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with late rates
Tuesday, included: 1.8505 West German marks, down from 1.8660;
1.5915 Swiss francs, down from 1.6075; 6.2695 French francs, down
from 6.3135; 2.0895 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1060; 1,332.00
Italian lire, down from 1,342.50; and 1.1755 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1743.
   Gold prices ended with modest to no change.
   Gold was bid at $368.25 a troy ounce late Wednesday in London,
unchanged from late Tuesday. Trading was suspended Wednesday in
Zurich for a national holiday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose 6 cents an ounce to close at
$371.32.
   Silver traded at $5.27 a troy ounce in London, up from $5.23
late Tuesday. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery fell to $5.225 a troy ounce from Tuesday's settlement of
$5.252.
