<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-02 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices closed mixed Wednesday
with crude oil bouncing back from earlier lows despite ongoing
concern about excess oil supplies.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the September contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, rose 25
cents to finish at $18.28 a barrel after falling 28 cents on
Tuesday. The contract had dipped to $17.78 a barrel during the
trading session.
   Contracts for later delivery were mixed.
   Among refined oil products traded on the exchange, unleaded
gasoline for September delivery fell 0.58 cent to 50.85 cents a
gallon, while future contracts were mixed.
   Domestic heating oil for September rose 0.34 cent to 49.54 cents
a gallon and other contract months were mostly higher.
   The market opened lower mainly on a report showing that oil and
gasoline inventories are continuing to rise.
   The American Petroleum Institute said supplies of crude oil,
gasoline and heating oil increased in the week ended July 28. The
API report was released after the close of trading on Tuesday.
   Crude oil inventories rose 882,000 barrels to 331.4 million
barrels from the previous week, while gasoline stocks increased by
4.6 million barrels to 225.96 million and heating oil rose by 2.1
million to 111.5 million barrels, the report said.
   On a yearly basis, however, crude oil stocks were down 16.9
million barrels from the same time last year and heating oil was
off 6.8 million barrels. Gasoline inventories, however, were 16.3
million barrels higher.
   Later in the day, traders said oil prices recovered, partly on
technical factors.
   ``The momentum just wasn't there to move lower,'' said Richard
Redoglio, energy broker for Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   Analysts said nervousness about the U.S. hostage situation in
the Middle East also helped boost prices. Traders have attributed
some price strength in recent days to investor concern that
political events involving U.S. hostages could disrupt oil
shipments from the Middle East.
</TEXT>
