<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 1830EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-02 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocoa Futures Soar on News of Big Export Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa futures snapped a slump and surged Wednesday on rumors
that the Ivory Coast, the world's largest producer, had sold
500,000 tons to a major trading house.
   On other markets, sugar continued rallying in the face of
growing demand and the fear of weak yields from Western Eurpoean
crops; soybeans fell to a new low for the seventh time in eight
days, depressed by wet weather and stuck there because many traders
halted trading early to await indictments stemming for a 2{-year
investigation into commodities trading fraud.
   Cocoa, traded on the New York Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange,
jumped at the opening bell after rumors surfaced that Ivory Coast
President Felix Houphet-Boigny, who had been in France in recent
days, helped seal a huge export deal with trading company Philipp
Brothers Inc.
   The rumored deal suggested a heightened demand for cocoa, which
has languished recently. The size of such a purchase, if confirmed,
would also raise the possibility of short-term supply problems.
   ``As sleepy as the market had been, a lot of traders thought the
market was at its technical bottom and as soon as it got a boost
from the Ivory Coast report, there were a lot of people jumping on
the bandwagon,'' said Pete Henig, who tracks commodities for Refco
Inc., New York.
   Cocoa climbed $66 to $70 per ton higher, with the contract for
delivery in September at $1,327 a ton.
   Sugar continued gaining because demand is outpacing supply.
Early reports that a virus has cut substantially into crop yields
in West Germany and France helped bolster prices.
   Sugar climbed .22 cent to .31 cent higher, with October at 14.43
cents a pound.
   Nervousness over commodity fraud indictments, announced after
the close of business Wednesday, had sent some traders to the
sidelines early at the Chicago Board of Trade. Wheat futures prices
closed higher, but corn and soybeans were mostly lower.
   Wheat thrived in the wake of a 100,000-ton buy late Tuesday by
the Chinese, and there were rumors they planned a second, equally
large purchase.
   But November soybeans slipped 7 cents, establishing a contract
low for the seventh time in eight days.
   The indictments ``probably kept people away,'' said one trader
who asked not to be identified. ``But how much effect it actually
had is debatable. A lot of this is already in the market.
   ``And besides,'' the trader added, ``bearish weather is killing
the beans _ not indictments.''
   Wheat was unchanged to 2} cents higher, with the contract for
delivery in September at $3.90\ a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to
1{ cents higher, with September at $2.21{ a bushel; oats were \
cent to { cent higher, with September at $1.33\ a bushel; and
soybeans were 1{ cents to 8{ cents lower, with August at $6.08\ a
bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were sharply higher at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle climbed .35 cent to 1.20 cents, with August at 73.55
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent to .60 cent higher, with
August at 83.62 cents pound; live hogs were .23 cent to 1.23 cents
higher, with August at 46.35 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies
were .35 cent to 1.10 cents higher, with August at 25.92 cents a
pound.
   Precious metals were off slightly, with silver leading the
decline.
   At the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold settled 79 cents to
$1.50 lower, with August at $370.10 a troy ounce; silver was 2.7
cents to 3 cents lower, with August at 522.5 cents a troy ounce.
Platinum, traded at the New York Mercantile Exchange, was off $1.50
to $1.60, with September at $500.10 a troy ounce.
   Petroleum futures were mixed at the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Crude oil was 9 cents lower to 25 cents higher, with September
at $18.28 a barrel; heating oil was .17 cent lower to .34 cent
higher, with September at 49.54 cents a gallon; and unleaded
gasoline was .58 cent lower to .35 cent higher, with Septmeber at
50.85 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
