<FIRST>r f AM-FarmExports     08-02 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Exports,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shipments of Horticulture Products Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fruit juice exports to Japan and Korea helped
boost overseas shipments of fruits, nuts, vegetables, hops and
other horticultural products in May, the Agriculture Department
reported Wednesday.
   Shipments to points other than Canada were valued at $252
million in May, up 3 percent from April and 4 percent from May
1988, the department's foreign agricultural service reported.
   Juice imports to Korea increased 18 times from last year to $2.1
million in May. Frozen vegetables increased from zero a year ago to
$270,000 in May.
   Shipments to East Asia accounted for 64 percent of fruit juices
exports, with Japan receiving the bulk.
   Canada remained the premier market, however, for horticultural
products. Imports rose nearly 11 percent from 1987 to reach a value
of $1.5 billion, 60 percent of total horticultural imports for
Canada.
</TEXT>
