<FIRST>u f AM-WorldStocks     08-02 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Stocks,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>World's Stock Markets Reach Record Levels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Wall Street's rally resumed Wednesday, major
stock market indexes set records in Paris, Brussels, Milan,
Amsterdam and Stockholm.
   The American stock exchanges are not the only ones that have
rebounded from the world stock market crash of Oct. 19 and 20,
1987. In fact, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks trails
other major indexes in its recovery.
   Stock prices rose Wednesday in Tokyo, the world's biggest stock
market, but remained below the record high set in Monday's session.
The Tokyo market was the first to climb back above the highs
reached in 1987.
   London shares remained below their 1987 peaks but set a
post-crash high, influenced by the rally on Wall Street and rallies
in retailing and pharmaceutical stocks. The Financial Times-Stock
Exchange 100 index rose to 2,307.8.
   In Paris, share prices recovered from their early weakness to
close slightly higher in thin trading. The CAC index of French
shares reached a record high of 505.9.
   In West Germany, foreign buying of blue-chip stocks kept a rally
going on the Frankfurt exchange. Daimler-Benz, maker of Mercedes
cars, was again the strongest performer. The exchange's Dax index
entered record territory during the session but slipped back.
   In Belgium, the Brussels stock market index set a record
6,208.77, rising in harmony with other European exchanges.
   In the Netherlands, stock prices were mixed but there were
enough gainers to push the Amsterdam main market index to a record
for a third consecutive session. The CBS general shares index hit
201.6.
   In Sweden, the bull run in Stockholm continued with an 18th
record in 20 sessions. Forestry shares led the way. The
Affaersvaerlden index closed at 1,317.2.
   Italy's news of a resurgence of inflation failed to hurt the
Milan stock market, where the main index jumped to a record 1,153.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
ended up 0.88 points at 34,899. It surpassed 35,000 for the first
time at the end of morning trading but then retreated.
   So far this year the U.S. stock market has risen 23.5 percent;
the British stock market is up 27 percent; the Japanese market is
up 9.6 percent; and the West German market is up 19.3 percent, when
measured in local currencies, according to statistics compiled by
Morgan Stanley Capital International Perspective, a Geneva-based
subsidiary of the U.S. investment banking firm.
   In the very long term, Tokyo's stock prices are up nearly 1,600
percent since 1969, while American prices are up a relatively
meager 320 percent.
</TEXT>
