<FIRST>u f AM-Time-Contempt     08-02 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time-Contempt,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warner Attorney Ordered to Delaware Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney who admitted she mistakenly
gave confidential court documents to a reporter during the Time
Inc. takeover fight has been ordered to appear before the Delaware
Supreme Court.
   Barbara Robbins of the New York-based law firm Wachtell, Lipton,
Rosen &amp; Katz has been ordered to court Aug. 22 to show why she
should not be held in contempt.
   Robbins was on vacation Wednesday and could not be reached for
comment.
   Law partner Michael Schwartz called the incident ``inadvertant
and not blameworthy.''
   The law firm represented Warner Communications Inc., which had
an agreement to be acquired by Time. Paramount Communications Inc.,
attempting a hostile takeover of Time, was appealing a Chancery
Court ruling that refused to block the merger.
   The documents had been submitted by Paramount in its appeal. The
court had ordered the documents be kept confidential after a
request from Time because they contained estimates of the dollar
value of Time's core businesses, including the value of People,
Sports Illustrated, Time and Fortune magazines.
   The estimates appeared July 26 in an article in The New York
Times.
   A spokesperson for Warner, who did not want to be identified,
called it an ``honest mistake.''
   ``We know that there was no intention on her part to violate the
court order and we're convinced it was an honest mistake,'' the
spokesperson said.
   Robbins admitted to the court last Thursday that she supplied
the documents to a Times reporter, unaware the documents were
confidential.
   In a letter to state Supreme Court administrator Stephen D.
Taylor, Robbins said the documents were not stamped ``Confidential
Under Seal'' on the cover.
   ``As I am sure you can imagine, as Warner's counsel I certainly
would have had no desire to release to the public documents as to
which Time sought confidential treatment. Indeed, in (Chancery
Court), Warner joined with Time in seeking confidentiality with
respect to certain documents,'' Robbins wrote.
   ``It is an unfortunate outcome of a document not being stamped
confidential which Paramount should have stamped confidential,''
Schwartz said.
</TEXT>
