<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Grandmother     08-02 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Grandmother,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grandmother Angry About $3,720 Lost on Eastern Tickets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys are haggling over millions of dollars
in the Eastern Airlines' strike-bankruptcy case, but all Beatrice
Lovinger wants is the $3,720 she spent on now-useless Eastern
tickets for her family.
   ``I'm a grandmother,'' Ms. Lovinger, 57, told a public meeting
of Eastern creditors Wednesday. ``It's pretty horrible that big
business can do this to me ... and I can be out this amount of
money. I'm overwrought about it.''
   Ms. Lovinger, who lives in New York, says she purchased 13
tickets for her children and grandchildren in January so they could
fly from New York to Miami for a family gathering in mid-April.
   Eastern's three unions struck March 4, grounding the Miami-based
carrier and forcing it to seek the refuge of Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection.
   Ms. Lovinger joined the thousands of other hapless ticketholders
caught by the strike, hoping a federal bankruptcy court in
Manhattan will make sure Eastern compensates them.
   Continental Airlines, Eastern's sister carrier, has been
honoring Eastern tickets, but Ms. Lovinger said Continental offered
only to put her and relatives on standby status. She wants her
money back or guaranteed seats.
   ``I need the tickets the way I bought them,' she told about 60
Eastern attorneys, creditors, shareholders and employees at Madison
Square Garden's Felt Forum in midtown Manhattan.
   On July 21, Eastern filed a proposed reorganization plan, which
it said would provide for full repayment of the $3.3 billion owed
to all creditors including ticketholders.
   Under the plan, people like Ms. Lovinger could exchange their
tickets for cash with interest or more valuable tickets on the
post-bankruptcy Eastern. But the plan must receive approval by the
bankruptcy court and other creditors first, so Ms. Lovinger could
be in for a long wait.
   ``This example is symptomatic of a problem we see coming up,''
James Flug, an attorney for Consumers Union, said of the
grandmother's case. Flug, who also attended the Eastern meeting,
said Consumers Union has heard of dozens of similar cases.
   Consumers Union, the non-profit consumer advocacy group that
publishes Consumer Reports magazine, has asked the court to require
Eastern to reimburse passengers before the company pays off other
creditors.
</TEXT>
