<FIRST>u f AM-HomeShopping-GTE 1stLd-Writethru f0239 08-02 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Shopping-GTE, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0239,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Awards GTE $100 Million in Damages After Rejecting HSN Claims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs to CORRECT spelling of Paxson; PICKS UP 6th
graf pvs, `Home Shopping...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Wednesday rejected Home Shopping
Network's $1.5 billion lawsuit charging GTE Corp. with providing
faulty telephone equipment and instead awarded $100 million to two
GTE subsidiaries for libel and slander.
   The cable television retailer claimed it lost millions of calls
and $500 million in potential sales in 1986 and early 1987 because
GTE telephone equipment it contracted for could not handle the
volume of calls.
   But after a six-week trial at Pinellas County Court, the jury
rejected charges of fraud, negligent misrepresentation, breach of
trust and confidence, and breach of fiduciary duty against the
telecommunications giant.
   Instead it awarded GTE Florida and GTE Communications $50
million each for damages to their reputation and credibility by
Home Shopping Network and its two top executives on charges in a
countersuit by Stamford, Conn.-based GTE.
   HSN was cited for $20 million of the total award with $40
million each against HSN Chairman Roy Speer and President Lowell
Paxson.
   Home Shopping immediately said it would appeal the decisions.
   The jury of four women and two men deliberated for about five
hours over two days.
   ``We are very disappointed with the jury's verdict and we will
appeal the decision immediately,'' said Nando DiFilippo, HSN's
executive vice president and general counsel.
   He said the network would maintain that the court should not
have presented GTE's libel and slander counterclaim to the jury.
   James V. Carideo, GTE Florida vice president and general
counsel, said the verdict reassures ``the integrity of the
companies,'' which the HSN suit ``had put at issue.''
   Home Shopping merchandise may be bought by home viewers only
while the item is being displayed on the screen. The network said
it lost 42 million calls when as much as 50 percent of its incoming
calls never got through to waiting sales operators because of the
allegedlt faulty equipment.
   HSN filed its suit in Septmeber 1987. GTE denied any wrongdoing,
contending there was nothing wrong with its equipment and it had
not misled Home Shopping.
   GTE's countersuit maintained that the electronic retailer blamed
the phone company for financial problems actually caused by
mismanagement. The company argued that over-expansion, competition
and customer dissatisfaction rather than ineffective equipment
triggered HSN losses.
   In one year, the number of Home Shopping subscribers soared from
9 million to 46.5 million, GTE attorney Roy Reardon said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
