<DOCNO> AP890802-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 2144EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-RJR     08-02 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-RJR,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>RJR Holdings Posts Loss in 2nd Qtr, Operating Income Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Holdings Corp., which acquired RJR Nabisco
Inc. for a record $24.5 billion in April, said Wednesday it lost
$309 million in the second quarter because of costs associated with
the buyout.
   But the company, which is 92.3 percent owned by the buyout firm
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co., said strong performances by its food
and tobacco businesses helped boost its operating income by 24
percent.
   ``We are pleased with the progress we have made in meeting our
objectives for reducing debt,'' said Louis V. Gerstner Jr.,
chairman and chief executive.
   The company has reached agreements to sell about $2.6 billion in
assets, mostly from the sale of five European food companies,
toward its goal of $5.5 billion in asset sales.
   ``At the same time, our core businesses are exceeding
expectations for earnings and cash flow,'' Gerstner said.
   The loss for the three months ended June 30 compared with a
profit of $354 million, or $1.50 a share, at RJR Nabisco a year
earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 4 percent to $3.91 billion from
$3.75 billion.
   But operating income before amortization charges rose to $848
million from $683 million a year earlier. Operatings income from
tobacco rose 16 percent while it was up 40 percent from food
operations.
   For the first six months, the new company lost $518 million in
contrast to a profit of $627 million, or $2.59 a share, a year
earlier at RJR Nabisco.
   Six-month revenue rose to $7.44 billion from $7.04 billion a
year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
