<FILEID>AP-NR-08-02-89 2209EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditesProbe-Scene     08-02 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodites Probe-Scene,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Commodities Probe, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Exchanges Move To Bolster Confidence Following Indictments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at the world's two largest commodities
exchanges moved quickly Wednesday to bolster public confidence
after a federal grand jury indicted 46 traders on charges of making
illegal trades.
   But ordinary traders at bars near the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange and Chicago Board of Trade in the downtown LaSalle Street
financial district took a more low-key view of the indictments.
   Several traders refused to comment on the indictments, while
others expressed mixed opinions about the federal probe that
resulted in charges ranging from tax fraud to racketeering. Those
traders willing to comment refused to identify themselves.
   ``If they're dirty, then they deserve it,'' one trader shouted
over his shoulder as he walked out of The Trade Inn across from the
Board of Trade building.
   But other traders questioned the validity of the indictments,
which resulted from a 2{-year undercover FBI investigation at the
two exchanges. The charges involve such violations as pre-arranged
trading, altering trading records and withholding customer orders
from the market in order to dole them out to compatriots.
   From the indictments emerge a picture of several dozen traders,
none of whom are considered especially influential, who allegedly
conspired to skim profits from customers' accounts and hide the
profits from the Internal Revenue Service.
   Some traders at the Limit Up Bar in the Mercantile Exchange
building portrayed several of those indicted as basically honest
brokers who were not smart enough to cheat.
   ``There are things that look real dishonest that are done for
the good of the customers,'' said one trader, who has been a member
of the Mercantile Exchange for 10 years. He refused to elaborate on
what practices he meant.
   The trader said he thought the federal investigation has focused
so far on traders who had done little wrong.
   ``They're taking honest people and turning them into crooks,''
said the trader. ``If they're looking for something bigger, that's
fine, great.''
   The trader and two colleagues sitting at the bar denied ever
breaking exchange rules and defended the record of most traders.
   ``That's very good if all they can find is 24 bad apples'' out
of the 2,724 seats on the Mercantile exchange, he said.
   The government announced indictments of 22 traders at the Board
of Trade and 24 at the Merc. The exchanges were not accused of
wrongdoing and neither were any of the scores of brokerage firms
whose customers were allegedly cheated.
   Officials at both exchanges said those traders under indictment
would be barred from trading except for their own personal accounts.
   When asked about the number of indictments, CBOT Chairman
Karsten Mahlmann told a news conference that ``one was too many''
and vowed to protect the integrity of the exchange.
   Mahlmann said the CBOT had launched its own investigation of
traders before reports about the FBI probe surfaced in January, but
was asked by federal authorities to hold off while the government
investigation continued.
   CBOT President Thomas Donovan said the exchange has since moved
to improve its computer surveillance system so that it will be able
to audit all transactions within one business day and stiffen its
maximum fines for violations from $75,000 to $250,000.
   Donovan said the board would conduct its own investigation into
the practices of the indicted traders and revoke the trading
privileges of anyone who pleads guilty or is convicted on charges
stemming from the probe.
   ``Without integrity being a major part of the way we do
business, we cannot exist,'' Donovan told the news conference.
   At the Merc, Leo Melamed, chairman of the executive committee,
and John T. Geldermann, chairman of the board of governors, issued
a statement promising to deal ``severely'' with any member found
guilty of the federal charges.
   They said the Merc had commissioned a special committee to
review all trading practices.
</TEXT>
