<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-TBS     08-02 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-TBS,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>TBS Reports Profit Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ted Turner on Wednesday credited his new
all-movie cable channel, Turner Network Television, with boosting
Turner Broadcasting System Inc.'s revenues and profit in the second
quarter.
   Atlanta-based TBS reported net income of $5.5 million for the
quarter ended June 30, compared with a loss of $25.9 million for
the same quarter a year earlier.
   However, it reported a net loss per common share of 12 cents in
this year's second quarter due to the payment of dividends and the
accumulation of discount on its Class B preferred stock.
   Quarterly revenues were up 33 percent, to $264.5 million from
$199.3 million.
   For the six months ended June 30, net income was $5.1 million,
or a loss of 37 cents a share after an extraordinary item, compared
with a loss of $40 million for the same period in 1988. Revenues
were $496.5 million, up 30 percent from revenues of $381.9 million
for the same period a year earlier.
   ``The addition of TNT to our already successful lineup of basic
cable networks has lifted our quarterly operating profit to an
all-time high,'' said Turner, chairman of TBS.
   ``We are particularly pleased that our improved performance is
the result of contributions from all four basic cable networks,
confirming our belief that each network remains attractive to
advertisers and viewers alike,'' he said.
   In addition to TNT, TBS owns Cable News Network, CNN Headline
News and Superstation WTBS. The company also owns professional
baseball's Atlanta Braves and professional basketball's Atlanta
Hawks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
